1
00:00:14,514 --> 00:00:18,485
-We'd like to begin with good news today.
-Already?

2
00:00:18,551 --> 00:00:20,687
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>

3
00:00:20,754 --> 00:00:25,592
was a part of the survey for
the 2026 Brand Customer Loyalty Awards,

4
00:00:25,658 --> 00:00:26,960
and we took first place.

5
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:28,261
FOR PROGRAMS (COOKING VARIETY SHOW)

6
00:00:28,328 --> 00:00:31,664
We were chosen as
the most influential cooking variety show.

7
00:00:31,731 --> 00:00:32,565
First place.

8
00:00:32,632 --> 00:00:33,733
WE ALL DID IT TOGETHER

9
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:35,869
-Congratulations.
-We owe it to the production crew.

10
00:00:35,935 --> 00:00:37,537
-We didn't do much.
-It's the crew.

11
00:00:37,604 --> 00:00:39,472
We got everything handed to us
on a silver platter.

12
00:00:40,006 --> 00:00:42,709
THANK YOU, DEAR VIEWERS

13
00:00:42,776 --> 00:00:45,812
-We have something else to brag about.
-There's a lot today.

14
00:00:45,879 --> 00:00:49,883
K-Brand Index analyzed
over 300 million data points

15
00:00:49,949 --> 00:00:52,519
-and found the top expert entertainer as…
-Expert entertainer.

16
00:00:52,585 --> 00:00:53,686
Don't get excited.

17
00:00:53,753 --> 00:00:55,021
-Is it me?
-It's not you.

18
00:00:55,088 --> 00:00:56,489
First place

19
00:00:56,556 --> 00:00:57,924
was Son Jong-won.

20
00:00:57,991 --> 00:00:58,858
1ST PLACE, SON JONG-WON

21
00:00:59,125 --> 00:01:00,794
CONGRATS

22
00:01:01,027 --> 00:01:02,695
BLUSH
1ST PLACE, SON JONG-WON

23
00:01:02,762 --> 00:01:05,832
-He's a broom, sweeping all the awards.
-Yes, he's sweeping everything up.

24
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:06,833
Lucky him.

25
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:10,370
I thought I'd always live
a quiet life in the kitchen,

26
00:01:10,437 --> 00:01:14,140
but thanks to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,
I even became first place in these awards.

27
00:01:14,207 --> 00:01:15,241
THANK YOU, EVERYONE

28
00:01:15,308 --> 00:01:18,178
We've unearthed a shiny gem.

29
00:01:18,244 --> 00:01:19,412
Good one, <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

30
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:21,114
We brought him up too.

31
00:01:21,181 --> 00:01:24,784
He started out as a tiny pearl.
We raised him into who he is today.

32
00:01:24,851 --> 00:01:26,019
It's more like

33
00:01:26,086 --> 00:01:27,720
-we farmed him.
-Yes, farming.

34
00:01:27,954 --> 00:01:30,557
FARMED THE PEARL SUCCESSFULLY

35
00:01:30,623 --> 00:01:32,459
Jong-won isn't the only one
within the top ten.

36
00:01:32,525 --> 00:01:33,359
No?

37
00:01:33,426 --> 00:01:34,394
IT'S NOW MY TURN

38
00:01:34,461 --> 00:01:36,062
Fifth place, Choi Kang-rok.

39
00:01:36,129 --> 00:01:36,996
5TH PLACE, CHOI KANG-ROK

40
00:01:37,063 --> 00:01:38,331
He doesn't even do much.

41
00:01:38,398 --> 00:01:40,166
Six place, Kim Poong.

42
00:01:40,233 --> 00:01:41,734
-What?
-Hey, Poong!

43
00:01:41,801 --> 00:01:44,104
-I can't believe it.
-<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> owned it.

44
00:01:44,170 --> 00:01:45,839
-"Expert"?
-Expert.

45
00:01:45,905 --> 00:01:47,474
-Expert?
-I'm an expert too?

46
00:01:47,540 --> 00:01:49,042
An expert of what, though?

47
00:01:49,109 --> 00:01:50,210
Seventh place, Choi Hyun-suk.

48
00:01:50,276 --> 00:01:53,246
YOU RANKED 7TH

49
00:01:53,580 --> 00:01:55,181
WHY IS HE SO HAPPY?

50
00:01:55,248 --> 00:01:56,649
-Poong won.
-Poong won against you.

51
00:01:56,716 --> 00:01:58,885
-You can do it too.
-Hyun-suk took seventh place.

52
00:01:58,952 --> 00:02:00,620
Eighth place, Kwon Sung-jun.

53
00:02:00,687 --> 00:02:03,423
CONGRATULATIONS, SUNG-JUN GOT CHOSEN

54
00:02:04,557 --> 00:02:05,458
Eighth place?

55
00:02:05,525 --> 00:02:08,461
-I could've done better.
-Five of our members are in the top ten.

56
00:02:09,863 --> 00:02:11,598
I'm very proud of you all.

57
00:02:11,664 --> 00:02:13,500
I think I could've done
better than eighth.

58
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,001
YOU COULD'VE DONE BETTER?

59
00:02:15,068 --> 00:02:16,836
No one ever calls me by my name.

60
00:02:16,903 --> 00:02:18,271
When I look up my name, I look for

61
00:02:18,338 --> 00:02:21,441
Matpizza, Pizza, Matdori,
Matdasi, Matstar, and whatnot.

62
00:02:21,508 --> 00:02:23,676
I have so many nicknames,

63
00:02:23,743 --> 00:02:25,111
so it's hard to look up everything.

64
00:02:25,178 --> 00:02:27,247
Do you think
you should've been in the top three?

65
00:02:27,313 --> 00:02:28,548
Not probably the top three,

66
00:02:28,615 --> 00:02:29,849
but maybe around 6.5.

67
00:02:29,916 --> 00:02:31,050
MOVE ASIDE, HYUN-SUK!

68
00:02:31,117 --> 00:02:33,019
-Hyun-suk should be eighth…
-Better than him.

69
00:02:33,086 --> 00:02:35,622
-…and Sung-jun was supposed to be here.
-Yes.

70
00:02:35,688 --> 00:02:37,457
I see.

71
00:02:37,524 --> 00:02:40,160
People don't just call me
Choi Hyun-suk either.

72
00:02:40,226 --> 00:02:41,094
Chef Choi.

73
00:02:41,161 --> 00:02:42,028
Show-off.

74
00:02:42,095 --> 00:02:44,063
Chef Grandpa. I have nicknames too.

75
00:02:44,130 --> 00:02:45,899
-You're right.
-You're right.

76
00:02:45,965 --> 00:02:47,033
I've seen Tank Boy too.

77
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:48,501
-Tank Boy?
-Tank Boy.

78
00:02:48,568 --> 00:02:50,770
The 11th place was Tank Boy.

79
00:02:50,837 --> 00:02:52,305
Chef Postwar.

80
00:02:52,372 --> 00:02:53,773
A NEW NICKNAME

81
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:55,742
Even my mom told me,

82
00:02:55,808 --> 00:02:58,378
"Hey, there were other pictures
where you look well-off."

83
00:03:00,079 --> 00:03:01,381
You gave it to us.

84
00:03:01,447 --> 00:03:03,249
MADE HIMSELF THE TANK BOY

85
00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:05,618
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>

86
00:03:05,685 --> 00:03:08,755
and our cast are beloved by the nation.

87
00:03:08,821 --> 00:03:09,789
Today,

88
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:12,992
the two who are called
the nation's sons-in-law

89
00:03:13,059 --> 00:03:14,894
have visited us.

90
00:03:14,961 --> 00:03:17,931
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

91
00:03:17,997 --> 00:03:19,132
Come on out!

92
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:21,901
Today's fridge owners.

93
00:03:22,869 --> 00:03:24,304
Today's guests!

94
00:03:24,370 --> 00:03:25,905
The men who live with the queens!

95
00:03:25,972 --> 00:03:29,375
Please welcome Ko Woo-rim and Kangnam!

96
00:03:29,442 --> 00:03:31,578
He looks a lot like Chef Jong-won.

97
00:03:32,178 --> 00:03:34,681
THESE TWO LOOK ALIKE

98
00:03:34,747 --> 00:03:35,949
My old dudes!

99
00:03:36,816 --> 00:03:38,117
-My old dudes!
-Take a seat.

100
00:03:38,184 --> 00:03:40,086
SAYING HI TO THE OLD DUDES

101
00:03:40,153 --> 00:03:41,287
My old dudes.

102
00:03:41,354 --> 00:03:43,356
These old dudes are the same!

103
00:03:43,923 --> 00:03:44,757
WHOA, WHOA

104
00:03:44,824 --> 00:03:46,492
Those old dudes are the same too!

105
00:03:46,559 --> 00:03:48,595
-Man. You're all alive.
-Take a seat.

106
00:03:48,661 --> 00:03:50,230
You've aged too.

107
00:03:50,296 --> 00:03:52,899
But all of you are so old
that I don't look as old.

108
00:03:53,299 --> 00:03:54,801
RUDE FROM THE START

109
00:03:54,867 --> 00:03:56,636
The men who live with the queens.

110
00:03:56,703 --> 00:03:59,038
I see. Instead of
"the man who lives with the King."

111
00:03:59,105 --> 00:04:00,139
Let me introduce them.

112
00:04:00,573 --> 00:04:01,741
FIRST, THIS GUEST

113
00:04:01,808 --> 00:04:04,811
<i>The man who captured Kim Yuna's heart</i>
<i>with his deep, resonant voice.</i>

114
00:04:04,877 --> 00:04:06,913
FORESTELLA'S TREASURED
DEEP, RESONANT VOICE

115
00:04:07,747 --> 00:04:09,382
<i>The romantic younger husband</i>

116
00:04:09,449 --> 00:04:10,717
<i>And a member of Forestella</i>

117
00:04:10,783 --> 00:04:11,718
SECONDHAND EMBARRASSMENT

118
00:04:11,784 --> 00:04:14,287
-Please welcome Ko Woo-rim!
-Welcome!

119
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:16,823
Hello.

120
00:04:16,889 --> 00:04:19,025
I'm the bass of Forestella, Ko Woo-rim.

121
00:04:19,092 --> 00:04:20,159
It's great to be here.

122
00:04:20,526 --> 00:04:21,361
UNRIVALED DEEP VOICE

123
00:04:21,427 --> 00:04:22,762
-What a great voice.
-He's different.

124
00:04:23,463 --> 00:04:24,464
Thank you.

125
00:04:24,530 --> 00:04:26,666
-It's nice to see you.
-It is. Let me introduce this man.

126
00:04:26,733 --> 00:04:30,136
<i>The only man who can evoke the rage</i>
<i>of Lee Sang-hwa, the Empress on Ice.</i>

127
00:04:30,203 --> 00:04:31,037
THE COUPLE'S KISS

128
00:04:32,238 --> 00:04:34,507
Please welcome,
the romantic troublemaker, Kangnam!

129
00:04:34,574 --> 00:04:36,409
Hello. It's nice to be here.

130
00:04:36,476 --> 00:04:37,543
WHOO

131
00:04:37,610 --> 00:04:38,911
You haven't aged a day.

132
00:04:38,978 --> 00:04:40,346
-I haven't, right?
-No.

133
00:04:40,413 --> 00:04:42,515
-I've been trying to lose weight.
-I see.

134
00:04:42,582 --> 00:04:45,518
Kangnam returned to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>
after a very long time.

135
00:04:45,585 --> 00:04:48,021
The show has been going since 2014, right?

136
00:04:48,087 --> 00:04:49,555
He was here as a guest

137
00:04:49,622 --> 00:04:51,157
-for our third episode.
-Wow.

138
00:04:51,224 --> 00:04:53,593
THE GUEST OF EPISODE 3

139
00:04:53,660 --> 00:04:54,861
Wow, the third episode.

140
00:04:54,927 --> 00:04:57,797
I didn't expect this show
to last this long.

141
00:04:58,731 --> 00:05:00,933
-He was on episode two.
-Episode two.

142
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,135
Yes, I remember.

143
00:05:02,201 --> 00:05:04,103
I didn't even know
what the show was about.

144
00:05:04,871 --> 00:05:07,073
But now I'm here hosting it.

145
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:09,876
-Back then, they were all nervous too.
-Right.

146
00:05:09,942 --> 00:05:10,843
WE WERE

147
00:05:10,910 --> 00:05:12,211
Do you remember?

148
00:05:12,278 --> 00:05:14,013
Hyun-suk deep-fried something.

149
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:16,082
-The fire?
-But then it suddenly caught on fire.

150
00:05:16,149 --> 00:05:17,417
He was like, "What do I do?"

151
00:05:17,483 --> 00:05:18,584
STOP IT!

152
00:05:18,651 --> 00:05:19,686
SIT DOWN

153
00:05:20,119 --> 00:05:21,487
FLUSTERED

154
00:05:21,554 --> 00:05:23,489
Shouldn't we deduct some points?

155
00:05:24,590 --> 00:05:26,459
You were all flushed,
so it was really funny.

156
00:05:26,526 --> 00:05:28,895
His face was as red as this can.

157
00:05:28,961 --> 00:05:31,764
I feel like
I have Kim Poong on both sides today.

158
00:05:31,831 --> 00:05:32,832
It does feel like that.

159
00:05:32,899 --> 00:05:34,600
-Like the old days.
-Yes, the old days.

160
00:05:34,667 --> 00:05:36,536
Kim Poong and Kang Poong.

161
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:38,604
-I remember the old days.
-I'm already feeling tired.

162
00:05:38,671 --> 00:05:41,708
-This is Woo-rim's first time on the show.
-That's right.

163
00:05:41,774 --> 00:05:45,712
I've been enjoying it a lot,
as well as my wife.

164
00:05:45,778 --> 00:05:48,114
She was really thrilled
that I was invited,

165
00:05:48,181 --> 00:05:50,616
and she told me
to become friends with the chefs.

166
00:05:51,884 --> 00:05:54,153
-Of course.
-She said that to me.

167
00:05:54,220 --> 00:05:56,956
Do you two have a favorite chef?

168
00:05:57,023 --> 00:05:58,291
Actually, our favorite is

169
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:00,693
Chef Nam-no.

170
00:06:00,760 --> 00:06:02,362
…Chef Nam-no.

171
00:06:02,428 --> 00:06:04,063
-Hey, what?
-Good for you, Nam-no.

172
00:06:04,130 --> 00:06:06,232
-It's Nam-no again.
-He almost spat out

173
00:06:06,299 --> 00:06:07,900
-his beverage.
-He was having a sip.

174
00:06:07,967 --> 00:06:10,837
-What's going on with my position lately?
-Nam-no.

175
00:06:10,903 --> 00:06:12,605
I'm not used to this.

176
00:06:12,672 --> 00:06:14,507
-You're their favorite.
-He's so popular.

177
00:06:14,574 --> 00:06:15,708
I need to hold him in check.

178
00:06:15,775 --> 00:06:20,313
My wife said she'd love to visit
Chef Nam-no's restaurant if she could.

179
00:06:20,380 --> 00:06:23,850
Also, he seems like someone
who knows a lot about good food.

180
00:06:23,916 --> 00:06:25,651
We're so curious about him.

181
00:06:25,718 --> 00:06:28,554
He has the look of someone
who can stir once and make good food.

182
00:06:28,621 --> 00:06:30,690
There are chefs you can trust
just by their looks.

183
00:06:30,757 --> 00:06:33,025
They don't even do much,

184
00:06:33,092 --> 00:06:35,361
but you can tell that
they'll whip up something good.

185
00:06:35,428 --> 00:06:37,730
-That's so true.
-So he's your favorite chef.

186
00:06:37,797 --> 00:06:39,532
Woo-rim's fans said

187
00:06:39,599 --> 00:06:43,536
he has a similar look to Chef Jong-won.

188
00:06:43,603 --> 00:06:46,072
-They look alike.
-Yes, I can see it too.

189
00:06:46,139 --> 00:06:48,975
-There have a similar vibe.
-A kind-hearted vibe.

190
00:06:49,041 --> 00:06:50,042
They're the same kind.

191
00:06:50,109 --> 00:06:53,146
-They're both dazzling.
-Looking back and forth, I see it.

192
00:06:53,212 --> 00:06:54,480
A CONVINCING TWO-SHOT

193
00:06:54,547 --> 00:06:56,149
They parted their hair the same way too.

194
00:06:56,215 --> 00:06:58,384
They have kind eyes
that are slanted downward,

195
00:06:58,451 --> 00:07:00,553
but the brows are both slanted up.

196
00:07:00,620 --> 00:07:02,088
-You're right.
-Right? That's it.

197
00:07:02,655 --> 00:07:04,724
-I hope you don't mind.
-Goodness, no.

198
00:07:04,791 --> 00:07:06,826
If it's okay with him, I'm fine with it.

199
00:07:06,893 --> 00:07:08,661
-That soft tofu look.
-Soft like tofu.

200
00:07:08,895 --> 00:07:10,096
LOOKS CAREFULLY

201
00:07:10,163 --> 00:07:13,833
-You have a tofu dregs look.
-…they're both pale and clean-cut…

202
00:07:13,900 --> 00:07:16,269
-Practically a black soybean look.
-Some even say they have

203
00:07:16,335 --> 00:07:19,772
-the wholesome, in-law-approved look.
-Yes, you could say that.

204
00:07:19,839 --> 00:07:20,840
The parent-approved looks.

205
00:07:20,907 --> 00:07:23,309
There's one person here
who has married a child off.

206
00:07:23,376 --> 00:07:25,578
The nation's father-in-law, Chef Hyun-suk.

207
00:07:25,645 --> 00:07:28,047
Please talk to us
from the father-in-law's perspective.

208
00:07:28,114 --> 00:07:30,183
Do they have the in-law-approved looks?

209
00:07:30,249 --> 00:07:31,317
Here are the basics.

210
00:07:31,384 --> 00:07:32,218
FATHER-IN-LAW MODE

211
00:07:32,285 --> 00:07:33,953
From the father-in-law's perspective,

212
00:07:34,020 --> 00:07:36,656
there are no guys
who will be automatically approved by us.

213
00:07:36,722 --> 00:07:38,791
-Are you that heartbroken?
-You only go,

214
00:07:38,858 --> 00:07:40,460
"He might be good enough."

215
00:07:41,861 --> 00:07:45,131
Considering that,
what if someone like these two came

216
00:07:45,198 --> 00:07:46,199
-to meet you?
-Goodness.

217
00:07:46,265 --> 00:07:47,099
Automatically approved.

218
00:07:48,634 --> 00:07:49,836
FACES THAT MAKE THE IMPOSSIBLE POSSIBLE

219
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:52,905
They look like
they wouldn't break your daughter's heart.

220
00:07:52,972 --> 00:07:54,273
Forget the approved looks, then.

221
00:07:54,340 --> 00:07:57,243
-Why don't you pick out automatic rejects?
-Is there anyone like that?

222
00:07:57,310 --> 00:07:59,479
-Automatic rejection by the parents.
-Automatic rejects.

223
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:02,081
SCANNING SHARPLY

224
00:08:02,148 --> 00:08:04,283
-Hey, smile.
-He'll slam the door in your face.

225
00:08:04,350 --> 00:08:05,351
Rejected as a son-in-law.

226
00:08:05,418 --> 00:08:08,688
-I love all these chefs, but…
-It's definitely not me.

227
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:10,089
LOOKING AROUND AGAIN

228
00:08:10,156 --> 00:08:12,058
-It's you.
-No, it's not me.

229
00:08:12,124 --> 00:08:12,959
HA!

230
00:08:13,025 --> 00:08:14,360
It <i>is</i> you.

231
00:08:14,660 --> 00:08:15,695
YOU'RE LYING…

232
00:08:15,761 --> 00:08:18,064
Why? Sung-jun is a decent guy!

233
00:08:18,130 --> 00:08:19,665
-Why?
-Why?

234
00:08:19,732 --> 00:08:21,901
-Why?
-He's talented

235
00:08:21,968 --> 00:08:23,569
and he makes good money.

236
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:24,937
-I don't drink or smoke.
-Also…

237
00:08:25,004 --> 00:08:26,806
-Yes, he doesn't drink or smoke.
-He doesn't.

238
00:08:26,873 --> 00:08:28,674
So he does live a good life,

239
00:08:28,741 --> 00:08:30,376
but I feel that's only for him.

240
00:08:31,744 --> 00:08:32,578
Yes, right.

241
00:08:32,645 --> 00:08:33,579
NOT TRUE

242
00:08:34,213 --> 00:08:36,182
-He's a good judge of character.
-He's sharp.

243
00:08:36,249 --> 00:08:37,984
Sung-jun, it's your turn to explain.

244
00:08:38,484 --> 00:08:40,486
I believe I'm ideal husband material.

245
00:08:40,553 --> 00:08:42,021
HAHAHAHA

246
00:08:42,088 --> 00:08:43,990
First of all, I neither drink nor smoke.

247
00:08:44,056 --> 00:08:45,291
I don't play video games.

248
00:08:45,358 --> 00:08:46,259
I don't even have friends.

249
00:08:46,325 --> 00:08:47,593
I'm a homebody.

250
00:08:47,660 --> 00:08:49,462
That's the problem. You're always home.

251
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:50,863
I don't even own a car.

252
00:08:50,930 --> 00:08:52,431
-That's a problem.
-I don't live large.

253
00:08:52,498 --> 00:08:53,399
She'll have to walk.

254
00:08:53,466 --> 00:08:56,903
Actually, Woo-rim and Sung-jun
have something in common.

255
00:08:56,969 --> 00:08:59,171
-Wait, what?
-Wait.

256
00:08:59,238 --> 00:09:01,474
-I was surprised.
-Me too.

257
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:02,675
They're the same age.

258
00:09:02,742 --> 00:09:03,843
-What?
-Born in 1995.

259
00:09:03,910 --> 00:09:06,112
-What?
-You were born in 1995?

260
00:09:06,178 --> 00:09:07,046
They're the same age.

261
00:09:07,113 --> 00:09:08,848
-What?
-Born in 1995.

262
00:09:08,915 --> 00:09:09,982
-What?
-You were born in 1995?

263
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:11,484
What happened to you?

264
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:14,854
-We're the same age.
-They're the same age.

265
00:09:15,321 --> 00:09:16,155
STARE…

266
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:17,456
You must've lived so diligently.

267
00:09:17,790 --> 00:09:19,926
HE MUST'VE BEEN THROUGH
LOTS OF UPS AND DOWNS

268
00:09:19,992 --> 00:09:21,928
-He did.
-He went through a lot.

269
00:09:21,994 --> 00:09:23,563
I heard that

270
00:09:23,629 --> 00:09:25,464
you two are actually close in real life.

271
00:09:25,531 --> 00:09:26,699
-Yes.
-Is that so?

272
00:09:26,766 --> 00:09:28,634
My wife and Sang-hwa

273
00:09:28,701 --> 00:09:31,604
<i>had been good friends</i>
<i>since their days as athletes.</i>

274
00:09:31,671 --> 00:09:34,073
<i>So after both got married,</i>

275
00:09:34,140 --> 00:09:36,242
I always wanted
to meet the two of them together.

276
00:09:36,309 --> 00:09:39,245
Then one day, I met Kangnam
on another show, and immediately,

277
00:09:40,146 --> 00:09:41,213
we became friends.

278
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:45,318
-We suddenly shook hands and…
-We were like, "We finally met."

279
00:09:45,384 --> 00:09:47,687
I also live

280
00:09:47,753 --> 00:09:49,355
as an ex-athlete's husband, right?

281
00:09:49,855 --> 00:09:51,324
I said, "It must be tough."

282
00:09:51,390 --> 00:09:53,726
-And we shared our difficulties.
-Having commonalities.

283
00:09:53,793 --> 00:09:55,328
Are your homes always a bit cold?

284
00:09:55,394 --> 00:09:57,263
They both competed on ice,
so is it colder?

285
00:09:57,330 --> 00:09:59,565
Actually, she never turns
the boiler on even in the winter.

286
00:09:59,932 --> 00:10:01,000
SHOCKED AS A GUY WHO GETS COLD

287
00:10:01,067 --> 00:10:02,902
-She loves winter.
-Are you serious?

288
00:10:02,969 --> 00:10:05,271
So we shook hands
and became friends immediately.

289
00:10:05,338 --> 00:10:07,239
The four of you have get-togethers?

290
00:10:07,306 --> 00:10:09,742
We visited Kangnam at his home

291
00:10:09,809 --> 00:10:12,078
and he showed us around.

292
00:10:12,144 --> 00:10:16,182
Recently, we ate together in Japan
and spent some time together.

293
00:10:16,248 --> 00:10:17,950
You two should be
on different wavelengths.

294
00:10:18,017 --> 00:10:22,088
-I guess we do have different wavelengths.
-I'm sure.

295
00:10:22,154 --> 00:10:25,958
I think we're mostly calm.
That's our default state.

296
00:10:26,025 --> 00:10:27,360
We don't have many ups and downs.

297
00:10:27,426 --> 00:10:30,029
-I see.
-Those two get along really well.

298
00:10:30,096 --> 00:10:32,164
Their back-and-forths are so much in sync.

299
00:10:32,231 --> 00:10:34,567
When she says something,
he follows up immediately.

300
00:10:34,634 --> 00:10:37,336
So they're very beautiful,
like a pair of cats.

301
00:10:37,403 --> 00:10:38,304
But we're like…

302
00:10:38,771 --> 00:10:39,805
ROAR

303
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:41,574
ROAR!

304
00:10:42,108 --> 00:10:43,809
I say one thing and she goes, "Roar!"

305
00:10:43,876 --> 00:10:45,911
We're completely different.

306
00:10:45,978 --> 00:10:46,979
PLEASE LISTEN TO HER…

307
00:10:47,046 --> 00:10:49,315
So we're quite different from them.

308
00:10:49,382 --> 00:10:51,884
I heard you had
something to promote today.

309
00:10:51,951 --> 00:10:54,387
I do. My quartet, Forestella,

310
00:10:54,453 --> 00:10:58,357
<i>will return with a full album</i>
<i>after five long years.</i>

311
00:10:58,424 --> 00:11:01,193
<i>We also have a tour coming up as well.</i>

312
00:11:01,260 --> 00:11:05,398
-So I wanted to share that with you today.
-As you should.

313
00:11:05,464 --> 00:11:07,867
In your group,

314
00:11:07,933 --> 00:11:11,070
-you're in charge of the lowest range.
-The bass.

315
00:11:12,405 --> 00:11:15,541
HIS DEEP VOICE RESONATES IN YOUR HEART

316
00:11:15,608 --> 00:11:18,477
I sing the part called bass.

317
00:11:18,544 --> 00:11:19,679
Because my voice is so low,

318
00:11:19,745 --> 00:11:23,949
I believe it acts as a nice touch
like MSG to our songs.

319
00:11:24,016 --> 00:11:25,685
Do you have to intentionally go down low?

320
00:11:25,751 --> 00:11:27,219
-On purpose?
-There is intention.

321
00:11:27,787 --> 00:11:29,055
GROWL

322
00:11:29,121 --> 00:11:30,890
Something like that.

323
00:11:30,956 --> 00:11:32,358
-I see.
-Chef Eun-yeong.

324
00:11:32,425 --> 00:11:34,593
I've never had many chances

325
00:11:34,660 --> 00:11:36,595
to listen to such a low voice.

326
00:11:36,662 --> 00:11:38,764
-It's fascinating.
-Thank you.

327
00:11:38,831 --> 00:11:40,199
They all sound like chipmunks.

328
00:11:40,266 --> 00:11:41,167
Everyone here is like…

329
00:11:41,233 --> 00:11:43,069
-Chitter-chatter.
-Eek!

330
00:11:43,135 --> 00:11:44,670
-Squeak!
-Something like that.

331
00:11:44,737 --> 00:11:46,505
"Hello, I'm Kim Poong!"

332
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:49,675
What do you mean?

333
00:11:49,742 --> 00:11:51,277
We never talked like that!

334
00:11:51,911 --> 00:11:53,145
Isn't that true?

335
00:11:53,212 --> 00:11:54,146
BE QUIET!

336
00:11:54,213 --> 00:11:55,281
That's not a low voice.

337
00:11:55,347 --> 00:11:57,016
-Then how do you do it?
-You're right.

338
00:11:57,516 --> 00:11:59,785
THIS IS THE REAL LOW VOICE?

339
00:11:59,852 --> 00:12:02,088
-I got chills.
-It sounds awful.

340
00:12:03,022 --> 00:12:05,491
I got a tip from the production crew
about Chef Eun-yeong.

341
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:06,892
After hearing Woo-rim's voice,

342
00:12:06,959 --> 00:12:09,562
-she said, "He'd even raise ghosts."
-No, wait.

343
00:12:09,628 --> 00:12:11,697
-What do you mean?
-Is that a compliment?

344
00:12:11,764 --> 00:12:13,866
-"He'd even raise ghosts."
-Raise ghosts?

345
00:12:13,933 --> 00:12:15,634
-What do you mean by that?
-What is that?

346
00:12:15,701 --> 00:12:17,937
-If he wakes up his wife…
-What do you mean by that?

347
00:12:18,003 --> 00:12:19,371
…with that voice in the morning,

348
00:12:19,438 --> 00:12:22,975
I thought that kind of voice
could even raise ghosts from the dead.

349
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:24,110
THANK YOU, I GUESS

350
00:12:25,077 --> 00:12:27,012
-"Wake up."
-Woo-rim, can you try it?

351
00:12:27,079 --> 00:12:29,915
-It's the morning, and you got up first.
-You have to wake her.

352
00:12:29,982 --> 00:12:31,917
She usually wakes up first.

353
00:12:31,984 --> 00:12:32,818
Is that so?

354
00:12:33,753 --> 00:12:36,989
Honey, what would you like to eat today?

355
00:12:37,223 --> 00:12:38,124
SWEETNESS OVERLOAD

356
00:12:38,190 --> 00:12:39,325
-<i>Malatang</i>.
-He's like an actor.

357
00:12:39,391 --> 00:12:41,193
Sung-jun, how about pork belly?

358
00:12:41,260 --> 00:12:44,096
But when I'm home with my wife,

359
00:12:44,163 --> 00:12:47,133
I guess I get a little cuter,
so my tone gets higher too.

360
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:48,534
-So it changes.
-Yes.

361
00:12:48,601 --> 00:12:50,402
I just go, "What do you want to eat?"

362
00:12:50,469 --> 00:12:52,838
I sound much more mischievous.

363
00:12:52,905 --> 00:12:54,240
You sound a bit more nasally.

364
00:12:54,306 --> 00:12:55,374
"What do you want to eat?"

365
00:12:55,441 --> 00:12:58,344
-How do you wake your wife, Kangnam?
-Let's say you're up first.

366
00:12:58,410 --> 00:13:00,780
I have never once woken up before her.

367
00:13:00,846 --> 00:13:03,783
-Really?
-She wakes up between 4 and 5 a.m.

368
00:13:03,849 --> 00:13:05,985
That's the life of a former athlete.

369
00:13:06,051 --> 00:13:07,486
Then she doesn't even wake me

370
00:13:07,553 --> 00:13:08,621
and does the dishes first.

371
00:13:09,255 --> 00:13:11,891
She goes, "Wham! Bam! Bang! Clang! Slam!"

372
00:13:11,957 --> 00:13:13,959
-She must not be in a good mood.
-"Smack!"

373
00:13:14,326 --> 00:13:15,594
YOU STILL WON'T WAKE UP?!

374
00:13:15,661 --> 00:13:17,963
-So naturally, I wake up.
-She doesn't have to tell you.

375
00:13:18,030 --> 00:13:19,265
It means you should get up.

376
00:13:19,331 --> 00:13:21,000
If she ever is slumbering in the day,

377
00:13:21,066 --> 00:13:22,902
-"Slumber"?
-…and I make the tiniest sound

378
00:13:22,968 --> 00:13:25,004
trying to clean up the place,

379
00:13:25,070 --> 00:13:26,839
she says, "Kangnam, be quiet!"

380
00:13:26,906 --> 00:13:29,909
So I have to be quiet.
There are such rules.

381
00:13:29,975 --> 00:13:30,810
When I go downstairs…

382
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:34,780
Are you a thief?

383
00:13:34,847 --> 00:13:35,881
Quietly.

384
00:13:35,948 --> 00:13:37,817
I go even slower as the years go by.

385
00:13:37,883 --> 00:13:38,784
Like a ninja.

386
00:13:38,851 --> 00:13:41,120
-I must be more careful than a ninja.
-Wear some <i>beoseon</i>.

387
00:13:41,187 --> 00:13:43,022
Do you know what's shocking?

388
00:13:43,088 --> 00:13:45,424
Even our dogs are careful.

389
00:13:46,091 --> 00:13:47,593
YOU MUST NOT WAKE HER MAJESTY

390
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:49,395
When there's a sound,
Kangnam and the dogs go…

391
00:13:49,461 --> 00:13:51,864
THE IMPLIED CHALLENGE BETWEEN THE THREE

392
00:13:51,931 --> 00:13:53,432
-We look around.
-And at each other.

393
00:13:53,499 --> 00:13:54,533
You do live with the queen.

394
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:56,635
This is a true story.

395
00:13:57,203 --> 00:13:58,204
Just wait eight years.

396
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:02,041
Have you ever walked quietly in the house?

397
00:14:02,107 --> 00:14:04,510
-My wife is also a light sleeper.
-She's sensitive.

398
00:14:04,577 --> 00:14:06,078
I guess it's an athlete thing.

399
00:14:06,145 --> 00:14:07,413
When I have to leave first,

400
00:14:07,479 --> 00:14:10,382
I'd wake up
and rustle the sheets a little,

401
00:14:10,449 --> 00:14:12,418
which wakes her up immediately.

402
00:14:12,484 --> 00:14:15,287
-Is this an athlete thing?
-Maybe they had too much pressure.

403
00:14:15,354 --> 00:14:16,822
What about you? You were an athlete.

404
00:14:16,889 --> 00:14:17,756
I was sensitive too.

405
00:14:17,823 --> 00:14:20,860
Then how long did it take
for you to become so lazy?

406
00:14:20,926 --> 00:14:23,295
-Immediately after you retired?
-I let go immediately.

407
00:14:23,362 --> 00:14:25,631
-So you dropped everything on day one?
-On day one.

408
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:28,634
Sang-hwa is still sensitive,
even after eight years.

409
00:14:28,701 --> 00:14:30,636
<i>-She keeps her routine?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

410
00:14:30,703 --> 00:14:33,639
Woo-rim and Yuna have been married
for four years already.

411
00:14:33,706 --> 00:14:36,075
-Already?
-Yes, it's our fourth year.

412
00:14:36,141 --> 00:14:39,245
<i>They dated in secret for four years,</i>
<i>then were married for four.</i>

413
00:14:39,311 --> 00:14:41,180
-They dated for a while.
-Right?

414
00:14:41,247 --> 00:14:42,815
Didn't Sang-hwa know?

415
00:14:42,882 --> 00:14:44,817
Sang-hwa… Sang-hwa <i>nuna</i>…

416
00:14:44,884 --> 00:14:46,085
I mean, Sang-hwa

417
00:14:46,151 --> 00:14:48,787
already knew they were dating
and about their plans to marry.

418
00:14:48,854 --> 00:14:50,990
-But she never told me once.
-That's right.

419
00:14:51,590 --> 00:14:53,225
I asked, "Why didn't you tell me?"

420
00:14:53,292 --> 00:14:55,060
She said, "You'd tell everyone."

421
00:14:55,127 --> 00:14:57,763
Yes, this guy is like a loudspeaker.

422
00:14:57,830 --> 00:15:00,633
I found out about Yuna's marriage
when the articles broke out.

423
00:15:00,699 --> 00:15:03,969
-She couldn't tell you.
-She wanted to keep their secret.

424
00:15:04,036 --> 00:15:07,606
We're about to find out
what Woo-rim and Yuna eat

425
00:15:07,673 --> 00:15:10,943
as we present their fridge.

426
00:15:11,010 --> 00:15:14,380
Isn't this the first time
you're revealing your fridge?

427
00:15:14,446 --> 00:15:16,782
-It's absolutely the first time.
-Wow.

428
00:15:16,849 --> 00:15:19,551
-I never thought I'd see this day.
-I see.

429
00:15:19,618 --> 00:15:21,820
Did your wife say anything?

430
00:15:21,887 --> 00:15:25,257
She said, "I don't think we have much."

431
00:15:25,324 --> 00:15:27,893
She seemed a little self-conscious.

432
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:30,462
Also, we often get delivery food,

433
00:15:30,529 --> 00:15:33,399
but she now has a legal reason
to order more delivery food.

434
00:15:33,465 --> 00:15:34,667
That was something she said.

435
00:15:34,733 --> 00:15:36,468
-Has it been illegal until now?
-Is that so?

436
00:15:36,902 --> 00:15:38,671
YUNA'S LEGAL DELIVERY FOOD DAY

437
00:15:38,737 --> 00:15:40,005
This is the first time

438
00:15:40,072 --> 00:15:41,774
Woo-rim and Yuna share their fridge on TV.

439
00:15:41,840 --> 00:15:43,943
We present their fridge!

440
00:15:44,009 --> 00:15:45,010
-Their fridge!
-It's a first.

441
00:15:47,346 --> 00:15:48,914
-We present their fridge!
-Their fridge!

442
00:15:48,981 --> 00:15:49,949
It's a first.

443
00:15:51,183 --> 00:15:52,885
-It's so neatly organized.
-It is.

444
00:15:52,952 --> 00:15:53,953
It's neat.

445
00:15:54,353 --> 00:15:55,387
FEELING PROUD

446
00:15:55,454 --> 00:15:58,090
First off, I noticed
that they have lots of sauces.

447
00:15:58,157 --> 00:16:00,426
This means they cook at home too.

448
00:16:00,492 --> 00:16:01,493
The first shelf.

449
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:04,763
We believe
these are the traces of delivery food.

450
00:16:04,830 --> 00:16:05,664
It's delivery food.

451
00:16:05,731 --> 00:16:08,367
They must've ordered pizza,
fried chicken, and snack foods.

452
00:16:08,434 --> 00:16:10,035
I doubt athletes

453
00:16:10,102 --> 00:16:14,473
-ever order late-night snacks.
-No, never.

454
00:16:14,540 --> 00:16:16,809
Yes, that's true. I'm the one…

455
00:16:16,875 --> 00:16:19,912
who introduced her
to the world of late-night snacks.

456
00:16:19,979 --> 00:16:22,648
She couldn't eat as much as she wanted
when she was an active athlete,

457
00:16:22,715 --> 00:16:25,250
so she never knew
the concept of a late-night snack.

458
00:16:25,985 --> 00:16:28,754
But I really love to eat,

459
00:16:28,821 --> 00:16:31,590
so she sometimes says
that I have a PhD in eating.

460
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:33,859
-Does Yuna call you a doctor?
-Why?

461
00:16:33,926 --> 00:16:36,228
There are different combinations
of late-night snacks.

462
00:16:36,295 --> 00:16:38,197
For example, fried chicken and <i>tteokbokki,</i>

463
00:16:38,263 --> 00:16:40,933
and when you order fried chicken,
there are particular franchises.

464
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:43,369
She goes,
"Doctor, what are we ordering today?"

465
00:16:43,435 --> 00:16:45,137
Something like that.

466
00:16:45,204 --> 00:16:48,140
-So I'm the doctor of eating at home.
-Doctor of eating.

467
00:16:48,207 --> 00:16:50,209
What's Yuna's favorite late-night snack?

468
00:16:50,709 --> 00:16:52,077
She loves <i>ramyeon</i>.

469
00:16:52,144 --> 00:16:53,545
-<i>Ramyeon</i>.
-<i>Ramyeon</i>?

470
00:16:53,612 --> 00:16:55,014
-She has…
-She knows what's good.

471
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:58,217
…this resentment in her heart that
she couldn't eat <i>ramyeon</i> as an athlete.

472
00:16:58,283 --> 00:16:59,318
I can see that.

473
00:16:59,385 --> 00:17:01,286
That'd drive me insane.
I have to have <i>ramyeon</i>.

474
00:17:01,353 --> 00:17:03,322
So even now, when I make <i>ramyeon</i>,

475
00:17:03,389 --> 00:17:05,257
she'd always have some
even if she felt full.

476
00:17:05,324 --> 00:17:06,925
What's her favorite <i>ramyeon</i>?

477
00:17:06,992 --> 00:17:08,360
She likes <i>ramyeon</i> with soup,

478
00:17:08,427 --> 00:17:10,662
-but her favorite is <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>.
-Black bean <i>ramyeon</i>.

479
00:17:10,729 --> 00:17:11,630
She loves those.

480
00:17:11,697 --> 00:17:15,801
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> has a leading expert
of late-night snacks.

481
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:17,936
Doctor Yoon Nam-no.

482
00:17:18,003 --> 00:17:19,972
Doctor Yoon, can you recommend

483
00:17:20,039 --> 00:17:22,808
the best combination
of late-night snacks for Yuna?

484
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:25,677
I'm a big figure in the world
of short-form <i>ramyeon</i> content.

485
00:17:25,744 --> 00:17:29,715
Allow me to share the food pairing
as someone who has hit ten million views.

486
00:17:29,782 --> 00:17:31,917
-You said she likes <i>jjajang ramyeon.</i>
-Yes.

487
00:17:31,984 --> 00:17:33,819
There's a product called Chacharoni,

488
00:17:33,886 --> 00:17:36,889
and another <i>ramyeon</i> brand
called Gan-Jjamppong.

489
00:17:36,955 --> 00:17:40,259
Try mixing those,
because it'll be four times as good.

490
00:17:40,325 --> 00:17:42,194
-I'll write it down.
-Not Chapagetti, Chacharoni.

491
00:17:42,261 --> 00:17:43,829
That's the best stir-fried <i>ramyeon</i> mix.

492
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:45,497
-Next.
-Gan-Jjamppong and Chacharoni.

493
00:17:45,564 --> 00:17:49,101
Also, try mixing <i>doenjang-jjigae</i>
with Ansungtangmyun. It's really good.

494
00:17:49,168 --> 00:17:51,403
-His glutton data.
-<i>Doenjang-jjigae,</i> the stew?

495
00:17:51,470 --> 00:17:53,172
Do you add the noodles and the soup base?

496
00:17:53,238 --> 00:17:55,340
-The entire packet?
-The whole thing.

497
00:17:55,407 --> 00:17:57,776
-That sounds too salty.
-Wouldn't it become too salty?

498
00:17:57,843 --> 00:17:59,344
<i>Ramyeon</i> is supposed to be salty.

499
00:18:00,179 --> 00:18:01,680
WRITE DOWN THAT AWESOME QUOTE

500
00:18:02,481 --> 00:18:04,183
And Ansungtangmyun has that hearty flavor.

501
00:18:04,249 --> 00:18:06,652
You can dilute the saltiness
with lots of vegetables.

502
00:18:06,718 --> 00:18:09,254
It'll taste really good
with wild chives or shepherd's purse now.

503
00:18:09,321 --> 00:18:10,789
Ansungtangmyun is

504
00:18:10,856 --> 00:18:14,293
-a <i>doenjang</i>-based <i>ramyeon</i>, so it fits.
-Is that so?

505
00:18:14,359 --> 00:18:15,861
One thing is a must, though.

506
00:18:15,928 --> 00:18:17,696
<i>Kkakdugi</i>, radish kimchi. You need that.

507
00:18:17,763 --> 00:18:19,565
-That does sound good.
-Yes.

508
00:18:19,631 --> 00:18:22,201
-<i>Kkakdugi</i>.
-So that's how you eat Ansungtangmyun.

509
00:18:22,267 --> 00:18:25,237
-I've stored it in my memory.
-That's why he's your favorite chef.

510
00:18:25,304 --> 00:18:26,638
The second shelf.

511
00:18:27,239 --> 00:18:29,108
-What's that?
-Caviar.

512
00:18:29,174 --> 00:18:32,144
-I found another one here.
-Caviar?

513
00:18:32,211 --> 00:18:34,146
I got those as presents,

514
00:18:34,213 --> 00:18:36,715
but I didn't know what to do with those.

515
00:18:36,782 --> 00:18:40,352
I was hoping the chefs here
would teach me how to use those.

516
00:18:40,419 --> 00:18:42,788
-Right.
-I wanted to ask.

517
00:18:42,855 --> 00:18:46,191
You may use the caviar
if you choose to cook with his fridge.

518
00:18:46,258 --> 00:18:48,427
Next, some meat.

519
00:18:48,494 --> 00:18:50,129
Do you prefer any type of meat?

520
00:18:50,195 --> 00:18:53,866
I especially love beef outside skirt.

521
00:18:53,932 --> 00:18:57,269
I like the meaty aroma
and how juicy the cut is.

522
00:18:57,336 --> 00:18:58,504
I love it.

523
00:18:58,570 --> 00:19:00,239
That's my favorite cut too.

524
00:19:00,305 --> 00:19:01,974
I also like the oyster blade too.

525
00:19:02,040 --> 00:19:03,408
So you must prefer beef.

526
00:19:03,475 --> 00:19:04,476
Yes, I prefer beef.

527
00:19:04,543 --> 00:19:06,311
-It's that texture.
-He prefers beef to pork.

528
00:19:06,378 --> 00:19:08,080
You're Cow Woo-rim.

529
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:11,116
-Just like his voice. Moo.
-Moo.

530
00:19:11,183 --> 00:19:12,251
THE VOICE THEY WANT

531
00:19:13,485 --> 00:19:15,220
I've heard that at a ranch in Pyeongchang.

532
00:19:15,287 --> 00:19:16,655
-At a pasture?
-Yes.

533
00:19:17,456 --> 00:19:19,024
COW WOO-RIM GOES ALONG WITH EVERYTHING

534
00:19:19,091 --> 00:19:20,626
Wait, what's this?

535
00:19:20,692 --> 00:19:22,728
I found a picture of Woo-rim.

536
00:19:22,794 --> 00:19:24,730
-<i>Dongchimi</i>?
-Yes.

537
00:19:24,796 --> 00:19:29,101
I was a part of a cooking competition,

538
00:19:29,168 --> 00:19:31,003
where I took the victory.

539
00:19:31,069 --> 00:19:32,704
So that product came out.

540
00:19:32,771 --> 00:19:33,939
KO WOO-RIM'S DONGCHIMI

541
00:19:34,006 --> 00:19:37,276
You won that show?
That means you must cook well.

542
00:19:37,342 --> 00:19:38,977
I'm not that good,

543
00:19:39,044 --> 00:19:40,479
but I guess they enjoyed it.

544
00:19:40,546 --> 00:19:44,049
-We have proof of his cooking skills…
-Really?

545
00:19:44,116 --> 00:19:45,784
…in some photos. Let's take a look.

546
00:19:45,851 --> 00:19:47,419
These were made by Woo-rim.

547
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:50,189
-He's good.
-Tell us about them.

548
00:19:50,255 --> 00:19:51,690
-All different types of cuisine.
-He's good.

549
00:19:51,757 --> 00:19:54,259
-He's better at making pasta than you.
-It looks good.

550
00:19:54,326 --> 00:19:55,460
HE'S BETTER THAN AMY PARK

551
00:19:55,527 --> 00:19:58,096
That <i>dongchimi</i> dish. I took that product,

552
00:19:58,163 --> 00:20:01,833
seasoned it a little more,
and turned it into a noodle dish.

553
00:20:01,900 --> 00:20:03,569
So I made those noodles.

554
00:20:03,635 --> 00:20:05,003
That looks really good.

555
00:20:05,070 --> 00:20:06,171
The last picture

556
00:20:06,238 --> 00:20:08,874
is the meal I made for my wife's birthday.

557
00:20:08,941 --> 00:20:11,577
-That was the birthday meal.
-<i>Miyeok-guk</i>, seaweed soup, right?

558
00:20:11,643 --> 00:20:14,780
There's hamburger steak under those eggs.

559
00:20:14,846 --> 00:20:16,949
The fried eggs look so pretty.

560
00:20:17,015 --> 00:20:18,984
-The yolks are in the dead center.
-Seriously.

561
00:20:19,051 --> 00:20:21,220
When he sent these pictures,

562
00:20:21,286 --> 00:20:25,891
he added that Yuna is actually
the better cook between them.

563
00:20:25,958 --> 00:20:29,795
-So he sent us pictures of her dishes too.
-Really?

564
00:20:29,861 --> 00:20:33,498
You're about to see
pictures of dishes Kim Yuna made.

565
00:20:33,565 --> 00:20:34,466
He said she's good.

566
00:20:35,634 --> 00:20:36,969
They look nice too.

567
00:20:37,035 --> 00:20:38,704
Is the first one kimchi fried rice?

568
00:20:38,770 --> 00:20:41,740
Yes, she seasons
kimchi fried rice perfectly.

569
00:20:41,807 --> 00:20:44,409
Look at the glean.
It looks like something from a restaurant.

570
00:20:44,476 --> 00:20:48,213
-The next one is tomato pasta with bacon.
-Tomato pasta.

571
00:20:48,280 --> 00:20:51,049
-The third one is Mongolian beef.
-That looks good.

572
00:20:51,116 --> 00:20:53,986
She wanted to try making it,
and she did a great job.

573
00:20:54,052 --> 00:20:56,989
The last one is an American breakfast.

574
00:20:57,055 --> 00:20:59,358
-Breakfast.
-These are some of the things she made.

575
00:20:59,424 --> 00:21:01,593
She made it look nice too.

576
00:21:01,660 --> 00:21:04,396
Look how happy he is.

577
00:21:04,463 --> 00:21:07,199
Yuna's good at everything.

578
00:21:07,266 --> 00:21:08,734
THERE'S NOTHING KIM YUNA CAN'T DO

579
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:10,702
Look at the third shelf.

580
00:21:10,769 --> 00:21:12,638
All kinds of side dishes.

581
00:21:12,704 --> 00:21:14,506
Did Yuna make all these?

582
00:21:14,573 --> 00:21:16,308
Actually, it wasn't her.

583
00:21:16,375 --> 00:21:17,476
-No?
-It's my mother-in-law.

584
00:21:17,542 --> 00:21:19,678
-His mother-in-law.
-Mother-in-law.

585
00:21:19,745 --> 00:21:21,446
There are so many kinds. What's this?

586
00:21:21,513 --> 00:21:24,750
-Stir-fried anchovies.
-Anchovies and shishito peppers.

587
00:21:24,816 --> 00:21:26,451
These look delicious.

588
00:21:26,518 --> 00:21:27,853
The shelf below that one.

589
00:21:28,353 --> 00:21:30,222
I see some bread here.

590
00:21:30,289 --> 00:21:31,490
And bagels.

591
00:21:31,556 --> 00:21:33,025
-That's a lot.
-And regular bread.

592
00:21:33,558 --> 00:21:34,760
-There's a lot.
-She must love bread.

593
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:36,295
I'm often busy with work,

594
00:21:36,361 --> 00:21:40,065
so I thought I should eat
at least one meal with my wife.

595
00:21:40,666 --> 00:21:41,833
Because of that,

596
00:21:41,900 --> 00:21:43,602
I often grab some bread.

597
00:21:43,669 --> 00:21:44,936
I came to like it a lot.

598
00:21:45,003 --> 00:21:47,706
They're a family
centered around breakfast.

599
00:21:47,773 --> 00:21:51,777
We say we should eat
a hearty first meal of the day.

600
00:21:51,843 --> 00:21:54,112
-I like to make pour-over coffee.
-I see.

601
00:21:54,179 --> 00:21:56,982
While my wife puts bread in the toaster,

602
00:21:57,049 --> 00:21:58,417
I brew coffee.

603
00:21:59,117 --> 00:22:00,385
That suits you.

604
00:22:00,452 --> 00:22:02,587
-Some hash browns.
-Yes.

605
00:22:02,654 --> 00:22:06,224
-These are the ingredients from the photo.
-You're right.

606
00:22:06,291 --> 00:22:08,927
-It's the breakfast shelf in the freezer.
-The breakfast shelf.

607
00:22:08,994 --> 00:22:10,629
Some vegetables here.

608
00:22:10,696 --> 00:22:13,532
-Asparagus, zucchini…
-Zucchini.

609
00:22:13,598 --> 00:22:15,500
-And some wine.
-Yes.

610
00:22:15,567 --> 00:22:17,803
This must be red wine…

611
00:22:17,869 --> 00:22:19,471
-White wine.
-…and this is white wine.

612
00:22:19,538 --> 00:22:20,405
Do you enjoy wine?

613
00:22:20,472 --> 00:22:22,174
-I…
-Woo-rim is an addict.

614
00:22:22,240 --> 00:22:23,575
Is he an addict?

615
00:22:23,642 --> 00:22:25,277
He's a huge wine lover.

616
00:22:26,111 --> 00:22:29,047
I've been really into wine lately.

617
00:22:29,114 --> 00:22:32,884
<i>I've been enjoying some wine</i>
<i>whenever there's a great occasion.</i>

618
00:22:32,951 --> 00:22:34,786
I personally hope

619
00:22:34,853 --> 00:22:38,357
my wife catches on to the fun of wine,

620
00:22:38,423 --> 00:22:40,759
but even when we have some,
she has one glass at most.

621
00:22:40,826 --> 00:22:44,429
A bottle of wine is a little too much
for anyone to have alone.

622
00:22:44,496 --> 00:22:45,664
Yes, it's too much.

623
00:22:45,731 --> 00:22:47,899
So if my wife begins to have more,

624
00:22:47,966 --> 00:22:50,102
I'd be able to pop a bottle.

625
00:22:50,168 --> 00:22:51,903
-But I haven't done that yet.
-Does this mean

626
00:22:51,970 --> 00:22:54,206
your wife is more into soju?

627
00:22:54,272 --> 00:22:56,274
-Does she not drink?
-She doesn't really drink.

628
00:22:56,341 --> 00:22:58,410
I got her into late-night snacks

629
00:22:58,477 --> 00:23:01,847
and coffee, especially pour-over coffee,

630
00:23:01,913 --> 00:23:04,750
so now I'm working on wine.

631
00:23:04,816 --> 00:23:05,784
I get it.

632
00:23:05,851 --> 00:23:07,586
What's here? Goodness.

633
00:23:07,652 --> 00:23:09,888
It's a container full of something.

634
00:23:09,955 --> 00:23:11,223
WHAT IS IT?

635
00:23:11,289 --> 00:23:13,291
-I see lots of fish cakes.
-Yes.

636
00:23:13,358 --> 00:23:18,897
Yuna and I both love soup dishes,
so we often make fish cake soup.

637
00:23:18,964 --> 00:23:21,299
We also love udon soup.

638
00:23:21,366 --> 00:23:22,768
So we like to stock up on those.

639
00:23:22,834 --> 00:23:24,436
Let's see some shelf-stable ingredients.

640
00:23:24,503 --> 00:23:26,772
-As he mentioned, <i>ramyeon</i>.
-Yes, <i>ramyeon</i>.

641
00:23:26,838 --> 00:23:28,974
There's more bread here.

642
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:30,675
I see Kang-rok there.

643
00:23:30,742 --> 00:23:33,011
I found Choi Kang-rok.

644
00:23:33,078 --> 00:23:36,114
-Japanese braising soy sauce.
-Yes.

645
00:23:36,181 --> 00:23:37,883
She enjoyed watching that show,

646
00:23:37,949 --> 00:23:41,386
so she must've become curious
and ordered it.

647
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:43,155
-He's still the same.
-Yes.

648
00:23:43,221 --> 00:23:45,290
-I miss that guy.
-Yeah.

649
00:23:45,357 --> 00:23:47,726
That's all for Woo-rim's fridge!

650
00:23:47,793 --> 00:23:49,461
THAT WAS WOO-RIM AND YUNA'S FRIDGE

651
00:23:49,528 --> 00:23:53,098
I wonder what Woo-rim wants to eat today.

652
00:23:53,165 --> 00:23:55,734
Here are his orders.

653
00:23:55,801 --> 00:23:57,102
His orders.

654
00:23:57,169 --> 00:23:58,670
It's called Temptation of Husband.

655
00:23:58,737 --> 00:24:00,705
TEMPTATION OF HUSBAND?

656
00:24:00,772 --> 00:24:02,674
-He needs a mole on his face.
-Yes.

657
00:24:02,741 --> 00:24:04,509
Looking closely, I can see that

658
00:24:04,576 --> 00:24:06,144
-Woo-rim has a mole on his face.
-I do.

659
00:24:06,211 --> 00:24:09,047
HAS A MOLE UNDER HIS EYE

660
00:24:09,414 --> 00:24:11,783
WHAT DOES HE MEAN
BY TEMPTATION OF HUSBAND?

661
00:24:11,850 --> 00:24:15,854
I'm hoping my wife
develops a taste for wine as I have.

662
00:24:16,655 --> 00:24:19,324
If I can find a dish
that pairs well with wine,

663
00:24:19,391 --> 00:24:22,394
I might be able to tempt her
much more easily.

664
00:24:22,828 --> 00:24:23,662
A DISH TO GO WITH WINE

665
00:24:23,728 --> 00:24:26,031
She may start drinking wine
because of that dish.

666
00:24:26,097 --> 00:24:26,998
Temptation of Husband.

667
00:24:27,065 --> 00:24:28,133
There's another order.

668
00:24:29,067 --> 00:24:32,037
-What's next? Couple's Breakfast.
-Couple's Breakfast.

669
00:24:32,103 --> 00:24:34,806
You two mostly have
bread and coffee, right?

670
00:24:34,873 --> 00:24:37,409
My wife and I promised

671
00:24:37,476 --> 00:24:39,611
to eat breakfast together
before we start our day.

672
00:24:39,678 --> 00:24:42,113
So it's a very important meal for us.

673
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:44,483
I want to eat breakfast dishes

674
00:24:44,549 --> 00:24:47,752
that we can enjoy deliciously
with some coffee.

675
00:24:47,819 --> 00:24:49,254
A new kind of breakfast.

676
00:24:49,321 --> 00:24:52,190
It's time to decide on the contenders.

677
00:24:52,257 --> 00:24:55,460
Nam-no, shouldn't you go first?
After all, you're their favorite.

678
00:24:55,527 --> 00:24:57,095
-Yes.
-You get the first chance.

679
00:24:57,162 --> 00:24:58,029
Maybe wine snacks?

680
00:24:58,096 --> 00:25:00,732
I have intended
the figuration of the order…

681
00:25:00,799 --> 00:25:01,867
What am I saying?

682
00:25:01,933 --> 00:25:03,101
-You get the intention?
-The order…

683
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:06,037
What do you mean you have intended
the figuration of the order?

684
00:25:06,104 --> 00:25:07,539
HAHA

685
00:25:07,606 --> 00:25:10,175
-He intended the figuration of the order.
-He intended the figuration of the order.

686
00:25:10,742 --> 00:25:12,644
What are you trying to say?

687
00:25:12,711 --> 00:25:14,679
You still don't get it, do you?

688
00:25:14,746 --> 00:25:17,148
You don't get it, so stop pretending.

689
00:25:17,215 --> 00:25:19,251
I'm sorry to ask, but is he not Korean?

690
00:25:20,752 --> 00:25:22,554
BORN AND RAISED IN KOREA

691
00:25:22,621 --> 00:25:26,091
-You figured out the intention.
-Yes, I figured out the intention.

692
00:25:26,157 --> 00:25:27,859
I'll go for Temptation of Husband.

693
00:25:27,926 --> 00:25:29,494
Temptation of Husband.

694
00:25:29,561 --> 00:25:31,696
A dish that pairs well with wine.

695
00:25:31,763 --> 00:25:34,933
-He's going for Temptation of Husband.
-He's set.

696
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:35,834
Next.

697
00:25:35,901 --> 00:25:40,205
Jong-won looks similar to him,
so why don't you go next?

698
00:25:40,272 --> 00:25:42,541
-Don't join my round.
-I'll go for Temptation of Husband.

699
00:25:43,108 --> 00:25:45,277
-I'll do Temptation of Husband.
-Temptation of Husband.

700
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:46,645
Why?

701
00:25:46,711 --> 00:25:48,847
You have lots of stars already.
Do the other thing.

702
00:25:49,247 --> 00:25:52,684
HE'S UP AGAINST SON JONG-WON,
THE CURRENT 1ST PLACE

703
00:25:52,751 --> 00:25:55,453
The first cook-off has been sealed.

704
00:25:55,520 --> 00:25:59,190
Who's up for Couple's Breakfast?
Something to eat with coffee.

705
00:25:59,257 --> 00:26:01,059
-I'll go.
-Sam!

706
00:26:01,626 --> 00:26:04,829
I always make breakfast and coffee too.

707
00:26:04,896 --> 00:26:07,799
I'll probably do a good job at it.

708
00:26:07,866 --> 00:26:09,434
It suits him.

709
00:26:09,501 --> 00:26:11,236
Sam joins the round.

710
00:26:11,303 --> 00:26:13,038
-One spot left.
-One last spot.

711
00:26:13,104 --> 00:26:15,707
-I'll go.
-Hey.

712
00:26:15,774 --> 00:26:17,842
He said he wanted breakfast,

713
00:26:17,909 --> 00:26:19,578
but I won't make anything conventional.

714
00:26:19,644 --> 00:26:23,014
I want to make something
only Yuna and he can enjoy

715
00:26:23,081 --> 00:26:24,950
when they're home.

716
00:26:25,016 --> 00:26:27,752
The cook-off is set
for Couple's Breakfast too.

717
00:26:27,819 --> 00:26:29,721
Temptation of Husband.

718
00:26:29,788 --> 00:26:33,358
Let us begin the cook-off
between Nam-no and Jong-won!

719
00:26:35,827 --> 00:26:39,965
<i>This is the first round</i>
<i>played with Woo-rim's ingredients.</i>

720
00:26:40,031 --> 00:26:42,167
Seduced by Jong-won,

721
00:26:42,233 --> 00:26:45,103
the self-professed pet piggy,

722
00:26:45,170 --> 00:26:46,571
Chef Yoon Nam-no

723
00:26:46,638 --> 00:26:48,406
versus his owner,

724
00:26:48,473 --> 00:26:51,209
-Chef Son Jong-won.
-The piggy owner.

725
00:26:51,476 --> 00:26:52,944
EXCITED

726
00:26:53,011 --> 00:26:57,048
Chef Jong-won currently has 7 stars,
and has won 3 games in a row.

727
00:26:57,115 --> 00:26:59,017
-He's in the lead.
-He's on a roll.

728
00:26:59,084 --> 00:27:01,586
Meanwhile, Chef Nam-no

729
00:27:01,653 --> 00:27:03,321
-has lost three times in a row.
-How?

730
00:27:03,388 --> 00:27:07,492
He's now the lowest-ranking chef
with only one star.

731
00:27:07,559 --> 00:27:09,194
If he had just understood the orders.

732
00:27:09,260 --> 00:27:11,296
We don't have to worry today, do we?

733
00:27:11,363 --> 00:27:12,864
I heard he kept mumbling
in the green room,

734
00:27:12,931 --> 00:27:15,967
"How can you tempt a husband?"

735
00:27:16,034 --> 00:27:17,736
I heard he mumbled that all by himself.

736
00:27:18,003 --> 00:27:19,638
TEMPT ME?

737
00:27:19,704 --> 00:27:21,439
I realized it'll be another easy round.

738
00:27:21,506 --> 00:27:23,108
What do you mean, tempt the husband?

739
00:27:23,174 --> 00:27:25,710
-It's the Temptation of Husband.
-Temptation of Husband.

740
00:27:25,777 --> 00:27:27,579
-He took it the wrong way.
-Nam-no.

741
00:27:27,646 --> 00:27:31,916
At first, I thought the order
was about tempting Woo-rim.

742
00:27:31,983 --> 00:27:33,885
He misunderstands stuff more than I do.

743
00:27:35,420 --> 00:27:37,355
BORN AND RAISED IN KOREA

744
00:27:37,422 --> 00:27:39,224
He must be too focused on cooking

745
00:27:39,290 --> 00:27:42,193
to hear anything else, so it's okay.

746
00:27:42,260 --> 00:27:44,062
It's got to be tough not to hear that.

747
00:27:44,129 --> 00:27:47,832
I heard Chef Nam-no
is feeling confident today.

748
00:27:47,899 --> 00:27:51,302
I've been the head chef
of a bistro and wine bar

749
00:27:51,369 --> 00:27:52,737
-for a long time.
-Really?

750
00:27:52,804 --> 00:27:55,940
I also plan to open my own,

751
00:27:56,007 --> 00:27:58,343
so this order is just for me, a drunkard.

752
00:27:58,410 --> 00:28:00,278
He ran a wine bar.

753
00:28:00,345 --> 00:28:03,248
-He's putting his reputation out there.
-I have lots of faith.

754
00:28:03,314 --> 00:28:04,449
Your eyes changed.

755
00:28:04,516 --> 00:28:06,651
-I trust him.
-It's perfect for him.

756
00:28:06,718 --> 00:28:10,088
But Chef Jong-won is also confident
when it comes to wine.

757
00:28:10,155 --> 00:28:13,458
I often have to pair wine
with the dining experience,

758
00:28:13,525 --> 00:28:14,793
and you had great wine.

759
00:28:15,093 --> 00:28:16,294
THANK YOU

760
00:28:16,361 --> 00:28:18,530
Here's the dynamic between you two.

761
00:28:18,596 --> 00:28:23,201
Nam-no is someone
who looks up to Jong-won.

762
00:28:23,268 --> 00:28:25,837
I'm just happy to stand here with him.

763
00:28:25,904 --> 00:28:27,072
You are?

764
00:28:27,138 --> 00:28:28,940
I looked through my old phone

765
00:28:29,007 --> 00:28:30,642
and found a cover letter

766
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:33,678
I prepared to apply for a job
when he had returned to Korea.

767
00:28:33,745 --> 00:28:35,680
-I see.
-Because you wanted to work with him?

768
00:28:35,747 --> 00:28:38,750
-Really?
-It's real. I can show it to you.

769
00:28:38,817 --> 00:28:39,851
It was 2019.

770
00:28:39,918 --> 00:28:42,053
-That's amazing.
-You actually did that?

771
00:28:42,120 --> 00:28:43,655
It's been several years.

772
00:28:43,722 --> 00:28:45,590
In the building I work at,

773
00:28:45,657 --> 00:28:48,159
you'll find my restaurant
and another Chinese restaurant.

774
00:28:48,226 --> 00:28:50,829
I believe he applied for a job
at that restaurant.

775
00:28:50,895 --> 00:28:52,697
-The Chinese restaurant?
-Come on.

776
00:28:52,764 --> 00:28:53,932
I'M GOOD AT TOSSING A WOK TOO

777
00:28:54,899 --> 00:28:57,001
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS:
SALMON, BREAD, HASH BROWNS

778
00:28:57,068 --> 00:28:59,270
CAVIAR, ASPARAGUS,
WHITE WINE, CREAM CHEESE, LEMON JUICE

779
00:28:59,337 --> 00:29:01,539
What are you making, Chef Nam-no?

780
00:29:01,606 --> 00:29:03,208
My dish is called

781
00:29:03,908 --> 00:29:05,276
Winestein.

782
00:29:05,343 --> 00:29:07,278
-Winestein.
-Winestein.

783
00:29:07,345 --> 00:29:09,247
-Winestein.
-Nice name.

784
00:29:09,314 --> 00:29:11,616
-I like this name. Winestein.
-Yes, nice title.

785
00:29:11,683 --> 00:29:12,817
I'm getting curious.

786
00:29:12,884 --> 00:29:14,753
Many people think I'm stupid,

787
00:29:14,819 --> 00:29:15,987
but I'm only pretending.

788
00:29:16,054 --> 00:29:18,423
-No one said that.
-I'm a genius pretending to be stupid.

789
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:21,226
No. No one said you were stupid.

790
00:29:21,292 --> 00:29:22,961
Everyone back there laughed too.

791
00:29:23,528 --> 00:29:25,864
You lack understanding,
but you aren't stupid.

792
00:29:26,498 --> 00:29:27,866
You just lack understanding.

793
00:29:27,932 --> 00:29:31,369
-You just don't get the context.
-We didn't say you were stupid.

794
00:29:31,436 --> 00:29:33,738
It's just his language skills.

795
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:35,607
It's not the lack of understanding.

796
00:29:35,673 --> 00:29:36,741
It's my lack of focus.

797
00:29:36,808 --> 00:29:39,210
-You do lack focus.
-Yes, it's your attention span.

798
00:29:39,277 --> 00:29:41,613
-Are you making a smart dish?
-Today,

799
00:29:41,679 --> 00:29:44,249
-I'm going to make <i>menbosha</i>.
-<i>Menbosha</i>?

800
00:29:44,315 --> 00:29:46,451
He did apply for a job
at that Chinese restaurant!

801
00:29:46,518 --> 00:29:48,453
He submitted his résumé there!

802
00:29:48,520 --> 00:29:52,290
-<i>Menbosha</i>. You're right.
-Jong-won's speculation was right.

803
00:29:52,357 --> 00:29:54,259
-However…
-I think I've seen you come and go.

804
00:29:54,325 --> 00:29:56,094
…it's not regular <i>menbosha</i>.

805
00:29:56,161 --> 00:29:57,028
It's French <i>menbosha</i>.

806
00:29:57,095 --> 00:29:58,630
-French <i>menbosha</i>?
-French <i>menbosha</i>?

807
00:29:58,696 --> 00:30:01,633
-<i>Menbosha </i>is originally made with shrimp.
-Yes.

808
00:30:01,699 --> 00:30:06,538
But I'll roll up salmon
in a piece of bread and grill it instead.

809
00:30:06,604 --> 00:30:09,007
-That sounds good.
-Salmon rolled up in bread.

810
00:30:09,073 --> 00:30:11,810
There's a French dish
called <i>poisson croustillant.</i>

811
00:30:11,876 --> 00:30:14,012
Think of it as a crispy fish dish.

812
00:30:14,078 --> 00:30:16,080
-That's a good dish.
-I'll serve that

813
00:30:16,147 --> 00:30:18,716
with delicious sauce
made with hot spring eggs.

814
00:30:18,783 --> 00:30:21,786
I'll also make pretty flower shapes
with the caviar in your fridge.

815
00:30:21,853 --> 00:30:22,987
Caviar flowers?

816
00:30:23,054 --> 00:30:24,722
I'll make the dish

817
00:30:24,789 --> 00:30:27,025
both genius
in its presentation and flavor.

818
00:30:27,091 --> 00:30:28,726
-It's Winestein.
-He keeps that going.

819
00:30:28,793 --> 00:30:31,229
He says it's a genius dish,
so let's look forward to it.

820
00:30:32,163 --> 00:30:34,098
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
SALMON, BREAD, CAVIAR

821
00:30:34,165 --> 00:30:36,234
ASPARAGUS, WHITE WINE, MILK,
CREAM CHEESE, LEMON JUICE

822
00:30:36,301 --> 00:30:38,903
Up against him is Jong-won.
What are you making?

823
00:30:38,970 --> 00:30:40,805
The name of my dish is this.

824
00:30:41,940 --> 00:30:42,874
Kim Yuna!

825
00:30:43,441 --> 00:30:45,443
Won't Yuna Fall for This?

826
00:30:45,510 --> 00:30:46,444
Huh?

827
00:30:46,511 --> 00:30:47,545
Won't you fall for this?

828
00:30:48,012 --> 00:30:51,516
A SHY ATTEMPT AT A TEMPTING NAME

829
00:30:51,583 --> 00:30:54,152
He's way too flushed.

830
00:30:54,219 --> 00:30:56,721
-He's really red.
-That was cute.

831
00:30:56,788 --> 00:30:58,923
I saw some caviar in his fridge

832
00:30:58,990 --> 00:31:00,825
and they were two different types.

833
00:31:00,892 --> 00:31:03,328
I'll serve one kind with salmon

834
00:31:03,394 --> 00:31:05,763
and the other with eggs.

835
00:31:05,830 --> 00:31:07,298
-They both go well together.
-I hear

836
00:31:07,365 --> 00:31:10,568
Yuna's birthday
and your anniversary are coming up.

837
00:31:10,635 --> 00:31:14,105
So I prepared a dish you could make her
on special occasions.

838
00:31:14,172 --> 00:31:16,674
All right, now.

839
00:31:16,741 --> 00:31:19,410
Let us begin the round for Woo-rim,
Temptation of Husband.

840
00:31:19,477 --> 00:31:20,912
-Wow.
-Hey.

841
00:31:20,979 --> 00:31:22,013
I get to see this?

842
00:31:23,448 --> 00:31:24,883
What does he mean by that?

843
00:31:24,949 --> 00:31:26,417
-Einstein.
-Einstein.

844
00:31:26,484 --> 00:31:27,685
He didn't wear glasses.

845
00:31:28,820 --> 00:31:31,489
You kind of look silly
with that light from above.

846
00:31:31,756 --> 00:31:33,625
THE INTENTION WASN'T DELIVERED

847
00:31:33,691 --> 00:31:35,460
Forget the Nam-no of the past.

848
00:31:35,526 --> 00:31:39,731
Yoon Nam-no returns a new man,
as a reincarnation of victory!

849
00:31:39,797 --> 00:31:41,432
Forget his kind-hearted nature.

850
00:31:41,499 --> 00:31:44,402
He's here to make Nam-no cry like a baby.

851
00:31:44,469 --> 00:31:46,604
Son Jong-won is up for the cook-off.

852
00:31:46,671 --> 00:31:50,975
Which one of them will tempt Queen Yuna
into the world of wine?

853
00:31:51,042 --> 00:31:54,579
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

854
00:31:56,614 --> 00:31:58,283
A wine snack cook-off.

855
00:31:58,349 --> 00:31:59,450
It's an honor.

856
00:32:00,151 --> 00:32:00,985
SALUTE

857
00:32:02,020 --> 00:32:03,421
SWOOSH

858
00:32:03,488 --> 00:32:04,989
-A wine snack cook-off.
-It's an honor.

859
00:32:05,056 --> 00:32:06,624
-He's cooking eggs.
-Eggs right away.

860
00:32:06,691 --> 00:32:09,761
I'll boil these for exactly four minutes

861
00:32:09,827 --> 00:32:11,863
and immediately cool them in iced water.

862
00:32:11,930 --> 00:32:13,264
I see. Four minutes.

863
00:32:13,331 --> 00:32:17,402
So the whites will be cooked,
while the yolks are still runny.

864
00:32:17,468 --> 00:32:18,836
He turned the stove off.

865
00:32:18,903 --> 00:32:21,606
He's going to
cook them with residual heat.

866
00:32:21,673 --> 00:32:25,276
He said he'd make sauce
with hot spring eggs,

867
00:32:25,343 --> 00:32:28,346
so he'll probably make them soft-boiled.

868
00:32:28,613 --> 00:32:30,748
WHAT'S NEXT?

869
00:32:31,149 --> 00:32:34,552
1. MAKE CIRCULAR HASH BROWN SHAPES
WITH A COOKIE CUTTER

870
00:32:34,619 --> 00:32:37,121
He's slicing bread

871
00:32:37,188 --> 00:32:38,790
and making pretty flower shapes.

872
00:32:38,856 --> 00:32:40,124
2. MAKE FLOWERS WITH BREAD

873
00:32:40,191 --> 00:32:43,861
Nam-no is cutting out shapes
from hash browns and bread.

874
00:32:44,429 --> 00:32:46,664
Chef Nam-no looks cool when he cooks.

875
00:32:46,731 --> 00:32:49,567
-Doesn't he seem cool now?
-He changes.

876
00:32:49,634 --> 00:32:51,869
They're sexy
when they do their actual jobs.

877
00:32:51,936 --> 00:32:53,938
SEXY AT WORK

878
00:32:54,005 --> 00:32:56,207
Nam-no is cool when he doesn't talk.

879
00:32:57,375 --> 00:32:58,209
He's so cool.

880
00:32:58,276 --> 00:33:01,379
-He just needs to stop doing this.
-I can't see his face or hear him talk,

881
00:33:01,446 --> 00:33:02,714
so he seems intelligent.

882
00:33:03,081 --> 00:33:05,950
HASH BROWNS & BREAD INTO THE OVEN

883
00:33:08,086 --> 00:33:09,954
There's his silly face again.

884
00:33:10,021 --> 00:33:12,623
-There's his silly face again.
-He looks silly.

885
00:33:12,690 --> 00:33:14,759
Drop your head.

886
00:33:14,826 --> 00:33:16,294
Try not to show your face.

887
00:33:16,361 --> 00:33:18,496
He just looked silly
when he lifted his head.

888
00:33:19,197 --> 00:33:20,765
WHAT ABOUT JONG-WON,
SLICING THE SAME BREAD?

889
00:33:20,898 --> 00:33:23,134
LOOKS COOLER IN COMPARISON

890
00:33:23,201 --> 00:33:25,203
He's making thin slices.

891
00:33:25,269 --> 00:33:27,171
-Yes, those are thin slices.
-Very thin.

892
00:33:27,238 --> 00:33:29,607
Jong-won is also
cutting a hole in the bread.

893
00:33:30,174 --> 00:33:32,243
And another hole.

894
00:33:32,310 --> 00:33:33,711
-Twice?
-Is that a ring?

895
00:33:33,778 --> 00:33:36,547
-Right? He's making rings.
-Yes, those are rings.

896
00:33:36,614 --> 00:33:38,182
-He made rings.
-He's using rings?

897
00:33:38,249 --> 00:33:39,083
Like squid rings.

898
00:33:39,984 --> 00:33:42,820
One of the bread rings snapped.

899
00:33:42,887 --> 00:33:43,888
-What?
-What?

900
00:33:43,955 --> 00:33:44,856
-It snapped?
-Yes.

901
00:33:45,323 --> 00:33:46,724
A CRACK ON THE RING

902
00:33:47,191 --> 00:33:48,092
SHH!

903
00:33:48,159 --> 00:33:49,827
Oh, that's a secret!

904
00:33:49,894 --> 00:33:50,995
Okay?

905
00:33:51,062 --> 00:33:52,397
Don't say it.

906
00:33:52,463 --> 00:33:54,065
-Don't say it. It's a secret!
-It's a secret!

907
00:33:54,132 --> 00:33:55,767
-You can't tell anyone.
-I won't tell.

908
00:33:55,833 --> 00:33:57,769
-Do not say it.
-I won't. I'll shut my mouth.

909
00:33:58,336 --> 00:33:59,604
I didn't hear anything.

910
00:33:59,670 --> 00:34:00,571
I know nothing.

911
00:34:01,305 --> 00:34:03,007
4 MINUTES HAVE PASSED

912
00:34:03,674 --> 00:34:05,443
He took the eggs out and put them
in cold water after four minutes.

913
00:34:05,510 --> 00:34:06,844
PUTS THE BOILED EGGS INTO ICE WATER

914
00:34:06,911 --> 00:34:08,546
He's exactly on time.

915
00:34:08,613 --> 00:34:11,682
In the old days, he would've been called
something like the Computer Chef.

916
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:13,518
WHAT AN OLD EXPRESSION

917
00:34:13,584 --> 00:34:14,986
-"Computer."
-Computer?

918
00:34:15,053 --> 00:34:17,054
Now, there's salmon.

919
00:34:17,121 --> 00:34:19,791
-What's that?
-What is it? Starch?

920
00:34:19,857 --> 00:34:21,192
What did you sprinkle on the fish?

921
00:34:21,259 --> 00:34:23,628
-What's that on the salmon?
-It's starch.

922
00:34:23,694 --> 00:34:26,264
-To stick the bread on the fish.
-Starch.

923
00:34:26,631 --> 00:34:27,899
PAN WITH MELTED BUTTER

924
00:34:27,965 --> 00:34:30,868
He's grilling the salmon with the bread

925
00:34:30,935 --> 00:34:32,837
-in a frying pan.
-I see.

926
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:34,806
It acts as the salmon's crispy skin.

927
00:34:34,872 --> 00:34:37,909
-Then the top will become very crispy.
-I see.

928
00:34:37,975 --> 00:34:39,744
You have ten minutes left.

929
00:34:39,811 --> 00:34:41,512
That's so fast.
Can they finish in 15 minutes?

930
00:34:41,579 --> 00:34:43,214
There's Nam-no's salmon.

931
00:34:43,281 --> 00:34:46,083
Both chefs are using salmon, right?

932
00:34:46,150 --> 00:34:47,218
3. CHOP AND SALT SALMON

933
00:34:49,654 --> 00:34:53,091
He said he'd roll the salmon
in bread, right?

934
00:34:53,157 --> 00:34:55,960
Chef Nam-no rolled the bread
with salmon in it.

935
00:34:56,027 --> 00:34:56,894
SQUEEZING

936
00:34:56,961 --> 00:34:59,530
-He made it into a roll.
-He rolled it up.

937
00:34:59,597 --> 00:35:00,832
ONCE FIXED, REMOVE THE PLASTIC!

938
00:35:01,432 --> 00:35:02,433
FUMBLING

939
00:35:02,500 --> 00:35:03,968
Can you remove the plastic, please?

940
00:35:05,436 --> 00:35:07,738
A HELPING HAND

941
00:35:09,340 --> 00:35:10,241
Gosh, butter.

942
00:35:10,308 --> 00:35:13,010
-Butter?
-French cuisine equals butter, doesn't it?

943
00:35:13,077 --> 00:35:17,715
They're both making something
based on French dishes.

944
00:35:17,782 --> 00:35:20,618
They're both using bread and salmon,

945
00:35:20,685 --> 00:35:21,819
but the shapes differ.

946
00:35:21,886 --> 00:35:23,921
One of them rolled it,
the other just put them together.

947
00:35:25,022 --> 00:35:26,991
-It's unraveling.
-It's unrolling.

948
00:35:27,692 --> 00:35:29,060
WILL YOU PLEASE BE QUIET?

949
00:35:29,127 --> 00:35:30,428
I feel anxious, so stop.

950
00:35:30,495 --> 00:35:32,930
-It's a secret that it came undone.
-What came undone?

951
00:35:32,997 --> 00:35:34,932
-It's a secret.
-It's a secret.

952
00:35:34,999 --> 00:35:37,768
You usually have to leave it wrapped
for at least a day.

953
00:35:37,835 --> 00:35:40,505
It's not something that can be done
in 15 minutes.

954
00:35:40,571 --> 00:35:43,174
-Should've unwrapped it tomorrow. Shame.
-Right, tomorrow.

955
00:35:43,608 --> 00:35:45,776
HOW ABOUT JONG-WON'S SALMON AND BREAD?

956
00:35:45,843 --> 00:35:48,179
That's why Chef Jong-won's dish

957
00:35:48,246 --> 00:35:49,614
is the smarter dish.

958
00:35:49,680 --> 00:35:52,116
The fish right on the bread
makes it fall apart.

959
00:35:52,183 --> 00:35:53,317
But he sprinkled starch

960
00:35:53,384 --> 00:35:57,722
and used the moisture from the salmon
to make it stick to the bread.

961
00:35:57,788 --> 00:36:00,658
I think
that's what we should call Winestein.

962
00:36:00,725 --> 00:36:02,493
THIS SIDE SEEMS MORE LIKE WINESTEIN…

963
00:36:02,560 --> 00:36:05,196
-Their recipes seem similar.
-Nam-no, show us something smart too.

964
00:36:05,263 --> 00:36:06,097
ASPARAGUS

965
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:08,900
He claimed that he'd make a genius dish.

966
00:36:11,536 --> 00:36:12,370
STIR-FRYING ASPARAGUS

967
00:36:12,436 --> 00:36:14,438
Jong-won also uses asparagus.

968
00:36:14,505 --> 00:36:17,775
-They're using the exact same ingredients!
-They're too similar.

969
00:36:17,842 --> 00:36:18,709
Is it always like this?

970
00:36:18,776 --> 00:36:20,077
-Not at all.
-No, not really.

971
00:36:20,144 --> 00:36:22,914
They're both using salmon,
bread, and asparagus.

972
00:36:22,980 --> 00:36:24,482
So far,

973
00:36:24,549 --> 00:36:27,552
it seems like they're competing
on who makes the same dish faster.

974
00:36:27,618 --> 00:36:30,288
-They're the same.
-They are. It's salmon and bread.

975
00:36:30,354 --> 00:36:32,223
-He's using asparagus.
-Like that.

976
00:36:32,290 --> 00:36:33,457
What's he doing?

977
00:36:33,524 --> 00:36:35,626
He's peeling the skin off the bottom.

978
00:36:35,693 --> 00:36:37,094
Because it's tough?

979
00:36:37,161 --> 00:36:39,597
That brings out its crunchiness even more.

980
00:36:39,664 --> 00:36:41,065
-I see.
-His presentation is beautiful.

981
00:36:41,132 --> 00:36:43,768
Have you ever seen him make
a careless dish?

982
00:36:43,834 --> 00:36:45,002
Never.

983
00:36:45,536 --> 00:36:47,171
THAT'S SONTAIL

984
00:36:48,239 --> 00:36:50,841
BLANCH IN BOILING WATER

985
00:36:50,908 --> 00:36:53,945
-He's putting it into iced water.
-For a crunchy texture.

986
00:36:54,579 --> 00:36:57,248
-That's how he does it?
-He's using asparagus in different ways.

987
00:36:57,315 --> 00:36:59,483
-He's doing a lot of stuff.
-He is.

988
00:36:59,550 --> 00:37:02,086
-He sliced this one.
-Yes.

989
00:37:02,153 --> 00:37:04,322
Asparagus is widely used in France
in the spring.

990
00:37:04,388 --> 00:37:06,357
KNOWN AS A SPRING DELICACY IN FRANCE

991
00:37:06,424 --> 00:37:10,094
They were doing similar things at first,
but not anymore.

992
00:37:10,528 --> 00:37:11,362
BUTTER

993
00:37:12,597 --> 00:37:14,899
4. GRILL JULIENNED ONION
AND ASPARAGUS IN BUTTER

994
00:37:14,966 --> 00:37:16,234
He gets more asparagus.

995
00:37:17,335 --> 00:37:18,669
ADD WHITE WINE

996
00:37:18,736 --> 00:37:19,971
White wine.

997
00:37:20,037 --> 00:37:21,505
He's adding wine.

998
00:37:21,572 --> 00:37:23,307
He's using wine in the dish as well.

999
00:37:23,374 --> 00:37:25,476
Chef, may I use some wine?

1000
00:37:25,977 --> 00:37:27,511
THEY'RE BOTH USING WHITE WINE

1001
00:37:28,045 --> 00:37:29,747
TIME FOR NAM-NO TO SHOW SOMETHING TOO!

1002
00:37:29,814 --> 00:37:32,083
-White wine.
-He's pouring a lot!

1003
00:37:32,683 --> 00:37:34,986
This type of wine
goes well with asparagus.

1004
00:37:35,052 --> 00:37:38,623
The asparagus is now boiling down in wine

1005
00:37:38,689 --> 00:37:41,592
-and is on fire.
-He's boiling it down in wine.

1006
00:37:41,659 --> 00:37:43,361
You're halfway done now.

1007
00:37:43,427 --> 00:37:44,595
CHECKING THE OVEN

1008
00:37:45,096 --> 00:37:47,431
TOASTED BREAD SNOWFLAKES & HASH BROWNS

1009
00:37:48,132 --> 00:37:51,235
GRILL SALMON MENBOSHA TOGETHER

1010
00:37:53,671 --> 00:37:54,805
HUH?

1011
00:37:56,240 --> 00:37:57,508
SNEAKING A BITE

1012
00:37:58,309 --> 00:38:00,044
-He dropped it to eat it.
-It was intentional.

1013
00:38:00,111 --> 00:38:01,946
Is that why he called it genius?

1014
00:38:02,013 --> 00:38:03,981
If he picked it up and ate it,
he'd get caught,

1015
00:38:04,048 --> 00:38:06,250
<i>so he threw one out of the pan and ate it.</i>

1016
00:38:06,317 --> 00:38:07,551
He's a genius.

1017
00:38:07,618 --> 00:38:09,954
-He's a genius. Winestein, indeed.
-He's a genius.

1018
00:38:10,021 --> 00:38:12,390
Genius. I couldn't even imagine that idea.

1019
00:38:12,456 --> 00:38:15,026
Once again, I'm a genius
who only pretends to be stupid.

1020
00:38:15,860 --> 00:38:16,794
EATING GENIUS AT WORK

1021
00:38:17,061 --> 00:38:18,195
CREAM CHEESE

1022
00:38:18,262 --> 00:38:19,096
Lemon juice.

1023
00:38:19,163 --> 00:38:20,097
Salt.

1024
00:38:20,765 --> 00:38:23,401
Chef Nam-no mixed
cream cheese and lemon juice,

1025
00:38:23,467 --> 00:38:25,970
-then put it in a piping bag.
-A piping bag!

1026
00:38:26,037 --> 00:38:29,040
Do the spinning thing. The cool thing.

1027
00:38:29,106 --> 00:38:30,675
What? I don't do that.

1028
00:38:30,975 --> 00:38:32,877
CAN ONLY BE SMART,
NOT COOL

1029
00:38:34,178 --> 00:38:35,379
MILK

1030
00:38:35,446 --> 00:38:37,982
Chef Jong-won is making
something called velouté.

1031
00:38:38,049 --> 00:38:39,283
Asparagus velouté.

1032
00:38:39,884 --> 00:38:41,452
BLEND

1033
00:38:41,786 --> 00:38:44,655
Add some broth, bring it to a boil,
and it becomes soup.

1034
00:38:44,722 --> 00:38:47,892
He made a thick purée
which is called velouté.

1035
00:38:47,958 --> 00:38:50,394
ASPARAGUS VELOUTÉ
AS THICK AS PURÉE

1036
00:38:50,461 --> 00:38:52,663
You have six and a half minutes!

1037
00:38:52,730 --> 00:38:53,898
You don't have much time.

1038
00:38:55,399 --> 00:38:58,035
5. BOIL OLIVE OIL, WHOLE BLACK PEPPER,
ONION, WHITE WINE, AND STRAIN

1039
00:38:58,102 --> 00:39:02,807
I boiled down white wine
with black pepper and onion.

1040
00:39:02,873 --> 00:39:06,243
-I have to use lots of butter.
-He moves really quickly.

1041
00:39:06,310 --> 00:39:07,912
-Five minutes, Sung-ju!
-Yes.

1042
00:39:07,978 --> 00:39:10,047
-Only five minutes?
-Please report from the kitchen!

1043
00:39:10,114 --> 00:39:12,216
Let me check how things are going.

1044
00:39:12,283 --> 00:39:14,819
Everything happens really quickly.

1045
00:39:14,885 --> 00:39:18,656
-First off, velouté. Let me try this.
-Velouté.

1046
00:39:18,723 --> 00:39:20,825
He's cooling it right now.

1047
00:39:20,891 --> 00:39:24,328
What's Jong-won's velouté like?

1048
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:26,664
Will she fall for the temptation?

1049
00:39:26,997 --> 00:39:28,999
WILL YUNA FALL FOR THE TEMPTATION?

1050
00:39:29,066 --> 00:39:30,368
OR WILL SHE NOT?

1051
00:39:30,434 --> 00:39:31,602
Hey.

1052
00:39:31,669 --> 00:39:32,937
Will she?

1053
00:39:33,003 --> 00:39:34,672
It's a bit too bland.

1054
00:39:35,573 --> 00:39:37,908
-Is it?
-He probably needs to season this.

1055
00:39:37,975 --> 00:39:39,110
IT NEEDS TO BE SEASONED

1056
00:39:40,044 --> 00:39:42,079
TOASTED BREAD RING, OUT

1057
00:39:42,613 --> 00:39:44,014
HOW'S THE SALMON?

1058
00:39:45,316 --> 00:39:47,485
Don't you need some salt?

1059
00:39:47,551 --> 00:39:48,452
Is this okay?

1060
00:39:48,753 --> 00:39:49,954
FIRST, CHECK THE TEMPERATURE

1061
00:39:50,020 --> 00:39:52,022
He's ignoring most of my words.

1062
00:39:52,089 --> 00:39:53,824
-He's barely listening.
-Not anymore.

1063
00:39:53,891 --> 00:39:55,693
I'm busy, I'm busy.

1064
00:39:55,760 --> 00:39:57,161
It's not intentional.

1065
00:39:57,228 --> 00:39:59,096
No, he's really busy.

1066
00:39:59,730 --> 00:40:01,632
PEELING EGGS COOKED FOR 4 MINUTES

1067
00:40:02,299 --> 00:40:03,768
BUT

1068
00:40:04,935 --> 00:40:05,770
Oh, no.

1069
00:40:08,639 --> 00:40:09,507
CHECKING THE TIME

1070
00:40:09,573 --> 00:40:10,508
He's…

1071
00:40:10,574 --> 00:40:12,109
WORRIED…

1072
00:40:12,176 --> 00:40:15,079
-Keep it up! You can do this!
-What's wrong?

1073
00:40:16,414 --> 00:40:17,782
The eggs are peeling?

1074
00:40:18,082 --> 00:40:19,550
TREMBLING

1075
00:40:19,617 --> 00:40:20,951
-Goodness.
-He's peeling it.

1076
00:40:21,018 --> 00:40:22,420
I want to peel them for him.

1077
00:40:22,486 --> 00:40:24,655
Wait, Jong-won is having a tough time
peeling the eggs!

1078
00:40:24,722 --> 00:40:25,990
-Is he?
-Yes.

1079
00:40:26,056 --> 00:40:29,527
-He boiled them for just four minutes!
-He needs to peel them pretty.

1080
00:40:29,593 --> 00:40:32,363
He boiled them exactly as long as needed!
What's going on?

1081
00:40:32,430 --> 00:40:34,031
It's not fully cooked,
so it's hard to peel.

1082
00:40:34,098 --> 00:40:36,700
-Yes.
-It's harder to peel soft-boiled eggs.

1083
00:40:36,767 --> 00:40:38,002
It's not easy to peel!

1084
00:40:38,068 --> 00:40:39,570
The eggs will come out in shreds!

1085
00:40:39,637 --> 00:40:41,439
Jong-won is in distress!

1086
00:40:41,505 --> 00:40:42,873
-It's tough to peel.
-It is.

1087
00:40:42,940 --> 00:40:45,042
-I want to help him.
-He puts it in and out of the water!

1088
00:40:45,109 --> 00:40:47,044
-He's in a crisis.
-It must be still hot.

1089
00:40:47,111 --> 00:40:49,547
-Three minutes left.
-This isn't good.

1090
00:40:50,014 --> 00:40:51,248
NAM-NO'S TURN TO TAKE THE LEAD!

1091
00:40:51,882 --> 00:40:55,219
PULL OUT ROASTED HASH BROWNS

1092
00:40:55,953 --> 00:40:57,721
-Is that burnt?
-No.

1093
00:40:57,788 --> 00:40:59,623
SALMON MENBOSHA IS OUT TOO

1094
00:40:59,690 --> 00:41:00,858
Where's my cream cheese?

1095
00:41:00,925 --> 00:41:02,026
-Cream cheese?
-Yes.

1096
00:41:02,092 --> 00:41:05,830
Chef Nam-no puts cream cheese
on top of the hash browns!

1097
00:41:05,896 --> 00:41:07,932
-That's Winestein.
-Winestein looks to be doing well.

1098
00:41:08,432 --> 00:41:09,467
HE'S NOT DONE YET!

1099
00:41:09,533 --> 00:41:12,536
-Is that caviar, Nam-no?
-He's adding details.

1100
00:41:12,603 --> 00:41:14,839
I've never seen Nam-no like this.

1101
00:41:14,905 --> 00:41:16,574
Caviar flowers.

1102
00:41:16,640 --> 00:41:18,776
He looks like a genius.

1103
00:41:18,843 --> 00:41:20,444
-His hands tremble.
-Try it.

1104
00:41:20,511 --> 00:41:21,545
-May I eat it?
-Yes.

1105
00:41:21,612 --> 00:41:23,747
He gave me one to try!

1106
00:41:23,814 --> 00:41:25,082
With caviar on top.

1107
00:41:25,149 --> 00:41:28,619
Did he figure out
the intention of the order?

1108
00:41:29,086 --> 00:41:30,521
DID OUR NAM-NO FIGURE IT OUT?

1109
00:41:31,789 --> 00:41:32,790
Hey.

1110
00:41:32,857 --> 00:41:34,358
Will it pair well with wine?

1111
00:41:35,226 --> 00:41:36,560
He's a genius!

1112
00:41:37,127 --> 00:41:38,362
GLASSES CEREMONY

1113
00:41:38,863 --> 00:41:40,364
FIGURED IT OUT ON THE 70TH EPISODE

1114
00:41:40,431 --> 00:41:42,032
-I'm curious.
-How did you do this?

1115
00:41:42,433 --> 00:41:45,069
JONG-WON IS STILL FIGHTING THE EGGS

1116
00:41:45,135 --> 00:41:46,604
-The shell is stuck.
-Yes, it is.

1117
00:41:46,971 --> 00:41:49,206
IT'S ALREADY THE THIRD EGG

1118
00:41:49,874 --> 00:41:51,242
TURNS OFF THE WATER TO FOCUS

1119
00:41:51,675 --> 00:41:53,744
TRYING AGAIN WITH A RENEWED MIND

1120
00:41:54,411 --> 00:41:56,380
I'm sorry, but can someone help
with those eggs?

1121
00:41:56,747 --> 00:41:58,115
GETS UP

1122
00:41:58,182 --> 00:42:00,351
-What happened?
-He can't peel the eggs.

1123
00:42:00,417 --> 00:42:02,887
-It's taking forever.
-The eggs must be important.

1124
00:42:02,953 --> 00:42:04,321
-It's hard.
-It must be important.

1125
00:42:04,388 --> 00:42:06,423
-You have two minutes left.
-Why won't it work?

1126
00:42:06,991 --> 00:42:08,692
-Two minutes!
-Two minutes left.

1127
00:42:09,527 --> 00:42:10,661
FINISHED WITH 2 MINUTES LEFT!

1128
00:42:10,895 --> 00:42:14,632
6. TOP ASPARAGUS VELOUTÉ ON THE EGG

1129
00:42:14,698 --> 00:42:16,467
He's coating the egg with velouté.

1130
00:42:17,067 --> 00:42:18,369
COATING WITH THE SAUCE

1131
00:42:18,435 --> 00:42:20,204
I see. Just like that.

1132
00:42:21,071 --> 00:42:22,907
NAM-NO PEELS THE HOT SPRING EGGS TOO!

1133
00:42:23,474 --> 00:42:25,509
That's pretty much raw.

1134
00:42:25,576 --> 00:42:27,878
I think Nam-no's eggs are ruined.

1135
00:42:27,945 --> 00:42:29,713
It's too raw.
His hot spring eggs are ruined.

1136
00:42:29,780 --> 00:42:32,516
-Aren't those raw?
-Those are raw.

1137
00:42:32,583 --> 00:42:34,351
-They seem raw.
-They're raw.

1138
00:42:34,418 --> 00:42:36,353
BUT THE GENIUS HAS A PLAN

1139
00:42:36,420 --> 00:42:37,621
He said it was for the sauce.

1140
00:42:37,688 --> 00:42:39,189
-The eggs?
-That's the sauce?

1141
00:42:39,256 --> 00:42:42,393
-That's the sauce.
-He's adding hot oil.

1142
00:42:42,459 --> 00:42:44,194
I wonder what this is like.

1143
00:42:44,261 --> 00:42:47,765
COOK WHILE STIRRING THE POT!

1144
00:42:47,831 --> 00:42:50,367
-One minute!
-One minute left!

1145
00:42:50,434 --> 00:42:51,435
-One minute!
-One minute.

1146
00:42:52,136 --> 00:42:53,971
JONG-WON USES CAVIAR TOO!

1147
00:42:54,038 --> 00:42:55,940
His hands are trembling.

1148
00:42:56,006 --> 00:42:57,107
They're trembling violently.

1149
00:42:58,475 --> 00:43:00,878
One minute left! One minute.

1150
00:43:01,412 --> 00:43:04,248
Jong-won made lots of shapes.

1151
00:43:04,315 --> 00:43:05,649
That egg is really cute.

1152
00:43:05,716 --> 00:43:07,952
-It's pretty.
-That egg.

1153
00:43:08,018 --> 00:43:09,420
-Whoa.
-His hands are trembling.

1154
00:43:09,486 --> 00:43:12,590
We haven't seen his hands tremble
in a long time.

1155
00:43:12,656 --> 00:43:14,325
Jong-won's hands tremble!

1156
00:43:14,391 --> 00:43:16,827
-Jong-won feels anxious too! 35 seconds!
-Can they finish?

1157
00:43:16,894 --> 00:43:18,963
-Thirty-five seconds!
-That egg is really pretty.

1158
00:43:19,029 --> 00:43:21,332
-How pretty!
-Thirty seconds.

1159
00:43:21,398 --> 00:43:25,736
It's as if Yuna is wearing a crown!

1160
00:43:25,970 --> 00:43:27,404
HOW PRETTY

1161
00:43:27,471 --> 00:43:29,940
-Thirty-five seconds.
-Thirty seconds.

1162
00:43:31,208 --> 00:43:33,978
PLATES THE HOT SPRING EGG SAUCE!

1163
00:43:34,044 --> 00:43:34,979
Fifteen seconds!

1164
00:43:35,045 --> 00:43:36,580
Nam-no puts his heart in!

1165
00:43:36,647 --> 00:43:38,916
He's also doing his best!

1166
00:43:38,983 --> 00:43:41,952
-Now. Nine. Eight. Seven.
-Nine. Eight. Seven.

1167
00:43:42,019 --> 00:43:44,054
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

1168
00:43:44,989 --> 00:43:47,524
PLATING THE SALMON STEAK

1169
00:43:48,058 --> 00:43:52,196
WITH ASPARAGUS ON TOP!

1170
00:43:52,262 --> 00:43:54,198
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

1171
00:43:54,264 --> 00:43:55,833
Jong-won is done!

1172
00:43:55,899 --> 00:43:58,869
Finish up, Nam-no!

1173
00:43:58,936 --> 00:44:02,039
He's done. Nam-no is done too.

1174
00:44:02,106 --> 00:44:02,940
AMAZED

1175
00:44:03,007 --> 00:44:05,142
-Fifteen minutes is so short.
-It really is.

1176
00:44:05,209 --> 00:44:07,978
HIGH QUALITY DISHES
MADE IN JUST 15 MINUTES

1177
00:44:08,045 --> 00:44:09,913
Don't you need the asparagus?

1178
00:44:09,980 --> 00:44:11,949
Right.

1179
00:44:12,016 --> 00:44:12,983
-I see.
-Asparagus.

1180
00:44:13,050 --> 00:44:14,818
I couldn't use these.

1181
00:44:14,885 --> 00:44:17,988
-Just serve them like this.
-Serve them.

1182
00:44:18,055 --> 00:44:20,557
-Serve them.
-Serve them in the frying pan!

1183
00:44:20,624 --> 00:44:23,060
Our rule is that
you serve them in the frying pan!

1184
00:44:23,127 --> 00:44:25,029
He finished making these, anyway.

1185
00:44:25,095 --> 00:44:27,831
-So he's allowed to serve them.
-He figured out the intention,

1186
00:44:28,332 --> 00:44:29,900
but he forgot to serve them.

1187
00:44:30,501 --> 00:44:32,569
Gosh, that was tough.

1188
00:44:32,636 --> 00:44:34,471
-They look pretty.
-They're both pretty.

1189
00:44:34,538 --> 00:44:36,273
TEMPTING PRESENTATIONS

1190
00:44:38,509 --> 00:44:39,743
They're pretty.

1191
00:44:39,810 --> 00:44:43,714
Both dishes were finished for Woo-rim.

1192
00:44:43,781 --> 00:44:45,215
Thank you.

1193
00:44:45,282 --> 00:44:47,985
Chef Jong-won finished first.

1194
00:44:48,052 --> 00:44:51,422
Kim Yuna! Won't Yuna Fall for This?

1195
00:44:52,656 --> 00:44:56,093
SALMON STEAK WITH ASPARAGUS

1196
00:44:56,727 --> 00:44:59,730
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
KIM YUNA! WON'T YUNA FALL FOR THIS?

1197
00:44:59,797 --> 00:45:01,532
It looks so pretty,

1198
00:45:01,598 --> 00:45:03,367
so I can't just eat it right away.

1199
00:45:03,434 --> 00:45:06,770
Just looking at the dish, it looks
like it was made elegantly in the kitchen.

1200
00:45:06,837 --> 00:45:09,006
We'll start with the egg dish.

1201
00:45:09,073 --> 00:45:10,641
First, you had two types of caviar.

1202
00:45:10,708 --> 00:45:13,143
<i>Beluga and Osetra.</i>

1203
00:45:13,210 --> 00:45:14,611
I served the first with a cold dish.

1204
00:45:14,678 --> 00:45:16,780
Please pop the egg
and enjoy them together.

1205
00:45:16,847 --> 00:45:18,615
All right.

1206
00:45:18,682 --> 00:45:20,617
Jung-hwan,
why don't you pour him some wine?

1207
00:45:20,884 --> 00:45:22,352
PREPARED WINE FOR THE TOPIC

1208
00:45:22,419 --> 00:45:23,587
That looks good.

1209
00:45:23,654 --> 00:45:26,623
Woo-rim is deep into wine right now.

1210
00:45:26,690 --> 00:45:29,460
That's nice. All right.

1211
00:45:29,526 --> 00:45:32,596
He has experience. He's a veteran now.

1212
00:45:32,663 --> 00:45:34,898
So I eat the caviar first?

1213
00:45:34,965 --> 00:45:36,400
Take the spoon with caviar

1214
00:45:36,467 --> 00:45:37,634
and pop the egg with it.

1215
00:45:37,701 --> 00:45:39,803
-I see. With it.
-With that spoon.

1216
00:45:39,870 --> 00:45:41,238
-In the ring?
-Like that?

1217
00:45:41,305 --> 00:45:42,740
Pour it on top. Yes.

1218
00:45:42,806 --> 00:45:45,309
THE EGG SPLITS SMOOTHLY

1219
00:45:45,375 --> 00:45:46,710
-Caviar.
-It's soft-boiled.

1220
00:45:46,777 --> 00:45:49,780
The texture is extraordinary.

1221
00:45:49,847 --> 00:45:52,683
-Egg yolk and caviar go so well together.
-They do.

1222
00:45:52,750 --> 00:45:54,184
I'll use that tip later.

1223
00:45:54,251 --> 00:45:55,352
The combination.

1224
00:45:56,186 --> 00:45:57,855
LOTS OF CAVIAR WITH EGG COVERED IN VELOUTÉ

1225
00:45:57,921 --> 00:46:01,091
He calculated everything exactly
to make that egg.

1226
00:46:05,596 --> 00:46:08,799
Egg, asparagus velouté,

1227
00:46:08,866 --> 00:46:11,235
and even caviar. Yes.

1228
00:46:11,301 --> 00:46:12,302
Does it taste velvety?

1229
00:46:12,369 --> 00:46:15,339
-Velvety velouté?
-Does it taste velvety?

1230
00:46:15,405 --> 00:46:19,143
Most people talk immediately,
but you aren't saying anything.

1231
00:46:19,209 --> 00:46:20,978
I had to savor it for a while

1232
00:46:21,044 --> 00:46:23,914
because caviar pops
and leaves a taste later on.

1233
00:46:23,981 --> 00:46:27,484
So I waited
until I could feel the saltiness.

1234
00:46:27,551 --> 00:46:29,620
-You take time with caviar.
-You know how to eat it.

1235
00:46:29,686 --> 00:46:32,756
And now, I need a sip of wine.

1236
00:46:32,823 --> 00:46:34,224
So it makes you crave wine?

1237
00:46:34,291 --> 00:46:35,125
DOES HE CRAVE IT?

1238
00:46:35,893 --> 00:46:37,094
The wine looks so befitting of you.

1239
00:46:37,828 --> 00:46:40,464
AN ELEGANT SIP OF WINE

1240
00:46:42,900 --> 00:46:45,235
-First of all, he needs to crave wine.
-Right.

1241
00:46:45,302 --> 00:46:48,038
I completely understand
what he said about egg yolks

1242
00:46:48,105 --> 00:46:49,840
going very well with caviar.

1243
00:46:49,907 --> 00:46:51,942
The egg was soft-boiled,

1244
00:46:52,009 --> 00:46:55,212
so the creamy texture mixes with caviar.

1245
00:46:55,279 --> 00:46:57,948
The texture becomes even richer.

1246
00:46:58,015 --> 00:47:02,186
Also, when it starts to get boring,
this crispy bread jumps in.

1247
00:47:02,252 --> 00:47:03,187
-It adds fun.
-Yes.

1248
00:47:03,253 --> 00:47:07,324
My wife doesn't like anything
overly salty or rich,

1249
00:47:07,391 --> 00:47:10,427
and I think he found the perfect balance.

1250
00:47:10,494 --> 00:47:13,764
This would be a perfect appetizer
before the main dish.

1251
00:47:13,831 --> 00:47:15,165
A PERFECT APPETITE STIMULATOR

1252
00:47:15,232 --> 00:47:18,702
I'm not the type who reacts loudly,

1253
00:47:18,769 --> 00:47:21,672
-but I really am enjoying it.
-That suits you.

1254
00:47:21,738 --> 00:47:23,807
You shouldn't go, "Man,"
while drinking wine.

1255
00:47:23,874 --> 00:47:24,808
That's Kangnam's thing.

1256
00:47:24,875 --> 00:47:26,543
I thought of something I can do.

1257
00:47:26,610 --> 00:47:27,744
Yes? What is it?

1258
00:47:27,811 --> 00:47:30,781
If you're reminded of a good song,
you can sing us one.

1259
00:47:30,848 --> 00:47:32,916
-He can use his expertise.
-Yes.

1260
00:47:33,584 --> 00:47:34,952
ANTICIPATION

1261
00:47:35,652 --> 00:47:36,486
INHALING

1262
00:47:36,553 --> 00:47:37,454
He's ready.

1263
00:47:37,521 --> 00:47:40,157
GROWL

1264
00:47:41,525 --> 00:47:42,960
EXTREMELY LOW GROWL

1265
00:47:44,962 --> 00:47:45,796
That suits him.

1266
00:47:45,996 --> 00:47:47,331
TREMBLE

1267
00:47:47,464 --> 00:47:49,066
STAYING IN CHARACTER

1268
00:47:49,132 --> 00:47:51,501
-It suits you.
-He can do that, thanks to his low voice.

1269
00:47:51,568 --> 00:47:54,004
We were all expecting a song.

1270
00:47:54,071 --> 00:47:56,306
That was the reaction I thought of.

1271
00:47:56,373 --> 00:47:58,475
It would've been awful if we did that.

1272
00:47:58,542 --> 00:48:00,277
-It won't make it on air.
-That was cool.

1273
00:48:00,344 --> 00:48:02,579
I've eaten every bit of precious caviar.

1274
00:48:03,146 --> 00:48:04,648
He eats everything.

1275
00:48:05,115 --> 00:48:07,150
FIRST DISH, CLEARED

1276
00:48:07,217 --> 00:48:09,186
-He's done with this one.
-Yes.

1277
00:48:09,253 --> 00:48:10,921
I loved that as the appetizer.

1278
00:48:10,988 --> 00:48:13,056
I actually have the sauce right here.

1279
00:48:13,123 --> 00:48:15,092
May I serve it, Chef Nam-no?

1280
00:48:15,158 --> 00:48:16,827
I thought it didn't come with sauce.

1281
00:48:16,894 --> 00:48:18,161
Did you plan to serve it later?

1282
00:48:18,228 --> 00:48:21,999
-You need permission from Nam-no.
-Just this once.

1283
00:48:22,065 --> 00:48:23,867
-Nam-no?
-If he gives me a bite.

1284
00:48:24,101 --> 00:48:25,435
A VERY NAM-NO-LIKE SUGGESTION

1285
00:48:25,502 --> 00:48:26,336
This one.

1286
00:48:26,403 --> 00:48:28,772
Put the sauce in Nam-no's mouth first.

1287
00:48:28,839 --> 00:48:30,674
-Nam-no will try the sauce first.
-How cute.

1288
00:48:30,741 --> 00:48:32,409
-He loves to eat.
-Yes.

1289
00:48:32,476 --> 00:48:34,578
Will he say no if it's good?

1290
00:48:34,645 --> 00:48:37,281
-It must be good.
-Is it good?

1291
00:48:37,481 --> 00:48:38,815
LINGERING FLAVOR…

1292
00:48:38,882 --> 00:48:40,484
Did you finish it but forget to serve it?

1293
00:48:40,550 --> 00:48:43,287
I need to add caviar
right before he eats it,

1294
00:48:43,353 --> 00:48:45,489
cold caviar into warm sauce.

1295
00:48:45,555 --> 00:48:47,024
Oh, I see.

1296
00:48:47,090 --> 00:48:49,026
That's how you're supposed
to make caviar sauce.

1297
00:48:49,092 --> 00:48:50,861
Because if you cook caviar with it,

1298
00:48:50,928 --> 00:48:54,064
it'll turn hard when it's fully cooked.

1299
00:48:54,131 --> 00:48:56,199
-It doesn't get tough, but hard.
-So you make it right before it's eaten.

1300
00:48:56,266 --> 00:48:57,100
Like sailfin sandfish.

1301
00:48:57,167 --> 00:49:00,137
-I kept this caviar cold.
-He kept it cold.

1302
00:49:00,203 --> 00:49:01,605
This is Osetra caviar.

1303
00:49:02,706 --> 00:49:05,242
-It's important to use a lot.
-Whoa.

1304
00:49:05,309 --> 00:49:07,077
-Everything?
-The entire thing?

1305
00:49:07,144 --> 00:49:08,812
Man, that's crazy awesome.

1306
00:49:08,879 --> 00:49:11,081
-He used it all.
-He had to pour it last minute.

1307
00:49:11,148 --> 00:49:12,015
Caviar beurre blanc.

1308
00:49:12,082 --> 00:49:13,216
He's circling the salmon.

1309
00:49:13,283 --> 00:49:14,751
That'll be delicious no matter what.

1310
00:49:14,818 --> 00:49:17,754
This is a warm dish.

1311
00:49:17,821 --> 00:49:19,790
First, dip the asparagus in the sauce.

1312
00:49:20,490 --> 00:49:21,825
Then I'll try this first.

1313
00:49:22,759 --> 00:49:26,396
Even the bottoms of the asparagus
were peeled off.

1314
00:49:28,198 --> 00:49:29,099
CRUNCHY

1315
00:49:29,166 --> 00:49:31,668
Can asparagus turn into…

1316
00:49:32,536 --> 00:49:34,104
-He looks surprised.
-…a bar snack?

1317
00:49:34,171 --> 00:49:35,405
NODS

1318
00:49:35,472 --> 00:49:37,374
That's his face
when something's really good.

1319
00:49:37,441 --> 00:49:39,009
-Is that so?
-Yes.

1320
00:49:39,076 --> 00:49:40,844
The sauce is heavenly.

1321
00:49:40,911 --> 00:49:42,479
HAPPY, SAD

1322
00:49:42,546 --> 00:49:45,315
-The sauce.
-That sauce really was important.

1323
00:49:45,382 --> 00:49:47,017
French is all about the sauce.

1324
00:49:47,084 --> 00:49:48,318
Why is this sauce so good?

1325
00:49:48,385 --> 00:49:50,787
The sauce itself is very simple.
It's called beurre blanc.

1326
00:49:50,854 --> 00:49:53,357
It's one of the basic
and classic French sauces.

1327
00:49:53,423 --> 00:49:56,259
It's usually made by boiling shallots
and ground pepper in wine.

1328
00:49:56,326 --> 00:49:58,395
But I used an onion instead of shallots.

1329
00:49:58,462 --> 00:50:01,565
After it boils down, you can add cream,
but I added butter

1330
00:50:01,631 --> 00:50:03,400
and emulsified it smoothly.

1331
00:50:03,467 --> 00:50:04,801
-It sounds good.
-Butter and wine.

1332
00:50:04,868 --> 00:50:07,070
I can finish that wine
with this sauce alone.

1333
00:50:07,137 --> 00:50:08,772
-It's so good.
-It's that good?

1334
00:50:08,839 --> 00:50:10,040
Try the salmon now.

1335
00:50:10,107 --> 00:50:11,975
-Next, the salmon.
-That sound.

1336
00:50:12,042 --> 00:50:13,744
-Sounds crunchy.
-Wow.

1337
00:50:13,810 --> 00:50:16,613
-Crackle, crackle.
-The crispy sound.

1338
00:50:16,680 --> 00:50:18,348
The bread is toasted perfectly.

1339
00:50:18,415 --> 00:50:20,884
My wife and I also eat fish often.

1340
00:50:22,052 --> 00:50:23,820
She would love this.

1341
00:50:24,521 --> 00:50:26,656
-Let me scoop up lots of sauce.
-Lots of sauce.

1342
00:50:26,723 --> 00:50:28,992
His mouth waters as he gets it ready.

1343
00:50:29,626 --> 00:50:31,862
A BITE WITH LOTS OF SAUCE

1344
00:50:33,563 --> 00:50:35,165
SATISFIED NOD

1345
00:50:35,232 --> 00:50:37,534
-Everything must go well.
-It has to be good.

1346
00:50:37,601 --> 00:50:39,569
Will Yuna fall for it?

1347
00:50:39,636 --> 00:50:41,505
-With the bread…
-Do you like the texture?

1348
00:50:41,571 --> 00:50:43,673
-…the texture is so nice.
-Is it different?

1349
00:50:43,740 --> 00:50:47,644
The bread is crispy,
while the sauce comes in from the bottom.

1350
00:50:47,711 --> 00:50:49,413
How can I put this?

1351
00:50:49,479 --> 00:50:51,214
I'm in a quartet, right?

1352
00:50:51,281 --> 00:50:55,952
Just like me, the sauce works as the bass
and makes the foundation.

1353
00:50:56,019 --> 00:50:58,588
Then this crispy texture

1354
00:50:58,655 --> 00:51:02,626
fills up the top range like a tenor.

1355
00:51:02,692 --> 00:51:06,296
Lastly, the salmon seizes
the middle range.

1356
00:51:06,363 --> 00:51:08,698
So you're that sauce?

1357
00:51:08,765 --> 00:51:09,599
Yes.

1358
00:51:09,666 --> 00:51:11,001
-The best part?
-Yes.

1359
00:51:11,234 --> 00:51:12,069
PLEASED

1360
00:51:12,135 --> 00:51:15,872
-I'm the lowest range, so…
-You have the most delicious voice?

1361
00:51:15,939 --> 00:51:18,308
Now, he turns it into a quartet.

1362
00:51:19,342 --> 00:51:20,510
Wow.

1363
00:51:20,577 --> 00:51:21,645
All together.

1364
00:51:21,711 --> 00:51:23,847
-What's the balance like?
-It must be good.

1365
00:51:23,914 --> 00:51:26,583
The harmony is insane.

1366
00:51:27,717 --> 00:51:29,686
-The sauce is absolutely delicious.
-The sauce.

1367
00:51:29,753 --> 00:51:32,556
-It must be the winning move.
-That's caviar for you.

1368
00:51:32,622 --> 00:51:35,725
Nam-no's dish is turning cold.

1369
00:51:35,792 --> 00:51:37,160
-Oh, no.
-No.

1370
00:51:37,227 --> 00:51:38,862
Next, Nam-no's dish.

1371
00:51:38,929 --> 00:51:41,031
-Winestein.
-Winestein.

1372
00:51:41,264 --> 00:51:43,467
HASH BROWNS TOPPED WITH CAVIAR

1373
00:51:43,533 --> 00:51:45,168
AND THE FRENCH MENBOSHA

1374
00:51:45,902 --> 00:51:48,271
WITH SOFT HOT SPRING EGG SAUCE

1375
00:51:49,573 --> 00:51:52,909
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S WINESTEIN

1376
00:51:52,976 --> 00:51:55,112
First of all, it's really pretty.

1377
00:51:55,178 --> 00:51:58,482
-Do you like the presentation?
-I can't believe he made it in 15 minutes.

1378
00:51:58,548 --> 00:52:00,117
It looks good.

1379
00:52:00,183 --> 00:52:03,620
-Asparagus and the sauce.
-Together?

1380
00:52:03,687 --> 00:52:07,624
Everything I used goes well with caviar.
Eggs and potatoes.

1381
00:52:07,691 --> 00:52:08,758
-Eggs, potatoes.
-And bread.

1382
00:52:08,825 --> 00:52:10,660
-This single bite is so rich.
-They were potatoes?

1383
00:52:12,395 --> 00:52:13,697
WILL IT TASTE AS RICH?

1384
00:52:18,034 --> 00:52:19,369
Mmm.

1385
00:52:19,736 --> 00:52:20,704
A BIT NERVOUS

1386
00:52:20,770 --> 00:52:22,139
The moment I had it,

1387
00:52:22,205 --> 00:52:24,274
I could figure out Chef Nam-no's style.

1388
00:52:25,242 --> 00:52:27,010
-Is it too salty?
-What do you mean by that?

1389
00:52:27,077 --> 00:52:29,980
It's crunchy, yet oily on the inside.

1390
00:52:30,046 --> 00:52:33,116
There's some sort of collaboration
going on.

1391
00:52:33,183 --> 00:52:35,852
-The buttery flavor of fat?
-A buttery fat flavor?

1392
00:52:35,919 --> 00:52:36,786
-The fat.
-The fat.

1393
00:52:36,853 --> 00:52:37,787
THIS?

1394
00:52:37,854 --> 00:52:41,625
It's the greasiness and crispiness
of hash browns,

1395
00:52:41,691 --> 00:52:44,528
but this asparagus
helps you eat a little healthy.

1396
00:52:44,594 --> 00:52:46,329
-I see.
-It's that combination.

1397
00:52:46,396 --> 00:52:47,964
I can feel the egg sauce's texture too.

1398
00:52:48,031 --> 00:52:49,166
AND THE FLUFFY EGG SAUCE!

1399
00:52:49,733 --> 00:52:52,035
-That salmon.
-Yes, that one.

1400
00:52:52,102 --> 00:52:54,271
-He called it <i>menbosha</i>.
-Yes, it's <i>menbosha</i>.

1401
00:52:54,337 --> 00:52:56,206
It does look like <i>menbosha </i>when it's cut.

1402
00:52:57,107 --> 00:52:58,542
The French <i>menbosha</i>.

1403
00:52:58,608 --> 00:53:01,044
I haven't had <i>menbosha </i>too often.

1404
00:53:01,111 --> 00:53:04,181
-It looks really good.
-He said it'd go well with white wine.

1405
00:53:05,248 --> 00:53:08,151
A BIG BITE

1406
00:53:08,585 --> 00:53:10,353
Does it go well with wine?

1407
00:53:10,420 --> 00:53:12,088
Nam-no looks anxious.

1408
00:53:12,622 --> 00:53:13,857
WIGGLING LIPS

1409
00:53:13,924 --> 00:53:15,992
-It must be good.
-A faint smile.

1410
00:53:16,059 --> 00:53:19,496
The salmon flavor
mixes very well with the bread.

1411
00:53:19,563 --> 00:53:21,064
I think I can share

1412
00:53:21,131 --> 00:53:25,435
the entire dish with my wife,
and it'd be enough for us.

1413
00:53:25,502 --> 00:53:28,104
When I had the bread
and the salmon together,

1414
00:53:28,972 --> 00:53:32,075
it felt really full in my mouth.

1415
00:53:32,142 --> 00:53:33,710
-I liked it.
-That's exactly it.

1416
00:53:33,777 --> 00:53:35,845
He says that's exactly it.

1417
00:53:35,912 --> 00:53:38,748
You reviewed Chef Jong-won's dish
with a sound,

1418
00:53:38,815 --> 00:53:39,916
so do one for Nam-no.

1419
00:53:39,983 --> 00:53:41,751
-After he's done.
-Why does he do that?

1420
00:53:41,818 --> 00:53:43,853
-Stop putting pressure on him.
-Right?

1421
00:53:43,920 --> 00:53:45,922
We were going to ask him after he's done.

1422
00:53:45,989 --> 00:53:47,691
People become silly as they age.

1423
00:53:47,757 --> 00:53:49,292
-You get ahead of yourself.
-Of course.

1424
00:53:49,359 --> 00:53:52,796
Our Forestella member
is feeling the inspiration.

1425
00:53:52,862 --> 00:53:54,664
There's so much pressure.

1426
00:53:54,998 --> 00:53:57,100
WHY IS SUNG-JUN MOVED?

1427
00:53:57,667 --> 00:54:01,705
-It fills you up with richness.
-Yes, the richness hits me really hard.

1428
00:54:01,771 --> 00:54:05,342
-Being rich, this light white wine…
-That's why.

1429
00:54:05,408 --> 00:54:06,343
…pairs perfectly.

1430
00:54:06,509 --> 00:54:07,410
GOOD ONE

1431
00:54:08,578 --> 00:54:09,679
RICH

1432
00:54:09,746 --> 00:54:13,049
-Kangnam, why don't you try it too?
-Sure.

1433
00:54:13,116 --> 00:54:15,352
-I'm really curious about this salmon.
-I see.

1434
00:54:15,418 --> 00:54:17,020
See how smooth it is.

1435
00:54:17,087 --> 00:54:18,321
Try it with the sauce.

1436
00:54:18,388 --> 00:54:19,789
A BITE OF SALMON STEAK AND SAUCE

1437
00:54:22,425 --> 00:54:24,961
-The sauce is so good.
-It is, isn't it?

1438
00:54:25,028 --> 00:54:26,730
-Nam, the moment you put it in…
-Yes?

1439
00:54:26,796 --> 00:54:27,897
SURPRISED?

1440
00:54:27,964 --> 00:54:30,033
-You still do that?
-At least, chew it a bit.

1441
00:54:30,100 --> 00:54:32,869
-Please do it seriously.
-Give us a review.

1442
00:54:32,936 --> 00:54:35,171
-Be serious.
-We're filming everything.

1443
00:54:35,238 --> 00:54:37,841
I'll film you and see
if you talk before you eat it.

1444
00:54:37,907 --> 00:54:39,542
Put it in and chew for a bit.

1445
00:54:40,977 --> 00:54:41,811
Okay.

1446
00:54:41,878 --> 00:54:44,381
The texture of the asparagus is like art.

1447
00:54:45,348 --> 00:54:47,951
And when it meets this sauce,

1448
00:54:48,018 --> 00:54:49,819
the asparagus flavor skyrockets-<i>masho</i>.

1449
00:54:49,886 --> 00:54:51,288
"Skyrockets-<i>masho</i>"?

1450
00:54:51,554 --> 00:54:54,157
MIXING UP KOREAN AND JAPANESE

1451
00:54:54,224 --> 00:54:55,925
He forgot the Korean language.

1452
00:54:55,992 --> 00:54:57,160
I was in Japan yesterday.

1453
00:54:57,227 --> 00:55:00,463
Next, Chef Nam-no's Winestein.

1454
00:55:00,530 --> 00:55:02,132
-Now, this…
-How do I eat this?

1455
00:55:02,198 --> 00:55:03,767
Can you react to this one

1456
00:55:03,833 --> 00:55:05,802
in the classic variety show style?

1457
00:55:05,869 --> 00:55:06,936
Like before?

1458
00:55:07,003 --> 00:55:09,639
-The variety show style is easier.
-The variety show style.

1459
00:55:09,706 --> 00:55:11,041
A variety show reaction.

1460
00:55:12,776 --> 00:55:13,877
Whoa, it's so good.

1461
00:55:14,878 --> 00:55:16,980
VARIETY SHOW 101

1462
00:55:17,414 --> 00:55:19,282
THE PROFESSIONAL SHOWMAN SURE IS DIFFERENT

1463
00:55:19,816 --> 00:55:21,718
AMAZED

1464
00:55:21,785 --> 00:55:23,386
-That's crazy.
-That's what I'm talking about.

1465
00:55:23,453 --> 00:55:24,688
That's the best I could do.

1466
00:55:24,754 --> 00:55:27,290
I racked my brains for that just now.

1467
00:55:27,357 --> 00:55:28,658
Next, the serious review.

1468
00:55:28,725 --> 00:55:30,026
Give us the real review.

1469
00:55:30,093 --> 00:55:31,261
-The actual review.
-Yes.

1470
00:55:31,328 --> 00:55:33,063
-You did the show.
-He's a genius.

1471
00:55:33,129 --> 00:55:34,764
Chew it for a while.

1472
00:55:34,831 --> 00:55:36,132
"Chew it for a while."

1473
00:55:36,199 --> 00:55:37,434
Yes, the sauce.

1474
00:55:37,500 --> 00:55:38,968
It's an egg sauce.

1475
00:55:39,903 --> 00:55:41,004
CLAPPING

1476
00:55:41,071 --> 00:55:42,439
He's clapping.

1477
00:55:42,505 --> 00:55:45,375
-It has the <i>menbosha</i> texture.
-It does?

1478
00:55:45,442 --> 00:55:47,677
But it tastes like a different dish.
It's amazing.

1479
00:55:47,744 --> 00:55:48,578
Is this salmon?

1480
00:55:48,645 --> 00:55:49,679
It is.

1481
00:55:50,313 --> 00:55:51,815
When are you opening your restaurant?

1482
00:55:51,881 --> 00:55:53,350
-Soon, right?
-In five days.

1483
00:55:53,416 --> 00:55:54,751
-In five days?
-That's so soon.

1484
00:55:54,818 --> 00:55:56,052
It'll be a huge hit.

1485
00:55:56,119 --> 00:55:58,054
It's so good. I'm in shock.

1486
00:55:58,121 --> 00:56:00,390
But Woo-rim must make the decision.

1487
00:56:00,457 --> 00:56:02,125
<i>Press one to pick Jong-won</i>

1488
00:56:02,959 --> 00:56:04,327
<i>and two to pick Nam-no.</i>

1489
00:56:05,128 --> 00:56:07,597
Which one did he choose?

1490
00:56:07,664 --> 00:56:09,432
Let's find out the result!

1491
00:56:09,499 --> 00:56:10,367
Show us!

1492
00:56:10,967 --> 00:56:13,770
<i>Why did you come into my life?</i>

1493
00:56:13,837 --> 00:56:16,172
-Oh, man. You're in a pickle.
-Temptation of Husband.

1494
00:56:16,239 --> 00:56:19,843
Will Jong-won take his fourth win in a row

1495
00:56:19,909 --> 00:56:22,846
and break the record
for the longest winning streak?

1496
00:56:22,912 --> 00:56:26,883
Or will Nam-no get his revenge on Jong-won

1497
00:56:26,950 --> 00:56:29,452
and win a star
for the first time in a while?

1498
00:56:29,519 --> 00:56:32,255
Which one did Woo-rim choose?

1499
00:56:32,889 --> 00:56:35,458
Which dish will he use to tempt his wife?

1500
00:56:35,525 --> 00:56:36,459
Who won?

1501
00:56:36,526 --> 00:56:38,161
SON JONG-WON WINS

1502
00:56:38,495 --> 00:56:39,863
KIM YUNA! WON'T YUNA FALL FOR THIS? WINS

1503
00:56:39,929 --> 00:56:40,830
Jong-won wins.

1504
00:56:41,398 --> 00:56:43,833
-Good work. I thought you'd win.
-Jong-won wins four in a row!

1505
00:56:43,900 --> 00:56:46,369
-Four wins in a row.
-Yes.

1506
00:56:46,436 --> 00:56:49,139
If I were to consider just my taste,

1507
00:56:49,205 --> 00:56:51,608
I really loved Chef Nam-no's dish,

1508
00:56:51,674 --> 00:56:53,376
how rich it was.

1509
00:56:53,443 --> 00:56:55,111
But if I were to consider just my wife,

1510
00:56:55,178 --> 00:56:58,882
that sauce tasted both refreshing
and creamy at the same time,

1511
00:56:58,948 --> 00:57:00,950
yet it tasted light.

1512
00:57:01,017 --> 00:57:03,887
I thought she'd like that more.

1513
00:57:03,953 --> 00:57:05,522
Because he has to eat with her.

1514
00:57:05,588 --> 00:57:06,689
The sauce

1515
00:57:06,756 --> 00:57:07,857
was the biggest kick.

1516
00:57:08,191 --> 00:57:09,359
THANK YOU

1517
00:57:09,426 --> 00:57:12,729
I enjoyed both dishes a lot. Thank you.

1518
00:57:12,796 --> 00:57:14,063
I see.

1519
00:57:14,130 --> 00:57:16,666
This is Son Jong-won's
fourth victory in a row

1520
00:57:16,733 --> 00:57:18,234
and his eighth star,

1521
00:57:18,301 --> 00:57:20,170
sealing his place at the top.

1522
00:57:20,236 --> 00:57:21,438
That's insane. Eight stars?

1523
00:57:21,504 --> 00:57:24,974
Woo-rim chose Chef Jong-won's dish.

1524
00:57:25,542 --> 00:57:28,344
He now stands alone at number one
with eight stars!

1525
00:57:29,279 --> 00:57:31,114
-It was delicious.
-He can't be stopped.

1526
00:57:31,181 --> 00:57:35,218
<i>Let us begin the second cook-off</i>
<i>with ingredients from Woo-rim's fridge.</i>

1527
00:57:35,285 --> 00:57:37,220
Even the romantic, Choi Soo-jong,
would back down

1528
00:57:37,287 --> 00:57:39,556
before Chef Sam Kim, the romantic.

1529
00:57:39,622 --> 00:57:42,358
And the star hunter who's all fired up,

1530
00:57:42,425 --> 00:57:44,194
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

1531
00:57:44,260 --> 00:57:46,496
The husband is done tempting his wife.

1532
00:57:46,563 --> 00:57:48,598
It's now the couple's morning.

1533
00:57:48,665 --> 00:57:51,034
We took a look at your records,

1534
00:57:51,100 --> 00:57:53,036
and as of now,

1535
00:57:53,102 --> 00:57:55,705
Sam has won three times in a row
against Hyun-suk.

1536
00:57:55,772 --> 00:57:57,740
After hearing about the topic,

1537
00:57:57,807 --> 00:58:00,777
Chef Sam was sure
that he simply could not lose.

1538
00:58:00,844 --> 00:58:01,678
What do you mean?

1539
00:58:01,744 --> 00:58:03,413
I always make breakfast at home.

1540
00:58:03,480 --> 00:58:07,217
-I see.
-I've been doing it for almost 20 years.

1541
00:58:07,283 --> 00:58:09,252
-How sweet of him.
-So I'm very confident.

1542
00:58:09,319 --> 00:58:12,589
Hyun-suk, what was your breakfast today?

1543
00:58:12,655 --> 00:58:14,757
A chef always

1544
00:58:14,824 --> 00:58:16,259
skips his breakfast.

1545
00:58:18,194 --> 00:58:19,863
They don't eat breakfast.

1546
00:58:19,929 --> 00:58:22,866
Sam is a guy
who volunteers to be a romantic,

1547
00:58:22,932 --> 00:58:24,901
but I've lived my life not as a romantic

1548
00:58:24,968 --> 00:58:27,437
but as a man with strong work ethics
to provide for my family.

1549
00:58:27,871 --> 00:58:29,372
THE LIFE OF A BREADWINNER

1550
00:58:29,439 --> 00:58:31,007
-It's so sad.
-How sad.

1551
00:58:31,074 --> 00:58:33,977
Along with breakfasts from these chefs,

1552
00:58:34,043 --> 00:58:35,879
he's going to have some coffee.

1553
00:58:35,945 --> 00:58:38,581
And Woo-rim will make that coffee himself

1554
00:58:38,648 --> 00:58:41,117
-right in the studio.
-Really?

1555
00:58:41,184 --> 00:58:43,419
You even brought some equipment.

1556
00:58:43,486 --> 00:58:44,621
-I did.
-Right?

1557
00:58:44,687 --> 00:58:46,589
What are they going to make

1558
00:58:46,656 --> 00:58:48,825
for him to have with coffee?

1559
00:58:49,659 --> 00:58:51,728
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:
JJAJANG RAMYEON, SIRLOIN, OUTSIDE SKIRT

1560
00:58:51,794 --> 00:58:53,830
ASPARAGUS, WAFFLE, FISH CAKE,
FISH CAKE SOUP SAUCE, MILK, AND MORE

1561
00:58:53,897 --> 00:58:55,832
My dish is called…

1562
00:58:55,899 --> 00:58:57,066
Today, I'm

1563
00:58:57,634 --> 00:58:59,602
Choipagetti Cook.

1564
00:59:00,103 --> 00:59:00,970
SWOOSH

1565
00:59:02,205 --> 00:59:03,907
COPY AND PASTE

1566
00:59:04,507 --> 00:59:06,442
THE HUSBAND IS MOVED

1567
00:59:06,509 --> 00:59:08,811
Hyun-suk never changes.

1568
00:59:08,878 --> 00:59:09,846
That's Yuna's thing.

1569
00:59:09,913 --> 00:59:11,581
-You're right.
-Dance of Death.

1570
00:59:11,648 --> 00:59:13,616
-Yes, Dance of Death.
-That's what he's doing.

1571
00:59:13,683 --> 00:59:15,418
DANCE OF THE SHOW-OFF

1572
00:59:15,485 --> 00:59:16,986
I was wondering what that was.

1573
00:59:17,053 --> 00:59:18,922
-I thought he was unwell.
-Me too.

1574
00:59:18,988 --> 00:59:21,424
I thought,
"He must be having frozen shoulder again."

1575
00:59:21,791 --> 00:59:22,926
HE WELCOMES THE SLANDER

1576
00:59:22,992 --> 00:59:25,128
Today, I'm Choipagetti Cook.

1577
00:59:25,194 --> 00:59:26,729
When do you think is the perfect time

1578
00:59:26,796 --> 00:59:28,331
to eat <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>?

1579
00:59:28,398 --> 00:59:29,599
It's breakfast.

1580
00:59:29,666 --> 00:59:31,768
You'll get bloated
if you eat it for dinner.

1581
00:59:31,834 --> 00:59:33,803
-So have it as breakfast…
-Breakfast?

1582
00:59:33,870 --> 00:59:34,837
…then it doesn't matter.

1583
00:59:34,904 --> 00:59:37,473
And I'll also be making

1584
00:59:37,540 --> 00:59:41,511
waffles with your favorite, outside skirt.

1585
00:59:41,578 --> 00:59:43,980
I'm going to cook it
with Kang-rok's braising sauce

1586
00:59:44,047 --> 00:59:47,150
and make a rich, Korean-style breakfast.

1587
00:59:47,216 --> 00:59:48,952
Isn't that too much for breakfast?

1588
00:59:49,018 --> 00:59:50,219
It isn't.

1589
00:59:50,286 --> 00:59:52,488
I'll add one pinch of sugar

1590
00:59:52,555 --> 00:59:54,857
to make the <i>ramyeon</i>
taste like <i>jjajangmyeon </i>at a hotel.

1591
00:59:54,924 --> 00:59:57,360
-Will it taste fancy?
-<i>Jjajangmyeon </i>at a hotel?

1592
00:59:58,294 --> 01:00:02,365
CHEF SAM'S INGREDIENTS: SMOKED DUCK,
BREAD, ASPARAGUS, LEMON JUICE

1593
01:00:02,432 --> 01:00:04,601
What are you making, Chef Sam?

1594
01:00:04,667 --> 01:00:07,470
The dish I'll make is…

1595
01:00:08,605 --> 01:00:09,973
Bun Massive Taste.

1596
01:00:10,039 --> 01:00:11,474
AWKWARDNESS +100

1597
01:00:11,541 --> 01:00:12,609
Bun Massive Taste.

1598
01:00:13,876 --> 01:00:15,745
-What did he just do?
-Bun Massive Taste.

1599
01:00:15,812 --> 01:00:17,480
IT'S TOO TOUGH FOR CHEF SAINT

1600
01:00:17,547 --> 01:00:19,048
-Bun Massive Taste.
-Bun Massive Taste.

1601
01:00:19,115 --> 01:00:22,151
-Let's do it again, do it just like him.
-Bun Massive Taste.

1602
01:00:22,218 --> 01:00:23,886
<i>Mamacita</i>

1603
01:00:24,587 --> 01:00:25,922
Bun Massive Taste.

1604
01:00:25,989 --> 01:00:27,490
Why are you scratching your neck?

1605
01:00:27,557 --> 01:00:29,692
Do you have to do the gesture
with your head?

1606
01:00:29,759 --> 01:00:32,428
-Thank you.
-What's the dish like?

1607
01:00:32,495 --> 01:00:33,763
It's a way for you to have

1608
01:00:33,830 --> 01:00:35,598
a variety of nutrients in the morning.

1609
01:00:35,665 --> 01:00:39,902
I'm going to use protein, carbs,
and even vegetables.

1610
01:00:39,969 --> 01:00:41,537
I'll make hollandaise sauce

1611
01:00:41,604 --> 01:00:43,539
and top it with asparagus
and poached eggs.

1612
01:00:43,606 --> 01:00:45,908
Then I'll cook the duck
until crispy like bacon

1613
01:00:45,975 --> 01:00:48,244
and top it on an onion.

1614
01:00:48,311 --> 01:00:51,948
Also, bread is better with an Americano
when it's a bit sweeter.

1615
01:00:52,015 --> 01:00:53,783
So I'll make a garlic butter toast.

1616
01:00:53,850 --> 01:00:55,685
-Garlic bread.
-That sounds good.

1617
01:00:55,752 --> 01:00:59,055
My wife loves anything
that's made with butter.

1618
01:00:59,622 --> 01:01:01,858
-She'd love that.
-I see. That sounds great.

1619
01:01:01,924 --> 01:01:03,626
And now, let us begin

1620
01:01:03,693 --> 01:01:06,696
the cook-off for Woo-rim,
Couple's Breakfast.

1621
01:01:06,763 --> 01:01:10,867
The man who has been making breakfast
for his wife for over 20 years,

1622
01:01:10,933 --> 01:01:12,769
the romantic Chef Sam Kim.

1623
01:01:12,835 --> 01:01:15,705
The man who has been sprinkling salt
for his family for over 30 years,

1624
01:01:15,772 --> 01:01:19,275
the man with a work ethic,
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

1625
01:01:19,342 --> 01:01:20,677
Which chef will present

1626
01:01:20,743 --> 01:01:23,680
the best breakfast to Woo-rim and Yuna?

1627
01:01:23,746 --> 01:01:26,616
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1628
01:01:27,817 --> 01:01:29,318
Make their morning happy!

1629
01:01:29,385 --> 01:01:30,653
Thank you.

1630
01:01:30,720 --> 01:01:32,555
Something that goes well with coffee.

1631
01:01:32,622 --> 01:01:33,523
Garlic?

1632
01:01:33,589 --> 01:01:34,957
As soon as you begin? What is it?

1633
01:01:35,024 --> 01:01:38,294
-I think he's steaming the garlic.
-I see.

1634
01:01:38,361 --> 01:01:39,429
You can do that?

1635
01:01:39,495 --> 01:01:40,663
-Is he steaming those?
-Yes.

1636
01:01:40,730 --> 01:01:44,167
I think he'll mash those
to use in many ways, like for his sauce.

1637
01:01:44,233 --> 01:01:45,768
-Like sauce?
-Why is he going that way?

1638
01:01:45,835 --> 01:01:48,471
-He's using both ovens.
-The ovens?

1639
01:01:49,439 --> 01:01:50,306
Here.

1640
01:01:53,276 --> 01:01:54,143
What?

1641
01:01:54,210 --> 01:01:55,344
Should I hold this?

1642
01:01:56,746 --> 01:01:58,448
What do I do?

1643
01:02:00,249 --> 01:02:02,285
Sam grabs some meat. What is it?

1644
01:02:02,351 --> 01:02:03,820
-It's duck meat.
-Duck.

1645
01:02:03,886 --> 01:02:06,689
-That's duck.
-We eat duck often too.

1646
01:02:06,756 --> 01:02:08,224
Sam begins to cook the duck.

1647
01:02:08,291 --> 01:02:10,793
-You said you'd make hollandaise sauce.
-You're right.

1648
01:02:10,860 --> 01:02:11,994
Oh, hollandaise sauce.

1649
01:02:12,061 --> 01:02:14,831
BREAKFAST 101, MAKING HOLLANDAISE SAUCE!

1650
01:02:15,965 --> 01:02:18,000
Asparagus.

1651
01:02:18,067 --> 01:02:21,237
Chef Jong-won had a successful cook-off,
thanks to asparagus.

1652
01:02:21,804 --> 01:02:23,106
DANCE OF SALT!

1653
01:02:23,172 --> 01:02:24,140
Wait!

1654
01:02:24,207 --> 01:02:26,109
-He's been doing that for 30 years!
-Nothing…

1655
01:02:26,175 --> 01:02:27,710
-Nothing made it in!
-Nothing.

1656
01:02:27,777 --> 01:02:29,812
-Not even one grain.
-Not even a single speck.

1657
01:02:29,879 --> 01:02:32,982
-He surprised me.
-Hyun-suk.

1658
01:02:33,049 --> 01:02:34,617
<i>Not even a single granule went in.</i>

1659
01:02:34,684 --> 01:02:36,085
TOTAL ELEMENT SCORE, PROGRAM
COMPONENT SCORE, DEDUCTIONS, TOTAL

1660
01:02:36,686 --> 01:02:37,820
HAHAHAHA

1661
01:02:37,887 --> 01:02:40,456
-You need to be quiet.
-I mean…

1662
01:02:40,523 --> 01:02:42,759
-Why did you yell? You surprised me.
-My bad.

1663
01:02:43,092 --> 01:02:45,061
OH, I CAN CHAT IF I WANT TO?

1664
01:02:45,394 --> 01:02:46,763
THE SEAL HAS BEEN LIFTED!

1665
01:02:47,530 --> 01:02:49,365
-Not even a little went in?
-Not at all.

1666
01:02:49,432 --> 01:02:50,833
-Is that sirloin?
-Strip loin, I think.

1667
01:02:50,900 --> 01:02:53,136
Beef strip loin?

1668
01:02:53,202 --> 01:02:55,605
It's the battle of duck versus sirloin.

1669
01:02:57,140 --> 01:02:59,308
What's that? Crushed garlic?

1670
01:02:59,375 --> 01:03:00,610
-Garlic.
-Garlic?

1671
01:03:00,676 --> 01:03:01,811
What's that?

1672
01:03:01,878 --> 01:03:03,212
-Garlic butter.
-Crushed garlic.

1673
01:03:03,279 --> 01:03:05,281
-Garlic butter!
-Garlic butter!

1674
01:03:05,348 --> 01:03:08,551
He mixed crushed garlic
with melted butter.

1675
01:03:08,618 --> 01:03:11,854
He's going to spread that on bread
and toast it.

1676
01:03:11,921 --> 01:03:13,956
Not a lot can beat that as breakfast.

1677
01:03:14,023 --> 01:03:15,191
It's not easy.

1678
01:03:15,258 --> 01:03:17,126
It'll be even better with some parsley.

1679
01:03:17,193 --> 01:03:19,729
-Sugar. He's adding sugar.
-Sugar.

1680
01:03:19,796 --> 01:03:21,697
-He added sugar? Yes!
-Yes.

1681
01:03:21,764 --> 01:03:23,833
-That's hands down delicious.
-That is. It has to be.

1682
01:03:23,900 --> 01:03:25,268
PERFECT COMBINATION

1683
01:03:25,835 --> 01:03:28,538
BLANCHED ASPARAGUS

1684
01:03:28,604 --> 01:03:31,674
Chef Hyun-suk is famous
for his <i>jjajang ramyeon </i>recipe.

1685
01:03:31,741 --> 01:03:32,875
-He is.
-Sometimes he makes it

1686
01:03:32,942 --> 01:03:35,378
-as the staff meal.
-Is that so?

1687
01:03:35,444 --> 01:03:37,980
-And they love it a lot.
-My staff's favorite staff meal

1688
01:03:38,047 --> 01:03:39,348
is my <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>.

1689
01:03:39,715 --> 01:03:41,250
RISING EXPECTATIONS

1690
01:03:41,317 --> 01:03:44,453
Let me give you some tips.

1691
01:03:44,520 --> 01:03:47,256
-Fish cake?
-It works great with shrimp or seafood.

1692
01:03:47,757 --> 01:03:50,226
-But I'm using fish cake.
-Fish cake.

1693
01:03:50,293 --> 01:03:52,061
That's new.

1694
01:03:52,128 --> 01:03:53,563
Does it go well with <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>?

1695
01:03:53,629 --> 01:03:54,664
It sounds so good.

1696
01:03:54,730 --> 01:03:55,798
It does.

1697
01:03:55,865 --> 01:03:57,333
I've never even thought of it.

1698
01:03:58,000 --> 01:03:59,735
SAM USES ASPARAGUS TOO!

1699
01:04:00,303 --> 01:04:01,437
ASPARAGUS, BREAD

1700
01:04:01,504 --> 01:04:03,606
-Bread.
-Bread. It's thick.

1701
01:04:03,673 --> 01:04:05,842
-A thick slice.
-Bun Massive Taste.

1702
01:04:05,908 --> 01:04:07,643
-Bun Massive Taste.
-Bun Massive Taste.

1703
01:04:07,710 --> 01:04:08,845
LET IS SOAK

1704
01:04:08,911 --> 01:04:12,148
He's cooking duck, asparagus, and onion.

1705
01:04:12,215 --> 01:04:13,382
That's right.

1706
01:04:13,449 --> 01:04:15,952
It'd be so nice
if I could do that for her in the morning.

1707
01:04:16,018 --> 01:04:19,488
Right? Isn't it nice just to imagine that?

1708
01:04:19,555 --> 01:04:22,225
-You promised to have breakfast together.
-Yes, and if she sees me

1709
01:04:22,291 --> 01:04:25,094
put in some work to make breakfast,
she'll see how devoted I am.

1710
01:04:25,428 --> 01:04:27,864
HOLLANDAISE SAUCE: MADE BY EMULSIFYING
EGG YOLK AND BUTTER!

1711
01:04:27,930 --> 01:04:31,767
He keeps adding melted butter
and makes hollandaise sauce.

1712
01:04:32,802 --> 01:04:33,636
DROP!

1713
01:04:34,403 --> 01:04:36,706
He's cooking outside skirt.

1714
01:04:36,772 --> 01:04:39,342
The most important thing
for <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>

1715
01:04:39,408 --> 01:04:41,677
-is good olive oil.
-I see.

1716
01:04:41,744 --> 01:04:43,412
Raise the heat high

1717
01:04:43,479 --> 01:04:45,748
and add some good olive oil.

1718
01:04:45,815 --> 01:04:48,317
-On high heat?
-That must be the kick. On high heat.

1719
01:04:48,618 --> 01:04:49,452
PRE-GRILLED OUTSIDE SKIRT

1720
01:04:49,518 --> 01:04:51,254
And he adds some meat

1721
01:04:51,320 --> 01:04:52,922
-and cooks it in olive oil.
-And fish cake.

1722
01:04:52,989 --> 01:04:54,523
Stir-fry over high heat.

1723
01:04:56,325 --> 01:04:58,694
THIS TIME, BEEF SIRLOIN!

1724
01:04:58,761 --> 01:05:02,131
-Kang-rok.
-Kang-rok's sauce.

1725
01:05:02,198 --> 01:05:04,967
Hyun-suk is using
Kang-rok's braising sauce.

1726
01:05:05,034 --> 01:05:06,602
FLAMES

1727
01:05:07,036 --> 01:05:09,071
A SMOKY FLAVOR! SIRLOIN OF PASSION

1728
01:05:09,138 --> 01:05:10,907
What's he going to do next?

1729
01:05:10,973 --> 01:05:13,376
He uses Kang-rok's braising sauce.

1730
01:05:13,442 --> 01:05:14,510
That looks good.

1731
01:05:14,577 --> 01:05:16,212
That must be delicious.

1732
01:05:16,879 --> 01:05:19,148
Kang-rok is the best at braising.

1733
01:05:19,215 --> 01:05:20,983
You won't find a better sauce.

1734
01:05:21,050 --> 01:05:21,984
ACCELERATE!

1735
01:05:22,051 --> 01:05:23,719
Kang-rok, are you watching this?

1736
01:05:24,086 --> 01:05:27,123
DOUBLE THE LAUGHTER

1737
01:05:27,189 --> 01:05:30,226
You said she liked butter,
so I'm adding two spoons of it.

1738
01:05:30,293 --> 01:05:32,528
5. BRAISE SIRLOIN AND ASPARAGUS
IN SAUCE AND BUTTER

1739
01:05:32,595 --> 01:05:34,597
Beef tastes great with butter.

1740
01:05:34,664 --> 01:05:36,866
It's just like
adding butter to teriyaki sauce.

1741
01:05:36,933 --> 01:05:39,101
You have 9 minutes and 30 seconds left.

1742
01:05:39,769 --> 01:05:40,836
The hollandaise sauce.

1743
01:05:40,903 --> 01:05:41,938
WHAT ABOUT SAM'S HOLLANDAISE SAUCE?

1744
01:05:42,905 --> 01:05:43,806
Huh?

1745
01:05:45,841 --> 01:05:46,676
Huh?

1746
01:05:46,742 --> 01:05:48,077
It's overcooked, right?

1747
01:05:48,144 --> 01:05:49,312
It became scrambled eggs.

1748
01:05:49,378 --> 01:05:51,714
Sam, why don't you
explain your process a little too?

1749
01:05:51,781 --> 01:05:53,616
-I'm busy.
-The hollandaise sauce has become

1750
01:05:53,683 --> 01:05:54,984
a bit like scrambled eggs.

1751
01:05:55,051 --> 01:05:55,885
What?

1752
01:05:55,952 --> 01:05:57,219
What do you mean? You're cooked?

1753
01:05:57,453 --> 01:05:58,421
AS IF HE WANTS HIM TO FAIL

1754
01:05:58,487 --> 01:05:59,822
Oh, no. Did you mess it up?

1755
01:05:59,889 --> 01:06:01,057
No, no.

1756
01:06:01,123 --> 01:06:02,792
FIRST AID: LEMON JUICE AND WATER

1757
01:06:03,259 --> 01:06:04,560
WILL HE SAVE IT?

1758
01:06:05,127 --> 01:06:06,195
Is it okay?

1759
01:06:06,262 --> 01:06:07,096
Yes.

1760
01:06:07,296 --> 01:06:08,297
LOOK

1761
01:06:09,098 --> 01:06:10,333
-Are you doing okay?
-I am.

1762
01:06:10,399 --> 01:06:11,901
-That's a relief.
-That's a relief.

1763
01:06:11,968 --> 01:06:13,703
Cook everything over high heat,

1764
01:06:14,337 --> 01:06:17,540
then briefly stir-fry some onion
and let it cook just a little.

1765
01:06:17,606 --> 01:06:19,075
4. ADD THE ONION LATER AND STIR-FRY

1766
01:06:19,141 --> 01:06:20,643
Do you see this broth?

1767
01:06:20,710 --> 01:06:22,778
-It's fish cake soup broth.
-Fish cake soup broth.

1768
01:06:22,845 --> 01:06:25,081
-The fish cake soup broth?
-It must add umami.

1769
01:06:25,147 --> 01:06:27,049
Where did you get that?

1770
01:06:27,116 --> 01:06:30,786
<i>-He had the soup concentrate.</i>
<i>-He had it.</i>

1771
01:06:30,853 --> 01:06:32,054
You have to add this.

1772
01:06:32,121 --> 01:06:35,391
-The vegetable flakes.
-Add the vegetable flakes.

1773
01:06:35,458 --> 01:06:37,693
-That has to be good.
-It must be.

1774
01:06:37,760 --> 01:06:39,295
If you smell that in the morning…

1775
01:06:39,362 --> 01:06:41,530
-You'd eat that.
-…you'd wake up and eat it.

1776
01:06:41,597 --> 01:06:43,232
It'll automatically wake you up.

1777
01:06:43,299 --> 01:06:46,469
-It can't be too early. Around 10 a.m.
-That's right.

1778
01:06:46,535 --> 01:06:47,570
Late morning.

1779
01:06:47,636 --> 01:06:49,405
-Late breakfast.
-For me, 11 a.m.

1780
01:06:49,472 --> 01:06:51,173
-I'd open the door and go…
-On a Sunday.

1781
01:06:51,240 --> 01:06:52,641
"What are you making?"

1782
01:06:52,708 --> 01:06:55,711
-I'd be happy to smell it in the morning.
-It'd make you happy.

1783
01:06:55,778 --> 01:06:58,781
-My wife's favorite food is <i>ramyeon</i>.
-Your wife?

1784
01:06:58,848 --> 01:07:01,984
-Yes.
-So she'd love to have it any time.

1785
01:07:02,051 --> 01:07:05,988
Sam's cooking some onion
in the pan he used to cook duck,

1786
01:07:06,055 --> 01:07:07,390
and duck fat is delicious.

1787
01:07:07,456 --> 01:07:09,692
-Duck fat.
-It'll make the onion even better.

1788
01:07:09,759 --> 01:07:13,062
I'm using duck fat
to cook asparagus and onion.

1789
01:07:13,129 --> 01:07:15,464
-With duck fat.
-Yes.

1790
01:07:15,531 --> 01:07:17,299
You need to sear the onion
to make it good.

1791
01:07:17,366 --> 01:07:21,470
-Hyun-suk mixes milk and cream cheese.
-Milk and cream cheese?

1792
01:07:21,537 --> 01:07:23,072
What's that for?

1793
01:07:23,439 --> 01:07:24,507
RUNNING OVER TO SHOW YOU!

1794
01:07:24,573 --> 01:07:25,641
For the waffles?

1795
01:07:25,708 --> 01:07:26,675
-Waffles?
-Waffle sauce?

1796
01:07:26,742 --> 01:07:28,644
-He flips them over.
-Waffles.

1797
01:07:29,345 --> 01:07:30,446
GARLIC BUTTER

1798
01:07:30,513 --> 01:07:32,381
Look. That bread.

1799
01:07:32,448 --> 01:07:34,150
That would taste good as is.

1800
01:07:34,216 --> 01:07:36,685
-It's a thick toast.
-It is.

1801
01:07:36,752 --> 01:07:39,188
-Look at that.
-This couple loves bread.

1802
01:07:39,255 --> 01:07:40,256
That looks so good.

1803
01:07:40,322 --> 01:07:43,392
He added sugar,
so the outside will caramelize…

1804
01:07:43,459 --> 01:07:45,961
-Right.
-…and make the toast crispier.

1805
01:07:46,028 --> 01:07:48,431
-But it's soft on the inside.
-Yes, but crispy on the outside.

1806
01:07:48,497 --> 01:07:50,499
You now have seven minutes left.

1807
01:07:51,133 --> 01:07:52,568
He's cooking the noodles now.

1808
01:07:53,469 --> 01:07:56,539
-If he's going to serve <i>ramyeon</i> today…
-Garlic?

1809
01:07:56,605 --> 01:07:58,274
-…he should finish first.
-Is it cooked?

1810
01:07:58,340 --> 01:08:01,343
-What are the garlic cloves for?
-Didn't you use too much water?

1811
01:08:01,410 --> 01:08:02,545
It's oil.

1812
01:08:02,611 --> 01:08:03,979
-It's oil?
-It's water.

1813
01:08:04,046 --> 01:08:04,914
-It's water?
-Yes.

1814
01:08:04,980 --> 01:08:07,049
-So it's water?
-It looks like water.

1815
01:08:07,116 --> 01:08:09,185
How can he get it wrong
with such confidence?

1816
01:08:09,718 --> 01:08:11,353
THESE TWO LOOK KIND OF SIMILAR TOO

1817
01:08:11,420 --> 01:08:13,656
-I think he'll blend the cooked garlic.
-I see.

1818
01:08:13,722 --> 01:08:15,191
It's cooked thoroughly.

1819
01:08:15,257 --> 01:08:16,725
-Garlic honey?
-Garlic honey?

1820
01:08:16,792 --> 01:08:17,726
No, it's syrup.

1821
01:08:17,793 --> 01:08:19,028
Garlic honey.

1822
01:08:19,095 --> 01:08:20,329
Garlic honey?

1823
01:08:20,396 --> 01:08:21,464
Garlic honey?

1824
01:08:21,530 --> 01:08:23,499
It's not garlic honey.
It's oligosaccharide syrup.

1825
01:08:23,566 --> 01:08:24,400
Oh, oligo syrup.

1826
01:08:24,467 --> 01:08:26,735
-That sounds good.
-It looks good.

1827
01:08:26,802 --> 01:08:28,237
WHAT'S THE GARLIC SYRUP FOR?

1828
01:08:28,304 --> 01:08:30,339
That much garlic for breakfast
will hurt your stomach.

1829
01:08:30,973 --> 01:08:31,974
OH, GARLIC!

1830
01:08:32,041 --> 01:08:33,642
But he already steamed the garlic,

1831
01:08:33,709 --> 01:08:36,512
so the bitterness is all gone,
leaving only the sweet flavor.

1832
01:08:36,579 --> 01:08:39,048
Garlic actually contains
a lot of sweetness.

1833
01:08:39,115 --> 01:08:41,250
You have six minutes left.

1834
01:08:41,317 --> 01:08:44,320
Hyun-suk should finish first
because he's making <i>ramyeon</i>.

1835
01:08:44,386 --> 01:08:46,355
-Yes, right.
-You're right.

1836
01:08:46,422 --> 01:08:48,691
That means Sam should finish quickly.

1837
01:08:48,757 --> 01:08:50,826
That'll make the noodles mushy.

1838
01:08:50,893 --> 01:08:52,695
<i>Ramyeon</i> is over when it's mushy.

1839
01:08:53,062 --> 01:08:53,896
ANXIOUS

1840
01:08:53,963 --> 01:08:56,866
-Forget the outside skirt or whatever.
-If it gets mushy, it's over.

1841
01:08:56,932 --> 01:08:59,068
The noodles are very important.

1842
01:08:59,135 --> 01:09:01,403
Especially for <i>jjajang ramyeon.</i>
You must eat it right away.

1843
01:09:02,004 --> 01:09:03,873
GARLIC PURÉE COMPLETED!

1844
01:09:03,939 --> 01:09:05,441
What's that? Hot water? Why?

1845
01:09:05,508 --> 01:09:07,443
-To poach eggs.
-Poached eggs?

1846
01:09:07,510 --> 01:09:09,411
-It's similar to eggs Benedict.
-Poached eggs.

1847
01:09:09,478 --> 01:09:12,114
-Eggs Benedict.
-Whoa!

1848
01:09:12,181 --> 01:09:15,151
-We love that.
-They love that. Yes.

1849
01:09:15,217 --> 01:09:16,385
Are you getting it out?

1850
01:09:16,452 --> 01:09:18,754
-The poached egg.
-Not yet.

1851
01:09:18,821 --> 01:09:20,456
-It's ruined.
-Oh, no!

1852
01:09:20,823 --> 01:09:21,657
THE EGG IS RAGGED!

1853
01:09:21,724 --> 01:09:22,691
He's ruined!

1854
01:09:22,758 --> 01:09:24,226
-He touched it too soon.
-No.

1855
01:09:24,293 --> 01:09:26,762
-You have no time!
-Five minutes!

1856
01:09:26,829 --> 01:09:28,898
Jung-hwan, please go to the kitchen!

1857
01:09:28,964 --> 01:09:30,032
The poached egg is ruined!

1858
01:09:30,099 --> 01:09:32,201
You can scoop it up with a strainer.

1859
01:09:32,268 --> 01:09:34,436
Just add some soup base in there

1860
01:09:34,503 --> 01:09:35,671
and make egg soup!

1861
01:09:35,738 --> 01:09:38,374
Even famous chefs make mistakes!

1862
01:09:39,542 --> 01:09:41,377
Even famous chefs!

1863
01:09:41,443 --> 01:09:42,378
Of course.

1864
01:09:42,444 --> 01:09:44,313
It feels like we have two Poongs today!

1865
01:09:44,380 --> 01:09:47,483
-Keep it going!
-Even a famous guy like him!

1866
01:09:47,550 --> 01:09:49,318
Add salt and make egg soup!

1867
01:09:49,385 --> 01:09:51,420
-Make egg soup instead!
-I like egg soup.

1868
01:09:51,487 --> 01:09:53,088
He failed to make a poached egg.

1869
01:09:53,155 --> 01:09:55,157
-It's ruined?
-He can always try again.

1870
01:09:55,224 --> 01:09:57,960
-The second try at the poached egg.
-He goes for the egg again.

1871
01:09:58,027 --> 01:09:59,195
-The poached egg!
-It's not ready yet.

1872
01:09:59,461 --> 01:10:01,363
DOESN'T LOOK TOO GREAT

1873
01:10:01,430 --> 01:10:03,165
LET'S WAIT

1874
01:10:04,099 --> 01:10:06,669
He puts it back in the water.

1875
01:10:06,735 --> 01:10:08,070
-No!
-It's burnt!

1876
01:10:08,804 --> 01:10:09,638
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

1877
01:10:09,705 --> 01:10:11,207
Oh, no!

1878
01:10:11,273 --> 01:10:12,775
What is this?

1879
01:10:14,143 --> 01:10:15,511
It's not burnt.

1880
01:10:15,578 --> 01:10:17,246
It's perfect.

1881
01:10:17,313 --> 01:10:20,149
Even a famous chef burns food!

1882
01:10:20,216 --> 01:10:23,152
-Oh, no! He's done.
-It looks burnt.

1883
01:10:23,219 --> 01:10:26,388
-It's an emergency.
-Yet he uses that toast.

1884
01:10:26,455 --> 01:10:29,291
-It's delicious with that much color.
-It's okay.

1885
01:10:30,826 --> 01:10:32,127
GIVE ME SOME ATTENTION TOO

1886
01:10:32,194 --> 01:10:33,195
And the salt!

1887
01:10:33,262 --> 01:10:34,763
CACKLE

1888
01:10:35,264 --> 01:10:38,400
KANGNAM AND POONG
STOLE EVERYONE'S ATTENTION

1889
01:10:38,567 --> 01:10:40,302
THE ONLY ONE WHO WITNESSED HIS PERFORMANCE

1890
01:10:40,536 --> 01:10:42,037
WHAT A GOOD MAN

1891
01:10:42,104 --> 01:10:43,739
Did they sweep the salt away?

1892
01:10:43,806 --> 01:10:46,709
HE QUICKLY MOVES HIS POSITION

1893
01:10:47,276 --> 01:10:48,777
NO ONE CARES

1894
01:10:49,111 --> 01:10:52,181
BUT THE WAFFLES ARE GOLDEN BROWN

1895
01:10:52,748 --> 01:10:54,350
Chef Hyun-suk, the noodles!

1896
01:10:54,416 --> 01:10:56,418
You're making noodles,
so you must hurry, Hyun-suk!

1897
01:10:59,321 --> 01:11:00,289
NOT ALLOWED IN

1898
01:11:00,356 --> 01:11:01,590
-It doesn't fit.
-It won't fit.

1899
01:11:03,626 --> 01:11:05,694
-The pot is too small.
-Oh, no.

1900
01:11:05,761 --> 01:11:08,931
-He hasn't changed over the last 12 years!
-He hasn't changed!

1901
01:11:08,998 --> 01:11:11,300
-He's the same.
-He hasn't changed!

1902
01:11:11,367 --> 01:11:13,702
-Hyun-suk strains the noodles.
-He's the same!

1903
01:11:13,769 --> 01:11:15,904
Time to stir-fry the noodles.

1904
01:11:15,971 --> 01:11:18,774
-The sauce.
-Sam made a poached egg.

1905
01:11:18,841 --> 01:11:21,076
-The egg looks nice.
-He made the poached egg.

1906
01:11:21,143 --> 01:11:23,712
-He made the poached egg.
-It looks pretty.

1907
01:11:23,779 --> 01:11:26,215
-The onion.
-Please.

1908
01:11:26,282 --> 01:11:27,816
-Top it with duck.
-Things are hectic.

1909
01:11:27,883 --> 01:11:29,952
-The duck.
-The duck.

1910
01:11:30,019 --> 01:11:31,954
It's okay. You still have time.

1911
01:11:32,021 --> 01:11:33,088
COOKED SMOKED DUCK

1912
01:11:33,155 --> 01:11:34,590
Three minutes left.

1913
01:11:34,657 --> 01:11:36,792
-The waffle.
-Hyun-suk works with a waffle.

1914
01:11:36,859 --> 01:11:38,294
-His waffle is ready.
-He gets the waffle ready.

1915
01:11:38,360 --> 01:11:42,031
-He's topping the waffle with meat?
-He's topping the waffle with meat too.

1916
01:11:42,097 --> 01:11:43,732
It smells so good.

1917
01:11:43,799 --> 01:11:46,502
-Really? I've never seen that.
-It's a thing in the US.

1918
01:11:46,568 --> 01:11:47,636
Waffles and meat?

1919
01:11:47,703 --> 01:11:49,071
What's this sauce?

1920
01:11:49,138 --> 01:11:50,005
What's that?

1921
01:11:50,072 --> 01:11:52,074
-Cream cheese sauce.
-Cream cheese sauce!

1922
01:11:52,141 --> 01:11:53,742
-I see.
-That looks good.

1923
01:11:54,310 --> 01:11:56,612
What are you looking for?
Did you forget something?

1924
01:11:56,679 --> 01:11:57,680
Garlic purée.

1925
01:11:57,746 --> 01:11:59,615
Right, garlic purée!

1926
01:11:59,682 --> 01:12:01,617
8. TOP WAFFLE WITH SIRLOIN,
CREAM CHEESE SAUCE, GARLIC PURÉE

1927
01:12:02,017 --> 01:12:03,986
WHAT'S SAM DOING?

1928
01:12:04,053 --> 01:12:07,556
-Hollandaise sauce. That's a nice texture.
-That sauce is really pretty.

1929
01:12:07,623 --> 01:12:08,924
That looks nice.

1930
01:12:09,491 --> 01:12:12,428
-That's something you see at a hotel.
-It looks nice.

1931
01:12:12,494 --> 01:12:14,763
-What's that sauce called?
-Hollandaise.

1932
01:12:14,830 --> 01:12:16,598
-Oh, right!
-That sauce.

1933
01:12:16,832 --> 01:12:18,567
PLATING THE ONION

1934
01:12:18,734 --> 01:12:21,036
AND TOPPING IT WITH SMOKED DUCK CHIPS!

1935
01:12:22,271 --> 01:12:24,239
HE'LL BE DONE
ONCE HE STIR-FRIES THE NOODLES!

1936
01:12:24,306 --> 01:12:25,607
The stir-fried noodles look good.

1937
01:12:25,674 --> 01:12:27,676
Let me give you one last tip.

1938
01:12:27,743 --> 01:12:29,111
"Tip!"

1939
01:12:29,178 --> 01:12:31,080
-What is it?
-Add a pinch of sugar!

1940
01:12:31,680 --> 01:12:32,948
HERE COMES THE COMBINATION

1941
01:12:33,782 --> 01:12:34,683
TRIPLE LUTZ!

1942
01:12:35,017 --> 01:12:36,385
TRIPLE TOE LOOP!

1943
01:12:36,585 --> 01:12:38,287
THE TRIPLE-TRIPLE SIGNALS THE GRAND FINALE

1944
01:12:38,354 --> 01:12:40,122
-He said "a pinch."
-It didn't go in.

1945
01:12:40,189 --> 01:12:42,057
-He used three pinches.
-It didn't go in anyway.

1946
01:12:42,124 --> 01:12:43,692
-Where's the good olive oil?
-Here.

1947
01:12:44,927 --> 01:12:47,396
Sam finishes first!

1948
01:12:47,463 --> 01:12:48,964
SAM TAKES THE LEAD AGAINST A RAMYEON DISH

1949
01:12:49,031 --> 01:12:50,366
He finishes first!

1950
01:12:50,432 --> 01:12:52,267
He finished with two minutes left
in the game.

1951
01:12:52,835 --> 01:12:54,970
No! Chapagetti should never be mushy!

1952
01:12:55,037 --> 01:12:56,638
It will be mushy! This is bad.

1953
01:12:56,705 --> 01:13:00,709
You're done. Your noodles will get mushy.

1954
01:13:00,776 --> 01:13:02,411
It's a total emergency.

1955
01:13:03,312 --> 01:13:05,180
You can take your time.

1956
01:13:05,247 --> 01:13:06,915
He's adding more sauce powder.

1957
01:13:06,982 --> 01:13:09,918
-He's adding more flavor.
-So no soup?

1958
01:13:09,985 --> 01:13:11,286
-I see. The broth.
-What's that?

1959
01:13:11,353 --> 01:13:13,088
The broth. Fish cake soup broth.

1960
01:13:13,155 --> 01:13:15,157
-He explained it earlier.
-The fish cake soup.

1961
01:13:15,224 --> 01:13:17,593
-Water.
-What water?

1962
01:13:17,860 --> 01:13:19,895
CONDITIONAL REFLEX
PAVLOV'S "SOMEONE"

1963
01:13:19,962 --> 01:13:21,864
-Sam gives him a hand.
-Turn the heat on.

1964
01:13:21,930 --> 01:13:23,665
-No, turn the heat on.
-The heat.

1965
01:13:24,233 --> 01:13:26,335
It was the heat, not water!

1966
01:13:26,402 --> 01:13:28,470
It was heat, not water.

1967
01:13:28,537 --> 01:13:29,605
They can't communicate!

1968
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:31,407
UNICHEF SAM, ALWAYS WILLING

1969
01:13:31,473 --> 01:13:33,942
-It was the heat.
-He got them confused.

1970
01:13:34,009 --> 01:13:35,844
Can you turn the heat on?

1971
01:13:35,911 --> 01:13:38,113
PLATING THE JJAJANG RAMYEON!

1972
01:13:38,180 --> 01:13:40,883
-The noodles are done!
-That was hilarious.

1973
01:13:40,949 --> 01:13:42,584
HALF SOLIDS, HALF NOODLES

1974
01:13:42,651 --> 01:13:44,486
-You have a minute left.
-One minute.

1975
01:13:44,553 --> 01:13:46,722
-Garlic purée here as well.
-Garlic purée.

1976
01:13:46,789 --> 01:13:48,891
-There too?
-Garlic purée on <i>jjajang ramyeon.</i>

1977
01:13:48,957 --> 01:13:50,025
It looks good.

1978
01:13:50,092 --> 01:13:52,895
If you smell this in the morning,
it'll be fantastic.

1979
01:13:52,961 --> 01:13:55,130
Hyun-suk finishes too!

1980
01:13:55,197 --> 01:13:56,799
Hyun-suk finishes.

1981
01:13:56,865 --> 01:13:58,967
HYUN-SUK ALSO FINISHES
WITH 40 SECONDS LEFT

1982
01:14:00,269 --> 01:14:02,905
We should shoot the B-rolls quickly
and let him eat fast.

1983
01:14:03,272 --> 01:14:05,307
THE DISHES FOR COUPLE'S BREAKFAST TAKE OFF

1984
01:14:05,374 --> 01:14:07,009
My gosh.

1985
01:14:07,075 --> 01:14:09,711
-Chef Sam finished two minutes earlier.
-Yes.

1986
01:14:09,778 --> 01:14:11,847
-That's amazing.
-He finished at 13 minutes.

1987
01:14:11,914 --> 01:14:13,549
-This has never happened.
-It's a first.

1988
01:14:13,615 --> 01:14:15,651
-He always needed more time.
-Right?

1989
01:14:15,717 --> 01:14:18,954
The moment someone mentioned
Hyun-suk should serve his food first

1990
01:14:19,521 --> 01:14:21,824
because he's making <i>ramyeon</i>,

1991
01:14:21,890 --> 01:14:25,294
-Sam began to move much faster.
-He's competitive.

1992
01:14:25,727 --> 01:14:27,896
THE CHOIPAGETTI MUST BE EATEN
BEFORE THE NOODLES GET MUSHY

1993
01:14:28,197 --> 01:14:31,533
A BRIEF MOMENT FOR B-ROLL SHOTS

1994
01:14:31,834 --> 01:14:33,769
MAKES A CUP OF POUR-OVER IN THAT WHILE

1995
01:14:33,836 --> 01:14:37,005
Did you bring your own equipment?

1996
01:14:37,072 --> 01:14:38,207
I did.

1997
01:14:38,273 --> 01:14:41,810
-That's the coffee Yuna drinks.
-Yes, this is how I make it.

1998
01:14:41,877 --> 01:14:43,245
He's so sweet.

1999
01:14:43,312 --> 01:14:46,381
He uses a scale and all.

2000
01:14:46,782 --> 01:14:49,084
QUITE PROFESSIONAL,
LETTING THE COFFEE SETTLE

2001
01:14:49,151 --> 01:14:51,553
-You need to wait until it filters.
-He makes coffee.

2002
01:14:51,620 --> 01:14:53,589
It must be a good morning.

2003
01:14:53,655 --> 01:14:55,657
How do you look so good
while making coffee?

2004
01:14:55,724 --> 01:14:56,558
Right?

2005
01:14:56,625 --> 01:14:57,993
It smells good.

2006
01:14:58,060 --> 01:14:59,962
-He's letting it settle.
-Right?

2007
01:15:00,028 --> 01:15:00,863
It takes a while.

2008
01:15:02,130 --> 01:15:03,131
SMACKING LIPS

2009
01:15:03,198 --> 01:15:05,167
He has to wait for a minute.

2010
01:15:05,234 --> 01:15:07,002
-I'll make it quick today.
-Please be quick.

2011
01:15:07,069 --> 01:15:08,170
-Yes.
-No way.

2012
01:15:08,237 --> 01:15:09,505
You should do it the right way.

2013
01:15:09,571 --> 01:15:11,507
The morning coffee must be perfect.

2014
01:15:11,740 --> 01:15:13,208
SNAP

2015
01:15:13,876 --> 01:15:16,912
STARTING THE POUR-OVER

2016
01:15:16,979 --> 01:15:19,815
It takes a lot of work to make coffee,
and he even grinds his own beans.

2017
01:15:19,882 --> 01:15:21,783
-It's a lot of work.
-Yes, also,

2018
01:15:21,850 --> 01:15:23,952
-taking time is important too.
-Yes.

2019
01:15:24,019 --> 01:15:26,154
But you can have the food
while the coffee brews.

2020
01:15:26,221 --> 01:15:27,489
You drink your coffee later.

2021
01:15:27,856 --> 01:15:29,525
ONLY ONE GUY FEELS RUSHED

2022
01:15:29,591 --> 01:15:33,161
But people mostly wake up,
have a sip of coffee, then eat breakfast.

2023
01:15:33,529 --> 01:15:34,730
AHN JUNG-HWAN, YOU!

2024
01:15:35,130 --> 01:15:37,132
TEASING SUCCESSFUL
HEHEHEHEHEHE

2025
01:15:37,566 --> 01:15:38,834
B-ROLL SHOTS ARE DONE
TIME TO EAT

2026
01:15:38,901 --> 01:15:40,502
-So you just have to wait?
-Yes.

2027
01:15:40,569 --> 01:15:43,138
Then please try his dish first.

2028
01:15:43,705 --> 01:15:50,445
THE BREAKFAST FULL OF LOVE
THAT SAM MAKES FOR HIS FAMILY

2029
01:15:52,080 --> 01:15:55,717
CHEF SAM KIM'S BUN MASSIVE TASTE

2030
01:15:55,784 --> 01:15:58,153
Just by the way it looks,

2031
01:15:58,220 --> 01:16:01,590
I have a feeling my wife will be happy
if I make her this.

2032
01:16:02,157 --> 01:16:03,125
-And coffee.
-Yes.

2033
01:16:03,191 --> 01:16:05,093
In the early days of our relationship,

2034
01:16:05,160 --> 01:16:07,529
we often had eggs Benedict.

2035
01:16:07,596 --> 01:16:08,897
It reminds me of those days.

2036
01:16:08,964 --> 01:16:10,666
He's remembering the old days.

2037
01:16:10,732 --> 01:16:12,901
But that bread

2038
01:16:12,968 --> 01:16:15,671
seems a little burnt on the outside.

2039
01:16:15,737 --> 01:16:16,939
It's the crust.

2040
01:16:17,005 --> 01:16:18,674
-The crust.
-The Maillard reaction.

2041
01:16:18,740 --> 01:16:20,275
-The Maillard reaction?
-Intentional.

2042
01:16:20,342 --> 01:16:22,644
It feels toastier
when you smell something a bit burnt.

2043
01:16:22,711 --> 01:16:24,379
-The Maillard reaction works for coffee.
-Yes.

2044
01:16:24,446 --> 01:16:26,715
-So it's not burnt?
-No, never.

2045
01:16:26,782 --> 01:16:28,183
-That's not burnt?
-Why is everyone

2046
01:16:28,250 --> 01:16:30,152
trying to meddle with Woo-rim's breakfast?

2047
01:16:30,719 --> 01:16:32,054
Let him eat already!

2048
01:16:32,120 --> 01:16:33,889
Okay. Fine.

2049
01:16:34,222 --> 01:16:36,558
THE CHOIPAGETTI COOK IS VERY SENSITIVE

2050
01:16:37,192 --> 01:16:40,963
FINALLY, HIS COFFEE IS DONE

2051
01:16:41,029 --> 01:16:42,531
-It looks good.
-Whoa.

2052
01:16:42,898 --> 01:16:45,500
ACCURATE

2053
01:16:45,567 --> 01:16:47,135
I do this in the morning.

2054
01:16:47,202 --> 01:16:49,571
I take my coffee iced,
my wife likes it hot.

2055
01:16:50,238 --> 01:16:51,373
I like it as a latte.

2056
01:16:51,440 --> 01:16:52,374
A macchiato for me.

2057
01:16:52,441 --> 01:16:53,475
HE'S NOT TAKING ORDERS…

2058
01:16:53,775 --> 01:16:55,010
FIRST, A SIP OF COFFEE

2059
01:16:55,077 --> 01:16:56,044
That looks great.

2060
01:16:56,845 --> 01:16:59,181
-What's it like?
-It must be a good morning.

2061
01:16:59,247 --> 01:17:01,049
Just the way I have it at home.

2062
01:17:01,116 --> 01:17:02,584
Coffee massive taste.

2063
01:17:02,651 --> 01:17:03,885
-It looks so good.
-<i>Mamacita</i>.

2064
01:17:03,952 --> 01:17:05,654
-Looks good.
-It looks delicious.

2065
01:17:05,721 --> 01:17:07,222
-Must be a good morning.
-The asparagus.

2066
01:17:07,723 --> 01:17:08,991
Starting with the asparagus.

2067
01:17:09,057 --> 01:17:10,425
I'm looking forward to this sauce.

2068
01:17:11,893 --> 01:17:12,928
CRUNCH

2069
01:17:13,962 --> 01:17:15,430
GLANCES

2070
01:17:15,497 --> 01:17:18,500
I'm reminded of the eggs Benedict

2071
01:17:18,567 --> 01:17:20,969
my wife and I had when we were dating.

2072
01:17:21,036 --> 01:17:23,071
This is definitely better than that.

2073
01:17:23,138 --> 01:17:25,707
It's better than the one he had back then.

2074
01:17:25,774 --> 01:17:27,643
-Next, the onion.
-The onion.

2075
01:17:27,709 --> 01:17:28,677
It looks good.

2076
01:17:28,744 --> 01:17:32,714
<i>-I cooked everything in duck fat.</i>
<i>-Everything?</i>

2077
01:17:32,781 --> 01:17:35,117
It's completely different
from regular cooking oil.

2078
01:17:35,183 --> 01:17:36,284
-The flavor is different.
-Yes.

2079
01:17:36,351 --> 01:17:40,222
Yes, and I'm sure what you get
at a restaurant doesn't use duck fat.

2080
01:17:41,757 --> 01:17:43,058
-I doubt it.
-Mmm.

2081
01:17:43,125 --> 01:17:44,526
He made the duck feel like bacon.

2082
01:17:44,593 --> 01:17:45,627
-Like bacon. Yes.
-Right.

2083
01:17:45,694 --> 01:17:48,330
-I thought it was bacon.
-Crispy bacon.

2084
01:17:48,397 --> 01:17:50,132
It's still warm and delicious.

2085
01:17:50,365 --> 01:17:51,633
GLAD

2086
01:17:51,700 --> 01:17:53,802
-Bun Massive Taste.
-I love that sound.

2087
01:17:53,869 --> 01:17:56,071
If the bun, the toast, tastes good,
say the name for us.

2088
01:17:56,138 --> 01:17:58,273
See if you want to eat it with your wife.

2089
01:17:58,340 --> 01:17:59,708
ONCE IN THE SAUCE
ONCE IN THE EGG

2090
01:17:59,775 --> 01:18:01,943
-It must be good.
-It looks soft on the inside.

2091
01:18:02,010 --> 01:18:03,645
You know how good that is.

2092
01:18:03,712 --> 01:18:06,615
It's a mix of sweetness and softness.

2093
01:18:06,682 --> 01:18:07,516
Mmm.

2094
01:18:07,582 --> 01:18:09,251
-Mmm.
-Mmm.

2095
01:18:09,317 --> 01:18:10,352
-Mmm.
-Does it smell burnt?

2096
01:18:10,719 --> 01:18:11,887
OVERDOING IT

2097
01:18:11,953 --> 01:18:13,055
Does it smell burnt?

2098
01:18:14,156 --> 01:18:16,191
It was just as you said. It's crispy.

2099
01:18:16,258 --> 01:18:18,193
It's crispy, not burnt.

2100
01:18:18,260 --> 01:18:19,494
I personally like

2101
01:18:20,062 --> 01:18:23,965
to eat breakfast that has
this kind of balance.

2102
01:18:25,133 --> 01:18:28,136
It's not too salty and not too sweet.

2103
01:18:28,203 --> 01:18:31,406
Something that's light
so you can chow down with some coffee.

2104
01:18:31,473 --> 01:18:32,774
This is exactly that.

2105
01:18:32,841 --> 01:18:33,975
It's a textbook breakfast.

2106
01:18:34,042 --> 01:18:35,711
When you roast coffee beans,

2107
01:18:35,777 --> 01:18:39,481
they're a little burnt on purpose too.

2108
01:18:39,548 --> 01:18:43,885
So the slightly burnt flavor
may connect those two together.

2109
01:18:43,952 --> 01:18:45,153
-That must be the case.
-I think

2110
01:18:45,220 --> 01:18:46,188
-it was intentional.
-Food pairing.

2111
01:18:46,254 --> 01:18:48,056
-Right? Was it intentional?
-It was.

2112
01:18:48,123 --> 01:18:48,957
I knew it.

2113
01:18:49,024 --> 01:18:50,659
His intention isn't important right now!

2114
01:18:50,926 --> 01:18:52,227
FORGET INTENTION OR WHATEVER

2115
01:18:52,294 --> 01:18:55,297
He's burning with frustration.

2116
01:18:55,363 --> 01:18:57,332
The way he burns can also connect to this.

2117
01:18:57,699 --> 01:18:58,767
EVEN PAIR IT WITH HYUN-SUK

2118
01:18:58,834 --> 01:19:00,268
You can come back to it.

2119
01:19:00,335 --> 01:19:02,637
-I'll try it before it gets mushy.
-Okay.

2120
01:19:02,704 --> 01:19:04,940
Next, Chef Hyun-suk's dish.

2121
01:19:05,006 --> 01:19:07,142
<i>Today, I'm Choipagetti Cook.</i>

2122
01:19:07,209 --> 01:19:09,311
HYUN-SUK'S SECRET RECIPE!
FANCY JJAJANG RAMYEON

2123
01:19:11,079 --> 01:19:13,315
AND A WAFFLE TOPPED WITH LOTS OF BEEF

2124
01:19:14,216 --> 01:19:18,353
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
TODAY, I'M CHOIPAGETTI COOK

2125
01:19:18,420 --> 01:19:20,088
You two try to stay in shape,

2126
01:19:20,155 --> 01:19:22,057
but you said
Yuna loves <i>jjajang ramyeon</i>, right?

2127
01:19:22,124 --> 01:19:23,992
Then it's best to eat it in the morning.

2128
01:19:24,059 --> 01:19:25,927
When you eat it later in the day
or at night,

2129
01:19:25,994 --> 01:19:27,896
it'll impact your diet.

2130
01:19:27,963 --> 01:19:29,831
He keeps selling snake oil.

2131
01:19:29,898 --> 01:19:33,368
-Snake oil?
-What you see on top is garlic purée.

2132
01:19:33,435 --> 01:19:37,405
Cook garlic, add oligosaccharide syrup,
and blend it to get that flavor.

2133
01:19:37,472 --> 01:19:40,375
You wanted him to eat it quickly.
Why are you talking?

2134
01:19:40,442 --> 01:19:41,676
Explain it after he has a bite.

2135
01:19:41,743 --> 01:19:43,712
Do you know how important
a chef's intention is?

2136
01:19:43,979 --> 01:19:45,147
YOU JUST SAID IT WASN'T IMPORTANT

2137
01:19:45,213 --> 01:19:47,415
-He's sensitive.
-Does it seem okay?

2138
01:19:47,482 --> 01:19:49,651
-It still seems fine. It's still fine.
-It does?

2139
01:19:49,885 --> 01:19:51,586
NOT MUSHY

2140
01:19:51,653 --> 01:19:54,089
-It's not mushy.
-It's not mushy. I'm so glad.

2141
01:19:54,556 --> 01:19:56,358
PHEW

2142
01:19:56,424 --> 01:19:57,859
That looks so good.

2143
01:19:57,926 --> 01:19:59,094
I desperately want some.

2144
01:19:59,161 --> 01:20:00,695
How did it not get mushy?

2145
01:20:00,762 --> 01:20:02,264
I calculated everything.

2146
01:20:02,330 --> 01:20:04,332
I need to take a big bite.

2147
01:20:05,767 --> 01:20:08,236
FINALLY, THE FIRST BITE OF CHOIPAGETTI

2148
01:20:08,303 --> 01:20:10,305
-For breakfast.
-Look at that. I want it so bad.

2149
01:20:11,239 --> 01:20:12,207
He's in shock.

2150
01:20:12,274 --> 01:20:13,208
-What is it?
-It must be good.

2151
01:20:13,275 --> 01:20:14,643
He seems to love it.

2152
01:20:14,709 --> 01:20:16,244
He just chuckled out of his nose.

2153
01:20:16,311 --> 01:20:17,512
That has to be good.

2154
01:20:17,579 --> 01:20:19,181
Is <i>jjajang ramyeon </i>the ultimate breakfast?

2155
01:20:19,247 --> 01:20:20,315
Chapagetti for breakfast?

2156
01:20:20,382 --> 01:20:22,884
-It's not so bad as breakfast.
-Do you like it?

2157
01:20:23,285 --> 01:20:24,519
I KNEW IT

2158
01:20:24,586 --> 01:20:26,188
Isn't it too heavy for breakfast?

2159
01:20:26,254 --> 01:20:27,589
The <i>jjajang ramyeon </i>you eat

2160
01:20:27,656 --> 01:20:29,758
-when you're drunk is the best.
-That's true.

2161
01:20:29,825 --> 01:20:30,659
Mmm.

2162
01:20:30,725 --> 01:20:31,793
-What did you just eat?
-What?

2163
01:20:31,860 --> 01:20:32,994
-Fish cake.
-Fish cake.

2164
01:20:33,061 --> 01:20:35,831
I thought it was a potato,
but it was a piece of fish cake.

2165
01:20:35,897 --> 01:20:37,499
-He thought it was potato.
-He added lots of fish cake.

2166
01:20:37,566 --> 01:20:38,834
If you add seafood,

2167
01:20:38,900 --> 01:20:41,937
it becomes fancy
like a hotel restaurant's <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

2168
01:20:42,003 --> 01:20:43,772
But I heard he was allergic to shellfish,

2169
01:20:43,839 --> 01:20:45,073
so I used fish cake instead.

2170
01:20:45,140 --> 01:20:46,308
Is that true?

2171
01:20:46,374 --> 01:20:48,610
I'm allergic to shrimp.

2172
01:20:50,078 --> 01:20:52,247
-You knew that already. Thank you.
-That's Hyun-suk.

2173
01:20:52,314 --> 01:20:53,415
-So considerate.
-He is.

2174
01:20:53,481 --> 01:20:55,917
And the color goes so well
with coffee too.

2175
01:20:56,484 --> 01:20:58,453
-They are the same.
-Does it go well with coffee?

2176
01:20:58,520 --> 01:20:59,821
Enough is enough.

2177
01:20:59,888 --> 01:21:02,123
I did forget that I had coffee here.

2178
01:21:02,190 --> 01:21:03,124
Let me try it.

2179
01:21:03,191 --> 01:21:05,360
-It needs to go well with coffee.
-It must.

2180
01:21:05,427 --> 01:21:08,496
-Iced coffee with greasy food.
-It's definitely a good pair.

2181
01:21:08,563 --> 01:21:09,598
It washes the grease down.

2182
01:21:10,699 --> 01:21:12,701
-It washes it down.
-It does?

2183
01:21:12,767 --> 01:21:14,603
It's 100% a good pair.

2184
01:21:14,669 --> 01:21:16,338
-I'm reminded of my wife.
-You are?

2185
01:21:16,404 --> 01:21:18,607
She'll squeal the moment she tries it.

2186
01:21:18,673 --> 01:21:20,775
What does she do
when she eats something good?

2187
01:21:20,842 --> 01:21:22,544
She goes, "Mmm!"

2188
01:21:22,611 --> 01:21:23,511
Mmm!

2189
01:21:23,778 --> 01:21:25,914
SO MANY FAKE YUNAS HERE

2190
01:21:25,981 --> 01:21:27,916
She rarely ever makes a sound,

2191
01:21:27,983 --> 01:21:29,751
but she does
when she eats something so good.

2192
01:21:31,686 --> 01:21:33,722
SLURP

2193
01:21:34,189 --> 01:21:36,658
-It's my favorite cut of meat.
-The meat.

2194
01:21:36,725 --> 01:21:38,460
-He used lots of meat.
-Is it cooked well?

2195
01:21:38,526 --> 01:21:40,629
Right now, it's dinnertime.

2196
01:21:40,695 --> 01:21:41,529
I'm craving it a lot.

2197
01:21:41,596 --> 01:21:44,232
-I really can't deal with this.
-It's tough to bear.

2198
01:21:44,633 --> 01:21:46,735
ABOUT TO JUMP IN RIGHT AWAY

2199
01:21:46,801 --> 01:21:50,372
I mentioned that the outside skirt has
a strong meaty aroma, right?

2200
01:21:50,939 --> 01:21:52,274
Even this sauce can't hide it.

2201
01:21:52,340 --> 01:21:54,576
I can sense the meaty aroma

2202
01:21:54,643 --> 01:21:56,978
-while tasting the <i>jjajang</i> sauce.
-Outside skirt has to be good.

2203
01:21:57,045 --> 01:21:58,446
I can taste everything.

2204
01:21:58,513 --> 01:22:00,515
I see. The flavor of the ingredients.

2205
01:22:00,582 --> 01:22:02,317
Outside skirt Chapagetti will catch on.

2206
01:22:02,384 --> 01:22:04,419
-The waffle.
-Try the waffle.

2207
01:22:04,486 --> 01:22:05,720
-This one.
-Thank you.

2208
01:22:06,454 --> 01:22:08,890
CRUNCH

2209
01:22:08,957 --> 01:22:10,892
-The waffle is crunchy too.
-It is.

2210
01:22:10,959 --> 01:22:12,360
Damn, I'm starving.

2211
01:22:14,062 --> 01:22:14,963
Can you not swear?

2212
01:22:15,030 --> 01:22:16,564
-I'm sorry.
-It's okay.

2213
01:22:17,198 --> 01:22:19,334
-I'll try a lot of garlic.
-I get that you're hungry.

2214
01:22:19,401 --> 01:22:20,969
-Hang in there.
-Wait till the next episode.

2215
01:22:21,036 --> 01:22:22,203
Hang in there for a week.

2216
01:22:22,270 --> 01:22:25,407
It would be amazing
if the waffle is delicious too.

2217
01:22:25,473 --> 01:22:26,875
CRUNCH

2218
01:22:26,942 --> 01:22:28,610
I hear crunchy sounds.

2219
01:22:28,677 --> 01:22:29,878
Mmm.

2220
01:22:29,945 --> 01:22:31,513
Gosh.

2221
01:22:31,579 --> 01:22:34,950
I think this could make
a nice dessert too.

2222
01:22:35,016 --> 01:22:37,018
But it also feels like the main dish.

2223
01:22:37,085 --> 01:22:39,688
I can taste many different things
that are on the border.

2224
01:22:39,754 --> 01:22:42,924
You put more garlic purée on this
than the main dish.

2225
01:22:42,991 --> 01:22:45,694
<i>Yes, I put more garlic purée there.</i>

2226
01:22:45,760 --> 01:22:47,829
My wife likes food
that smells strongly of garlic.

2227
01:22:47,896 --> 01:22:48,964
I see.

2228
01:22:49,965 --> 01:22:51,533
ANOTHER BITE

2229
01:22:52,367 --> 01:22:53,835
It's simple, so I'll try it.

2230
01:22:53,902 --> 01:22:56,237
-I know this pairs well with coffee.
-Will it?

2231
01:22:56,304 --> 01:22:58,506
It's a waffle, so he's sure.

2232
01:22:58,573 --> 01:22:59,708
All right.

2233
01:22:59,774 --> 01:23:03,178
Now, Kangnam, why don't you try some?
You must be hungry.

2234
01:23:03,244 --> 01:23:05,246
-Yes.
-Please try some first.

2235
01:23:05,313 --> 01:23:08,116
This is Chef Sam's dish.

2236
01:23:08,183 --> 01:23:10,618
THE TUBBY TWINS GET THE FOOD TOO

2237
01:23:10,685 --> 01:23:12,220
Bun Massive Taste.

2238
01:23:12,287 --> 01:23:13,588
Tell us in Kangnam's style.

2239
01:23:13,655 --> 01:23:14,723
Like a bacon dish.

2240
01:23:14,789 --> 01:23:16,024
SECOND BITE

2241
01:23:16,558 --> 01:23:20,295
THE TUBBY TWINS GET A BITE
AFTER A LONG WAIT

2242
01:23:20,695 --> 01:23:21,529
Mmm.

2243
01:23:21,896 --> 01:23:22,731
YUM

2244
01:23:23,465 --> 01:23:25,200
I was starving to death.

2245
01:23:25,467 --> 01:23:26,901
SO HONEST…

2246
01:23:27,635 --> 01:23:28,903
This is cheating.

2247
01:23:28,970 --> 01:23:31,206
-Why?
-It's way too good.

2248
01:23:31,272 --> 01:23:34,476
There's a particular taste of bread
that everyone likes, right? It's that.

2249
01:23:36,011 --> 01:23:37,612
He's amazing.

2250
01:23:37,679 --> 01:23:38,513
This one wins.

2251
01:23:38,580 --> 01:23:39,414
Is it really not burnt?

2252
01:23:39,481 --> 01:23:40,915
KANGNAM'S MAKES HIS DECISION

2253
01:23:40,982 --> 01:23:44,319
-No. The texture is perfect too.
-It's not you

2254
01:23:44,386 --> 01:23:46,588
-that gets to decide.
-This one wins.

2255
01:23:46,654 --> 01:23:48,790
-That's the winner?
-Isn't the bread so good?

2256
01:23:48,857 --> 01:23:50,458
I want to be here as a guest too.

2257
01:23:50,525 --> 01:23:51,526
We should do that sometime.

2258
01:23:51,593 --> 01:23:53,962
-It should be you and me.
-Let's do that.

2259
01:23:54,029 --> 01:23:55,864
Next, Chef Hyun-suk's dish.

2260
01:23:55,930 --> 01:23:57,665
Today, I'm Choipagetti Cook.

2261
01:23:58,233 --> 01:23:59,667
It goes in at once.

2262
01:23:59,734 --> 01:24:01,770
The noodles are already all gone.

2263
01:24:01,836 --> 01:24:03,738
-That was one bite.
-It's definitely delicious.

2264
01:24:04,472 --> 01:24:05,340
NAM-NO TAKES THE WHOLE BOWL

2265
01:24:05,407 --> 01:24:06,708
The twins are done too.

2266
01:24:06,775 --> 01:24:08,176
Look at all of you.

2267
01:24:08,243 --> 01:24:09,477
My gosh.

2268
01:24:09,544 --> 01:24:10,678
Why? Is it good?

2269
01:24:10,745 --> 01:24:12,414
This is so good.

2270
01:24:13,148 --> 01:24:15,817
-You said Sam had won.
-No, this is so good too.

2271
01:24:15,884 --> 01:24:17,285
May I have some more?

2272
01:24:17,986 --> 01:24:19,354
"May I have some more?"

2273
01:24:19,421 --> 01:24:20,989
BRIGHTENS UP

2274
01:24:21,056 --> 01:24:22,791
It's not the Chapagetti we normally eat.

2275
01:24:22,857 --> 01:24:24,592
-It's so different.
-It is.

2276
01:24:24,659 --> 01:24:25,960
-Is it different?
-It's fancy.

2277
01:24:26,027 --> 01:24:27,162
Try the fish cake.

2278
01:24:27,228 --> 01:24:28,229
The fish cake.

2279
01:24:28,296 --> 01:24:29,564
I see.

2280
01:24:30,265 --> 01:24:31,633
-Good.
-"Good."

2281
01:24:31,699 --> 01:24:33,268
It's so good.

2282
01:24:33,701 --> 01:24:35,336
CLEANING UP

2283
01:24:35,403 --> 01:24:36,237
Look at them.

2284
01:24:36,571 --> 01:24:38,907
HE'S CLEANING UP THE PLATE TOO

2285
01:24:39,641 --> 01:24:41,643
Twins, how did you like it?

2286
01:24:41,709 --> 01:24:42,944
Well,

2287
01:24:43,011 --> 01:24:44,913
here's a list
of my top three <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>

2288
01:24:44,979 --> 01:24:46,714
Hu Deok-juk's <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

2289
01:24:46,781 --> 01:24:48,616
Amy Park's <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

2290
01:24:48,683 --> 01:24:52,020
-And I think Choipagetti is a close third.
-Really?

2291
01:24:52,087 --> 01:24:54,556
-It's that good? Whoa.
-Yes.

2292
01:24:54,622 --> 01:24:56,024
It was incredible.

2293
01:24:56,091 --> 01:24:57,358
SATISFIED

2294
01:24:57,425 --> 01:25:00,562
I would be surprised at how good it is
even if this was sold at a restaurant.

2295
01:25:00,628 --> 01:25:03,364
He used fish cake
instead of seafood, right?

2296
01:25:03,431 --> 01:25:04,499
But there's nothing lacking.

2297
01:25:04,566 --> 01:25:05,867
I'd pay 30,000 won for this.

2298
01:25:05,934 --> 01:25:07,602
Yes, I'd pay up to 30,000 won.

2299
01:25:07,669 --> 01:25:09,237
Have you tried Sam's dish?

2300
01:25:09,304 --> 01:25:10,171
I had it all.

2301
01:25:10,238 --> 01:25:11,673
What was that like?

2302
01:25:12,207 --> 01:25:13,975
I forgot after having Choipagetti.

2303
01:25:14,676 --> 01:25:16,177
Yes, it's way too strong.

2304
01:25:16,244 --> 01:25:18,746
-It was way too strong.
-What if Sam had gone after?

2305
01:25:18,813 --> 01:25:21,182
It's time to make your choice.

2306
01:25:21,749 --> 01:25:22,817
Couple's Breakfast.

2307
01:25:22,884 --> 01:25:25,220
<i>Press one to choose Sam Kim,</i>

2308
01:25:25,286 --> 01:25:27,455
<i>and two to choose Choi Hyun-suk.</i>

2309
01:25:27,522 --> 01:25:30,091
Please make your decision
and press the button!

2310
01:25:31,259 --> 01:25:32,293
Hmm…

2311
01:25:33,628 --> 01:25:35,263
-I chose one.
-You did?

2312
01:25:35,330 --> 01:25:37,632
Let's find out the result.

2313
01:25:37,699 --> 01:25:38,967
-Show us!
-I'm sorry!

2314
01:25:39,934 --> 01:25:40,869
-What?
-To whom?

2315
01:25:40,935 --> 01:25:43,204
-"I'm sorry"?
-He said he was sorry.

2316
01:25:43,271 --> 01:25:45,206
I wonder who he said that to.

2317
01:25:45,273 --> 01:25:47,976
Will Chef Sam continue his winning streak

2318
01:25:48,042 --> 01:25:50,044
against Chef Hyun-suk?

2319
01:25:50,111 --> 01:25:53,982
Or will Chef Hyun-suk beat Chef Sam

2320
01:25:54,048 --> 01:25:55,917
and get his revenge?

2321
01:25:55,984 --> 01:25:57,285
Which side

2322
01:25:57,352 --> 01:25:58,686
did you take, Woo-rim?

2323
01:25:58,753 --> 01:26:00,054
Who's the winner?

2324
01:26:00,121 --> 01:26:01,789
Was it the textbook…

2325
01:26:01,856 --> 01:26:03,691
SAM KIM WINS

2326
01:26:04,192 --> 01:26:05,460
SAM KIM'S BUM MASSIVE TASTE WINS!

2327
01:26:05,527 --> 01:26:06,828
Sam Kim wins!

2328
01:26:06,895 --> 01:26:08,630
He chose the textbook breakfast.

2329
01:26:08,696 --> 01:26:10,198
SAM KIM WITH 20 YEARS OF EXPERIENCE WINS!

2330
01:26:10,265 --> 01:26:11,599
Actually, I was torn.

2331
01:26:11,666 --> 01:26:15,770
I thought I could be happy
to eat this Chapagetti in the morning.

2332
01:26:15,837 --> 01:26:17,172
I had that thought,

2333
01:26:17,238 --> 01:26:19,073
but when I thought about it again,

2334
01:26:19,140 --> 01:26:21,442
Chef Sam's dish

2335
01:26:21,509 --> 01:26:25,280
would be a better pair with coffee,

2336
01:26:25,346 --> 01:26:27,482
and I'd have it much more often.

2337
01:26:27,549 --> 01:26:29,918
You can't eat <i>jjajang ramyeon</i> every day.

2338
01:26:29,984 --> 01:26:31,819
Instead of breakfast…

2339
01:26:31,886 --> 01:26:33,788
-It's for dinner.
-…it should be for dinner.

2340
01:26:34,122 --> 01:26:36,858
JJAJANG RAMYEON
IS BETTER AS DINNER WITH SOME BEER!

2341
01:26:36,925 --> 01:26:40,028
If I had a bite of it
after a day of hard work,

2342
01:26:40,094 --> 01:26:41,729
-it would be the perfect dinner.
-Yes.

2343
01:26:41,796 --> 01:26:43,865
Viewers of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

2344
01:26:43,932 --> 01:26:45,533
Chapagetti is a must-eat dish

2345
01:26:45,600 --> 01:26:46,734
every Sunday morning.

2346
01:26:47,135 --> 01:26:49,404
CONTINUES TO INSIST

2347
01:26:49,470 --> 01:26:51,339
So I decided to go with

2348
01:26:51,406 --> 01:26:53,708
-Bun Massive Taste.
-Bun Massive Taste.

2349
01:26:53,775 --> 01:26:56,544
-He takes Sam's side.
-Bun Massive Taste.

2350
01:26:56,611 --> 01:26:58,846
This means Sam has won

2351
01:26:58,913 --> 01:27:01,983
four times in a row against Hyun-suk!

2352
01:27:02,050 --> 01:27:03,818
He took four wins in a row from last year.

2353
01:27:03,885 --> 01:27:05,587
-That's amazing.
-What's going on?

2354
01:27:05,887 --> 01:27:08,256
HE BECOMES HYUN-SUK'S KRYPTONITE

2355
01:27:09,023 --> 01:27:12,026
Chef Sam gets his sixth star!

2356
01:27:12,093 --> 01:27:13,061
Bun Massive Taste!

2357
01:27:13,127 --> 01:27:15,263
Congratulations, Sam!

2358
01:27:15,797 --> 01:27:18,399
Sang-hwa and Kangnam have been married
for eight years already.

2359
01:27:18,466 --> 01:27:19,567
Has anything changed?

2360
01:27:19,634 --> 01:27:21,469
Life is very intense.

2361
01:27:21,536 --> 01:27:22,937
You have to adjust yourself to her.

2362
01:27:23,004 --> 01:27:25,073
I didn't expect her
to discipline me this much.

2363
01:27:25,139 --> 01:27:27,275
Even when I crave <i>jjajangmyeon</i>,
she never lets me.

2364
01:27:27,342 --> 01:27:28,977
But you keep making her angry.

2365
01:27:29,043 --> 01:27:29,911
Isn't that my car?

2366
01:27:29,978 --> 01:27:31,112
It's my car!

2367
01:27:31,179 --> 01:27:32,380
I really hate it.

2368
01:27:32,447 --> 01:27:34,315
No YouTubers risk their lives
for content like I do.

2369
01:27:34,549 --> 01:27:35,917
THE PROBLEM HUSBAND ASKS FOR TROUBLE

2370
01:27:35,984 --> 01:27:38,086
Show us Kangnam's orders!

2371
01:27:38,720 --> 01:27:41,356
Dishes Lee Sang-hwa would love and hate.

2372
01:27:41,723 --> 01:27:42,957
TWO EXTREME ORDERS

2373
01:27:43,024 --> 01:27:44,192
A ROUND OF HEALTHY DISHES

2374
01:27:44,259 --> 01:27:45,560
LEE SANG-HWA WOULD LOVE

2375
01:27:45,893 --> 01:27:47,929
ALREADY IN HEALTHY COLORS

2376
01:27:47,996 --> 01:27:49,330
Whoa.

2377
01:27:49,397 --> 01:27:50,698
Sang-hwa would love this.

2378
01:27:50,765 --> 01:27:51,766
I got that over with.

2379
01:27:51,833 --> 01:27:53,034
Make me something she'd hate.

2380
01:27:53,301 --> 01:27:54,202
A BOMBSHELL OF CARBS!

2381
01:27:54,369 --> 01:27:55,403
SUGAR EXPLOSION!

2382
01:27:55,570 --> 01:27:56,471
OVERLY RICH AND INTENSE

2383
01:27:56,704 --> 01:27:57,839
THAT'S WHAT I'M TALKING ABOUT

2384
01:27:57,905 --> 01:27:58,906
Thanks, Poong.

2385
01:27:58,973 --> 01:28:00,008
What's she doing?

2386
01:28:00,074 --> 01:28:01,142
Can she steal what I made?

2387
01:28:01,209 --> 01:28:02,176
GETS HIS CHILI OIL STOLEN

2388
01:28:02,243 --> 01:28:03,678
Sorry. I'm sorry.

2389
01:28:03,745 --> 01:28:04,712
Unbelievable.

2390
01:28:04,779 --> 01:28:05,913
It's insane. It's so good.

2391
01:28:06,414 --> 01:28:08,249
VIEWER DISCRETION IS ADVISED FOR SANG-HWA

2392
01:28:08,516 --> 01:28:10,151
KANGNAM THE TROUBLEMAKER SEEMS SO EXCITED!

2393
01:28:13,321 --> 01:28:14,622
Thanks for the chili oil.

2394
01:28:14,689 --> 01:28:16,157
I'll teach you how to make <i>jjamppong</i>.

2395
01:28:27,235 --> 01:28:32,006
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn

